<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Profile of Treasury Secretary Rubin </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- For years it was a joke among Wall Street  
watchers: When Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin finally decided to 
leave, the stock market would take a dive. 
</P>
<P>
	The former Goldman, Sachs &AMP; Co. investment banker, a millionaire  
many times over, may have been mostly unknown to the public. 
</P>
<P>
	But to Wall Street traders, business leaders and even many  
Republicans, he was the linchpin -- with Federal Reserve Chairman 
Alan Greenspan -- who held together the Clinton administration 
policies that some credited with fostering the nation's economic 
boom. 
</P>
<P>
	``Everybody always believed that as long as he was secretary of  
the Treasury, nothing bad could happen,'' Clinton said Wednesday as 
he announced Rubin's departure. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dow Jones industrial average did indeed take an initial  
200-point drop when Rubin's resignation was announced. But at a 
time when the economy continues to boom, it quickly recovered, 
perhaps because Greenspan is still around or because most believe 
the administration's economic policies will not change. 
</P>
<P>
	Rubin, 60, who spent most of his life as a trader on Wall Street  
before joining the Clinton administration six years ago, gave the 
markets confidence because they knew he thought like them and had 
the president's ear -- whether his actual policies helped the boom 
or not. 
</P>
<P>
	But it was his close relationship with Greenspan that mattered  
most. They met each week for breakfast to hash over everything from 
the October 1997 stock market crash to the subsequent boom to the 
Asian economic crisis. 
</P>
<P>
	Rubin insisted that no one in the Clinton administration  
publicly should criticize Greenspan's actions at the Fed. And as 
the central bank pursued policies that led to low inflation, Wall 
Street cheered. 
</P>
<P>
	Even some Republicans were pleased. House Ways and Means  
Committee Chairman Bill Archer, R-Texas, praised Rubin for being 
``a strong and sometimes solitary voice within the Clinton 
administration for open markets and fiscal discipline.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Republicans did criticize Rubin over the 1995 government  
shutdown, and his handling of first the Mexican crisis and then the 
Asian one. 
</P>
<P>
	In an interview once, Rubin said the controversial Mexican  
bailout was ultimately praised for the wrong reason -- because it 
worked. Instead, it should have won praise because it was the 
rational economic decision to make, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Rubin also frustrated some fellow Democrats, especially when he  
helped steer Clinton toward deficit reduction early on, hoping it 
would lead to lower interest rates. 
</P>
<P>
	Rubin had long ``pined for private life,'' Clinton noted, and  
made no secret of the fact that he wished to return to New York 
City, where his wife continued living. He told reporters he had no 
immediate plans, although he is viewed as a possible candidate for 
the Fed chairmanship if Greenspan does not want a fourth term. 
</P>
<P>
	Rubin, who has two grown sons, became a retired partner at  
Goldman, Sachs during his government years and put his own fortune 
-- estimated at more than $100 million -- in a blind trust. He 
entered an arrangement where he could neither profit nor suffer 
from the firm's performance, Treasury officials say. 
</P>
<P>
	Last week, Goldman went public in the second-largest initial  
public offering in history, gaining $3.66 billion. Some senior and 
retired partners made millions, but Rubin missed out. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton joked Wednesday that Rubin came to Washington ``to help  
me save the middle class and he'd stayed so long that by the time 
he left, he'd be one of them.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The president, Rubin responded dryly, has always found that joke  
``a lot funnier than I have.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
