<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ill. Amtrak Deaths Ruled Accidental </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	KANKAKEE, Ill. (AP) -- The deaths of 11 people in the collision  
of an Amtrak train and a steel-laden truck were ruled an accident 
and not homicide Thursday by a coroner's inquest jury -- a decision 
that does not prevent prosecutors from bringing charges. 
</P>
<P>
	Amtrak's City of New Orleans slammed into the truck March 15 in  
Bourbonnais. Investigators have been looking into whether the truck 
driver tried to go around the crossing gates and beat the train. No 
one has been charged. 
</P>
<P>
	The coroner's inquest jury heard testimony Thursday from two  
Bourbonnais police officers and the town's fire chief and 
deliberated just 20 minutes. 
</P>
<P>
	John R. Stokes, the truck driver, attended the hearing but  
declined to testify, citing his Fifth Amendment right against 
self-incrimination. 
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutors are not bound by the findings of a coroner's jury,  
made up of six ordinary citizens who had been called for jury duty. 
</P>
<P>
	Stokes -- who was driving on a probationary permit because of  
previous traffic violations -- will lose his commercial driver's 
license June 1 for 60 days because of a ticket unrelated to the 
crash. 
</P>
<P>
	He has been ticketed at least seven times for moving violations  
since 1993. 
</P>
</TEXT>
