<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> London Museum Opening Mummy Exhibit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- The British Museum will open two galleries of  
ancient Egyptian burial artifacts Friday, containing newly 
researched mummies, coffins and other tomb finds from its vast 
collection. 
</P>
<P>
	The new displays will show burial practices over 3,000 years,  
from 2500 B.C. to the early centuries A.D. Exhibits will include 
models, toys and figures to give a better conception of the life of 
the period. 
</P>
<P>
	``The last major reorganization of (the mummies) was in 1898 and  
not much was done to them since then,'' said John Taylor, assistant 
keeper of Egyptian antiquities. 
</P>
<P>
	The mummies were added to the museum's collection in 1756, three  
years after its founding. But only recently, as technology 
advanced, have they been closely examined. 
</P>
<P>
	They were sent to London hospitals for scanning, producing X-ray  
type pictures of thin slices ranging from head to foot, without 
disturbing the wrappings. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have been able to discover ages, diseases, parasites,  
embalming methods and what's in the wrappings,'' Taylor said. 
</P>
<P>
	One mummy, never displayed before and one of the best-preserved,  
is of an anonymous woman, her skin a deep brown color and hair 
still on her head. 
</P>
<P>
	``She lived about 700 B.C., which we worked out from the very  
sophisticated and costly embalming method, so she must have been 
the wife of an important and wealthy man,'' Taylor said. 
</P>
<P>
	The British Museum's entire holdings include 80 human and more  
than 1,000 animal mummies, including cats, dogs, baboons, bulls, 
crocodiles, snakes and falcons. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Egyptians mummified almost everything that moved, as they  
were considered representative of gods or goddesses and so could be 
objects of devotion,'' Taylor said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
