<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Sarazen Was An Ambassador for Golf  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Gene Sarazen was 97 when death caught up with him Thursday  
morning in a hospital bed in Florida, so it's hard to argue he 
lived too little or left us even a moment too soon. 
</P>
<P>
	But that's not the same thing as saying the Squire won't be  
missed. A whole generation of kids, led by Tiger Woods and David 
Duval, may already have learned to play golf as skillfully as 
Sarazen did at a tender age. But there are still a few lessons they 
could learn about handling the fame and fortune that follows -- and 
few role models have held up as gracefully for as long as Sarazen 
did. 
</P>
<P>
	Like Joe DiMaggio, who preceded Sarazen in death by little more  
than two months, there was never a better ambassador for his game. 
And like DiMaggio, Sarazen was as humble as guys that good ever 
get. But he was hardly a square. 
</P>
<P>
	Mark O'Meara was playing at the Byron Nelson Classic just  
outside Dallas when he found out Sarazen died, and the first thing 
he remembered was a brief conversation they had last month at the 
Masters. 
</P>
<P>
	``He said, `My mind is going good, but everything else ... I  
can't play golf. I can't walk. It sucks to be 97.''' 
</P>
<P>
	And here O'Meara paused. For a moment, he worried the anecdote  
sounded disrespectful. And so O'Meara quickly added, ``That's 
exactly what he said.'' 
</P>
<P>
	No one would doubt it. Nobody liked a funny story more than the  
Squire. Sarazen sat graciously for interviews well into his 90s, 
but even after all those years, it was impossible to pin down the 
source of his modesty. That's because most of the time he was too 
busy lampooning his roots, his upbringing, or the threadbare state 
of golf when he became, at age 20, one of its brightest lights. 
</P>
<P>
	The first time he saw his name in the newspaper, after making a  
hole-in-one, he decided Eugenio Saraceni was a handle better suited 
for a violin player than a golfer. So he changed it. 
</P>
<P>
	The only time his father, an Italian immigrant carpenter, ever  
watched his son play, the freshly dubbed Gene Sarazen missed a 
40-foot putt. He recalled the old man asking him that night, `You 
mean to say they pay you fellows to play that game and you couldn't 
put that thing in the hole?''' 
</P>
<P>
	A pro's feet were more likely to swell than his head back then,  
Sarazen would point out, because a sponsor who plunked down $250 
expected the golfer to play in an exhibition during the day and 
turn up on the floor of a department store afterward to hawk some 
goods. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was,'' Sarazen said with some satisfaction, ``pretty tough  
in those days.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But even after the rewards changed and his life got easier,  
Sarazen never misplaced his sense of responsibility. The pride in 
his craft, in the way he carried himself, even in his clothes, 
remained unchanged to the end. 
</P>
<P>
	A few years ago, already into his 90s, Sarazen was having  
trouble hitting the golf ball and so he called then-Masters 
chairman Hord Hardin to say that he might not come out to the 
tournament. For nearly two decades, Sarazen hit a ball off the 
first tee in his ceremonial role as an official starter. 
</P>
<P>
	``Gene, people don't come out here to see you hit a golf ball,''  
Hardin told him. ``They come out to see if you're alive.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In 1993, Sarazen made a trip across the Atlantic to promote his  
role in designing a golf course and then stopped off at the British 
Open. It was being played that year at Royal St. George's, which 
was next door to the Prince's course, where Sarazen won his only 
British Open, among seven major titles, in 1932. 
</P>
<P>
	Sarazen's fame back in the States was assured by many things:  
his major titles, his famed double-eagle at the Masters and the 
invention of the sand wedge, among other things. But in Britain, 
lore had it that he had made eagle twice on a long and difficult 
par-4 at Prince's en route to winning the British. 
</P>
<P>
	When a writer preparing a book had sent Sarazen a letter asking  
about the tournament, Sarazen replied he could not remember the 
details, or even if the story were true. And so, during a windswept 
morning on his brief stay in England, he graciously agreed to be 
driven in a golf cart out to the hole to see if that would stir 
memories. 
</P>
<P>
	By the time they made it back to the clubhouse, the writer  
jumped out of the golf cart and headed toward some friends to share 
his story. An old friend of Sarazen's, meanwhile, sidled up to the 
cart and asked, ``So, did you or didn't you?'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sarazen was quiet for a moment, and then he smiled.  
</P>
<P>
	``Did,'' he said with a twinkle in his eye. ``At least, I hope  
so.'' 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	Jim Litke is a sports columnist for The Associated Press. Write  
to him at: jlitke@ap.org. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
