<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-13 05:45:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Gun Lobby Does Old-Fashioned Work </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Though on opposite sides of a fiery issue, Bob  
Walker and James Baker shared the same lookout near the Senate 
floor and the same mission -- stopping any legislative aide who 
scurried by to give their latest gun control pitches. 
</P>
<P>
	Baker, the chief lobbyist for the National Rifle Association,  
cajoled willing listeners with a plea not to insert gun control 
provisions in the juvenile crime bill as a knee-jerk reaction to 
the Colorado school shootings. 
</P>
<P>
	Walker, the head of Handgun Control Inc., grabbed his cellular  
phone any time he got a taker to order that the latest gun control 
literature be shipped immediately to that aide's office. 
</P>
<P>
	For both, there's no time to waste.  
</P>
<P>
	Lobbyists on both sides of the gun issue have had just three  
weeks to react since juvenile crime legislation now before the 
Senate was instantly transformed into a vehicle for gun control 
measures by the Littleton high school massacre. 
</P>
<P>
	So they're using the oldest form of influence peddling in the  
business -- walking the halls of the Capitol to make personal 
pitches. 
</P>
<P>
	While the lobbyists buttonholed lawmakers and aides, senators  
began debating the juvenile crime legislation, while Democrats 
tried to amend the bill to include new restrictions on guns. 
</P>
<P>
	In the first vote on gun control since the Littleton shooting on  
April 20, the Senate on Wednesday rejected fresh restrictions on 
sales at gun shows. Instead, lawmakers signaled support for 
voluntary background checks on private sales at gun shows. 
</P>
<P>
	Those who back stricter gun laws believe the Littleton shooting  
has given momentum to their efforts. ``It would have been much more 
difficult to bring these issues to the floor of the Senate without 
that tragedy,'' Handgun Control spokeswoman Naomi Paiss conceded. 
</P>
<P>
	Baker contended that the gun control forces were trying ``to  
build their legislative agenda based on tragedies.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The NRA finds itself in the unaccustomed position of being alone  
in opposition to some of the provisions being proposed for the 
juvenile crime bill. That's because the Colorado tragedy caused a 
split in the usually united pro-gun lobby. 
</P>
<P>
	The trade group that represents gun manufacturers, distributors  
and dealers has endorsed such measures as increasing the minimum 
age for buying a gun to 21 and banning violent juveniles from ever 
owning guns. 
</P>
<P>
	American Shooting Sports Council Executive Director Robert  
Ricker admitted getting some double takes when he tells lawmakers 
or their aides that he favors some restrictions on gun owners' 
rights. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have to re-examine our positions so we can concentrate on  
the areas where we can help prevent more tragedies,'' Ricker said. 
</P>
<P>
	Both Ricker and Baker said the two gun groups still agree 95  
percent of the time, just not on this issue. 
</P>
<P>
	The NRA, one of Washington's most potent lobbies, isn't  
conceding defeat. It has taken out full-page ads in major national 
newspapers, sent mailings to the states where senators are wavering 
and activated its grass-roots lobby. 
</P>
<P>
	``Because Bill Clinton and his anti-gun cronies in the Senate  
are trying to exploit the recent school shootings, we urgently need 
you to call your two U.S. senators immediately and urge them to 
oppose the Clinton gun control package,'' an NRA alert to members 
said, urging each member to also call five other supporters of gun 
owners' rights and encourage them to follow suit. The NRA also 
plans to send a letter later this month to all of its millions of 
members, urging them to call their senators and representatives. 
</P>
<P>
	Baker also previewed another argument the gun lobby is making  
all over Capitol Hill -- that lawmakers don't need new laws, they 
just need to enforce the current ones. 
</P>
<P>
	``If we're not going to enforce the laws we currently have, what  
sense does it make to pass another one?'' Baker asked. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, NRA supporters in Congress admit that emotions are  
running against them. 
</P>
<P>
	``Whenever there is a disaster, there are always people who will  
be more prone to pass something as a knee-jerk response than under 
normal circumstances,'' said Rep. Bob Barr, R-Ga. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1994, Democrats lost control of both houses of Congress after  
approving a waiting period for handgun purchases and a ban on 
certain assault-style weapons. 
</P>
<P>
	``Some of the most restrictive provisions of the crime bill were  
responsible for some Democratic members losing their seats and the 
Democrats losing control of the House,'' said Rep. Maurice Hinchey, 
D-N.Y. 
</P>
<P>
	But the dynamics may have changed since then, lawmakers said.  
Barr admits that the Democrats would have a year and a half before 
the next election for gun owners' passions to cool. 
</P>
<P>
	And Rep. Sherwood Boehlert, R-N.Y., said he believes the House  
would enact new restrictions on guns if they pass ``the 
common-sense reasonable test.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
