<DOCNO> APW19990513.0021 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-13 05:45:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Easy confirmation thought for Summers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Lawrence Summers may be a harried leap in  
style from the unflappable Treasury secretary he's been nominated 
to replace, but on matters of substance the two could be twins. 
That's expected to earn him an easy confirmation in the Senate. 
</P>
<P>
	Summers, 44, has served since 1995 as deputy to Treasury  
Secretary Robert Rubin, who announced his long-expected resignation 
Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	``The right course has been set, and the challenge is to carry  
on,'' Summers said. 
</P>
<P>
	Senators key to the confirmation process appear to largely agree  
-- if anyone in President Clinton's Cabinet has had a bipartisan fan 
club on Capitol Hill, it's been Rubin. 
</P>
<P>
	Even so, they are likely to grill Summers about the  
administration's support for recent international bailouts as well 
as domestic policies in which he has had a strong hand, such as 
President Clinton's proposed Social Security reforms. 
</P>
<P>
	Rubin, 60, who was co-chairman of the Wall Street firm Goldman  
Sachs &AMP; Co. before he joined the administration, said that beyond 
taking a fishing trip he has not yet decided what he will do next. 
</P>
<P>
	``I felt inside myself it was time to go back home,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	Rubin and Summers have worked together on Clinton's economic  
policies from the beginning. Little change is expected. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't see any reason for thinking policy will change one  
iota,'' said Lyle Gramley, former Federal Reserve governor. ``It is 
in the international arena where Treasury shines, and that is where 
Larry has been taking the lead for some time.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Even from administration critics, Summers and Rubin, along with  
Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan, have won praise for 
helping keep a global economic crisis from derailing the 
high-flying U.S. economy, now in its ninth year of uninterrupted 
growth, a record unmatched in peacetime. 
</P>
<P>
	Summers has proved an unlikely economic commando -- a rumpled,  
blustering former Harvard professor parachuting into financial 
trouble spots. 
</P>
<P>
	Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., said he saw no  
problems with the Senate nomination. Sen. William Roth, R-Del., 
chairman of the Senate Finance Committee, which must approve the 
nomination, said his panel had a ``good working relationship'' with 
Summers. 
</P>
<P>
	However, he may face some heat from senators who have been  
critical of the administration's support for the International 
Monetary Fund as it assembled more than $100 billion in emergency 
bailout packages during the recent global currency crisis that 
leveled economies in Asia, Russia and Latin America. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's a lot of questions he'll have to answer,'' said Senate  
Majority Whip Don Nickles, R-Okla., who noted Republicans have also 
found fault with Clinton's proposal for a Social Security overhaul 
this year, which Summers and Rubin helped formulate. 
</P>
<P>
	Rubin's departure had been rumored for more than a year, but he  
reluctantly stayed on, first to deal with the overseas financial 
crisis and then out of concern that he could not leave while 
Clinton was facing impeachment. 
</P>
<P>
	Although Rubin has groomed Summers for the job, the deputy's  
personal style couldn't be more different. 
</P>
<P>
	Rubin is suave and slim and wears impeccably tailored suits. The  
portly Summers, a full professor at Harvard University at the 
tender age of 28, sometimes gives the impression of a preoccupied 
academic who has trouble keeping his shirttail tucked in. 
</P>
<P>
	Rubin appears relaxed and amiable. Summers, who almost always  
works with an open can of Diet Coke at hand, is intense and seldom 
smiles. In his moment of triumph, he got a catch in his throat as 
he thanked his family in his remarks at the Rose Garden ceremony at 
which Clinton announced his nomination. 
</P>
<P>
	His blunt self-assurance can rub some members of Congress the  
wrong way. Rep. Mark Foley, R-Fla., recalled that Summers once 
described Republican efforts to eliminate estate taxes as 
``selfish,'' raising concerns about his ability to avoid making 
``ill-tempered, partisan remarks.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Still, even Summers' detractors acknowledge his ability to  
``think outside the box'' and ``add value'' to deliberations on 
almost any topic. 
</P>
<P>
	Summers grew up outside Philadelphia and hails from a family of  
distinguished economists. At Harvard, he was known for research 
into practical economic questions such as tax policy, joblessness 
and the stock market. In 1991, he left academia to become chief 
economist at the World Bank. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1993, he worked on Clinton's transition team and took the job  
of Treasury undersecretary for international affairs. He was 
promoted to deputy secretary after Rubin replaced Clinton's first 
Treasury secretary, former Texas Sen. Lloyd Bentsen, in 1995. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
