<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Gov. Wants NJ Teams Under One Roof </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEWARK, N.J. (AP) -- Gov. Christie Whitman says if the New Jersey  
Nets and New Jersey Devils are interested in state funding for a 
new basketball court and new hockey rink, the teams should put them 
under one roof. 
</P>
<P>
	That seems fine with the Nets, whose president said Wednesday  
the team's new owners are flexible and would ``move heaven and 
earth'' in their quest to have a new arena for both teams built in 
Newark. 
</P>
<P>
	Devils owner John J. McMullen, however, said he still wants to  
build a hockey-only arena in Hoboken. 
</P>
<P>
	As for the Nets, ``I wish them luck. I hope they get it. There's  
nothing wrong with having two arenas in the state,'' McMullen said 
Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	There is if you ask Whitman, who insisted ``everything we've  
seen to date says you have to have two teams in a facility. Put it 
another way: we can't sustain two different arenas in that part of 
the state.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``So somehow, there has to be some type of an agreement between  
Nets and Devils, it would seem, unless one or the other is going to 
move out of the state,'' Whitman said Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Whitman's remarks, her strongest on the topic, came a day after  
the Nets -- to no one's surprise -- advised officials they will move 
the basketball franchise from the state-run Meadowlands sports 
complex to downtown Newark. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, the New Jersey Sports and Exposition Authority, which  
operates the Meadowlands, wants to build a new arena for both the 
Nets and Devils at the East Rutherford complex. 
</P>
<P>
	Without offering specifics, the Nets told Whitman and the  
Meadowlands leadership in a letter delivered Tuesday that their 
Newark plan is a good deal for state taxpayers because it ``better 
enables the state to capitalize on existing investment.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The team did not release the letter, which was obtained  
Wednesday by The Associated Press. It was signed by one of the 
owners as well as the franchise's president, Michael Rowe. 
</P>
<P>
	Whitman reiterated that her goal is to keep the state's five  
professional teams in New Jersey. ``Where they stay in New Jersey 
is secondary to keeping them here,'' Whitman said. 
</P>
<P>
	All now play at Meadowlands venues: The football Giants and  
Jets, and the New York-New Jersey MetroStars of Major League Soccer 
in Giants Stadium; and the Nets and Devils at the Continental 
Airlines Arena. 
</P>
<P>
	The complex also include the Meadowlands Racetrack, a premier  
horse racing venue. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
