<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Financial News at 5:10 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Dow Closes at Record 11,107.19  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks were mostly higher today on reports  
showing moderate inflation. The Dow Jones industrial average and 
Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 hit new records. But weakness in some 
technology shares pulled the Nasdaq Stock Market lower. The Dow 
Jones industrial average closed up 106.82 at 11,107.19, breezing 
past its previous closing record of 11,031.59 posted last Friday. 
The Dow is up more than 21 percent so far this year. IBM led the 
Dow higher after Merrill Lynch raised its prediction for how much 
the stock would rise over the next 12 months. That came after an 
analyst meeting yesterday during which chairman Louis Gerstner said 
Internet would play a large part in the company's future, and that 
a quarter of IBM's 1998 revenues came from electronic commerce. IBM 
stock soared 19 1/2 to a record 245, accounting for more than 89 
points on the Dow. The Nasdaq Composite Index was at 2,582.00, down 
24.54. 

</P>
<P>
	Financial Figures  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Financial figures at Thursday's close:  
Dow Industrials:        11,107.19 + 106.82
NYSE Issues:         Advances 1807  Declines 1193  Unchgd  564
NYSE Volume:         769,638,420
Most Active NYSE issue:        America Online133 1/8   - 5 5/16
S&AMP;P 500:         1367.56  + 3.56
AMEX Mkt Value Index:          800.39  + 2.04
Nasdaq Composite Index        2,582.00 - 24.54
Gold(final) -    $277.40    troy oz., NY Comex spot month Thu.
Silver(final) -   UNCH    troy oz., NY Comex spot month Wed.

</P>
<P>
	Producer Prices Rise 0.5 Percent  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Most prices charged by factories, farmers and  
other producers remained tame in April, but soaring energy prices -- 
including a record jump for gasoline -- may be starting to affect 
consumers. The government's Producer Price Index for finished goods 
rose 0.5 percent in April, the Labor Department said today. That 
followed a smaller 0.2 percent increase in March and brought the 
annual rate of inflation in prices wholesalers pay to 1.1 percent 
so far in 1999, compared with a 0.1 percent decline for all of 
1998. The April rise was largely due to a 5.1 percent jump in 
energy prices -- the largest in nearly nine years -- which economists 
had expected. 

</P>
<P>
	American Air Faces Antitrust Charge  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Justice Department charged today that  
American Airlines, the nation's second-largest air carrier, 
monopolized airline passenger service to and from Dallas-Fort Worth 
International Airport. American was charged in a lawsuit with 
repeatedly trying to drive small, startup airlines out of the DFW 
airport, the nation's third largest, by saturating their routes 
with its own flights and cutting fares. The lawsuit was filed in 
U.S. District Court in Wichita, Kan. Although this is the first 
predatory-practices case brought since airlines were deregulated in 
1978, other airlines and their tactics at other hub airports are 
being investigated by the department's antitrust division. American 
called the allegations unwarranted and said they go against the 
very essence of free-market competition. AMR shares were at 74, 
down 3/16. 

</P>
<P>
	Dell, Micron Settle FTC Charges  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Two of the nation's largest computer makers  
settled government charges they misled consumers with Internet 
advertisements to lease new computers with low monthly payments, 
federal regulators said today. Dell Computer Corp. and Micron 
Electronics Inc. both agreed to provide consumers with ``clear, 
readable and understandable information in their lease 
advertising,'' the Federal Trade Commission said. The FTC said ads 
from Dell and Micron included important cost information in 
inconspicuous or unreadable fine print, or they omitted the 
information. The FTC settlement, approved 4-0 by the commission, 
becomes final after a 60-day public comment period. Dell shares 
were at 43 1/4, down 11/16. Micron shares were at 10 7/8, down 3/16. 

</P>
<P>
	SEC Targets Online Investment Fraud  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- In a bid to bolster its ability to fight  
online fraud, the Securities and Exchange Commission has turned to 
Congress for help, asking for an increase in its budget and greater 
leeway in the kind of enforcement actions it can take. Even if it 
gets the help it is seeking, however, the SEC's crime-fighting 
powers will continue to be hampered in several ways, including the 
fact that it can only file civil lawsuits against suspected 
violators. There are other limits: The SEC can bar brokers who have 
violated the law from the brokerage industry, but not from other 
financial activities such as promoting stocks. And it it lacks 
authority to shut Web sites. 

</P>
<P>
	Radio Shack: RCA Video Products Only  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Tandy Corp. has chosen Thomson Consumer  
Electronics' RCA line to be the exclusive brand of audio and video 
products sold at its Radio Shack stores, the companies announced 
today. Tandy will phase out its house brands of electronics -- known 
under the Optimus and Realistic names -- in the next year and 
replace them entirely with RCA goods. 

</P>
<P>
	Brown &AMP; Williamson Wins Court Case  
</P>
<P>
	KANSAS CITY, Mo. (AP) -- A federal jury handed the tobacco  
industry its second victory in four days today, deciding Brown &AMP; 
Williamson Tobacco Corp. was not at fault in the case of a man who 
died of lung cancer in 1995 after smoking Kools. Charles Steele's 
family had sued for $26 million, claiming the nation's 
third-largest tobacco company sold him an unreasonably dangerous 
product. Jury foreman Gary White said Steele ``was quite aware of 
the dangers, but the pleasures outweighed the dangers.'' On Monday, 
a jury in Memphis, Tenn., cleared B&AMP;W and two other tobacco 
companies of liability in the deaths of three smokers. 

</P>
<P>
	Lands' End Profits Increase  
</P>
<P>
	DODGEVILLE, Wis. (AP) -- Catalog and Internet retailer Lands' End  
reported a 6 percent gain in first-quarter earnings from a year 
ago, boosted by strong sales from the liquidation of its Willis &AMP; 
Geiger outdoor-clothing catalog. Lands' End earnings from 
continuing operations were $5.7 million, or 18 cents a share, for 
the quarter ended April 30, compared with $5.2 million, or 17 cents 
a share, in the same period a year ago. Land's End shares were at 
42 1/2, up 3 13/16. 

</P>
<P>
	Gap Earnings Up More Than 50 Pct.  
</P>
<P>
	SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- Gap Inc.'s first-quarter earnings climbed  
by more than 50 percent from a year ago, fueled by strong results 
at its Old Navy stores. The San Francisco-based retailer earned 
$202 million, or 34 cents a share, in the quarter ended May 1, 
compared with $136 million, or 22 cents a share, a year ago. Sales 
were $2.28 billion, up from $1.72 billion a year ago. Sales at 
stores open at least a year rose 11 percent, slowing from the 
previous year's 17 percent increase. Gap shares were at 62 1/16, 
down 3/16. 

</P>
<P>
	Nortel To Cut 1,000 Jobs  
</P>
<P>
	TORONTO (AP) -- Nortel Networks, Canada's largest  
telecommunications company, is selling plants and cutting 1,000 
jobs as part of a restructuring plan intended to make the company 
more competitive. The job cuts and other measures announced today 
are part of a retrenchment program originally revealed in January. 
Starting this year, Nortel will contract out all but its most 
complex printed circuit board assembly, most of its 
electro-mechanical subsystems manufacturing and a significant part 
of its repair business. 

</P>
<P>
	Economic Numbers  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Economic numbers:  
</P>
<P>
	Producer prices: up 0.5 percent  
</P>
<P>
	Retail sales: up 0.1 percent  
</P>
<P>
	Jobless claims: unchanged at 303,000  
</P>
<P>
	Tomorrow: Consumer prices  
</P>
<P>
	Tomorrow: Business inventories  
</P>
<P>
	Tomorrow: Industrial production  

</P>
