<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Money Wirers Settle Overcharge Case </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- MoneyGram and Western Union have agreed to  
provide discounts and pay a total of $2.3 million to settle claims 
the companies charged exorbitant fees to wire money from the United 
States to Mexico. 
</P>
<P>
	The settlement announced Wednesday by Western Union parent First  
Data Corp. and MoneyGram Payment Systems Inc. would end lawsuits 
filed in California, Illinois and Texas by predominately poor 
Hispanics who relied on the services to send money to family and 
friends. 
</P>
<P>
	More than $4 billion a year is sent to Mexico, and most who wire  
money use MoneyGram and Western Union. The companies were accused 
of using currency exchange rates far exceeding the prevailing daily 
rates without informing customers. 
</P>
<P>
	The companies admitted no liability but promised to offer  
discount coupons to customers who had wired money to Mexico since 
1987. The companies also announced plans to donate $2.3 million to 
Hispanic organizations in the United States and agreed to disclose 
currency exchange rates on company forms and in advertising. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. District Court for the Northern District of Illinois  
gave preliminary approval to the deal. 
</P>
<P>
	California attorney Fred Kumetz, who has filed separate  
class-action lawsuits against the companies in state court, called 
the settlement a ``sweetheart deal'' and said he would fight it. 
</P>
<P>
	``I have a problem when a Chicago court ... imposes its will on  
a California lawsuit when California has eight times as many 
affected people and its own set of laws.'' 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
