<HEADLINE> Japanese Stock Prices Close Lower / Japanese Stocks  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Japanese stock prices closed lower today as market  
sentiment was hurt by U.S. Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin's 
announcement that he will resign. The dollar rose against the yen. 
</P>
<P>
	The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average lost 96.11 points,  
or 0.57 percent, ending the day at 16,851.25. On Wednesday, the 
average rose 204.18 points, or 1.22 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar bought 121.58 yen in late afternoon trading, up 0.72  
yen from late Wednesday in Tokyo and also higher than its late New 
York level of 120.95 yen overnight. The currency ranged from 120.87 
yen to 121.70 yen. 
</P>
<P>
	Stock market confidence was weighed down following U.S. Treasury  
Secretary Rubin's decision Wednesday to step down, traders said. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. President Bill Clinton said he would nominate Deputy  
Treasury Secretary Lawrence Summers to succeed Rubin. 
</P>
<P>
	The market also reacted negatively to reports Russian President  
Boris Yeltsin had dismissed the country's prime minister, Yevgeny 
Primakov, traders said. In addition, many players sat on the 
sidelines amid expectations for poor corporate earnings reports, 
they said. 
</P>
<P>
	Most Japanese companies will release profit results later this  
month for the fiscal year ended in March. 
</P>
<P>
	But today's declines were limited. Japanese officials reacted  
quickly to word of Rubin's departure, downplaying the possible 
impact on financial markets. 
</P>
<P>
	Finance Minister Kiichi Miyazawa said, ``I don't expect U.S.  
policy to change.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the  
first section fell 9.18 points, or 0.67 percent, to 1,351.97. The 
TOPIX closed up 5.33 points, or 0.39 percent, the day before. 
</P>
<P>
	Volume on the first section was estimated at 579.44 million  
shares, down from 648.77 million shares Wednesday. Retreating 
issues outnumbered advancers 812 to 394, with 110 others closing 
unchanged. 
</P>
<P>
	In currency dealings, the dollar was stable against the yen  
after gaining ground on dollar-buying prompted by a belief that 
Rubin's successor may maintain a strong dollar policy. 
</P>
<P>
	In other currencies, the euro bought 129.36 yen in midafternoon  
trading, up from 129.15 yen late Wednesday in Tokyo. 
</P>
<P>
	The yield on the benchmark No. 212 10-year Japanese government  
bond fell to 1.275 percent from Wednesday's finish of 1.340 
percent, driving its price up to 102.01 yen from 101.42 yen. 
</P>
</TEXT>
