<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Tour Boat Mechanic Testifies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HOT SPRINGS, Ark. (AP) -- A mechanic testified Thursday that he  
replaced a seal on an amphibious tour boat about two hours before 
it sank in about a minute, drowning 13 tourists. 
</P>
<P>
	Mike Oliver, a mechanic for Land and Lake Tours Inc., said he  
worked on the drive shaft seal April 30 and May 1. The boat, the 
Miss Majestic, sank shortly after taking on water May 1. 
</P>
<P>
	Oliver's statement came before a U.S. Coast Guard Marine Safety  
Board, which is investigating the sinking. 
</P>
<P>
	Oliver said he was not rushed and that there were two other  
boats available in case his work had not been completed. He was 
confident the seal was replaced properly. 
</P>
<P>
	The boat's operator testified this week that the boat's bilge  
pump kicked on two days before the fatal accident and that she took 
the vessel in for repairs. The National Transportation Safety Board 
said last week that the problem indicated a hole in the drive shaft 
seal. 
</P>
<P>
	Oliver said the seal was tight, but acknowledged under  
questioning that it might have been misaligned. When the boat was 
pulled from the water Sunday, there was a rip in an accordion-like 
seal at one end of the drive shaft cover. 
</P>
<P>
	Oliver said Elizabeth Helmbrecht, the boat's operator, gave the  
vessel a visual inspection before selecting it to take 20 tourists 
on a tour of Hot Springs and Lake Hamilton. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Helmbrecht and seven passengers survived the accident.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
