<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-13 20:11:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Highlights of Kosovo Spending Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Highlights of a roughly $15 billion measure to pay for U.S. air  
attacks on Yugoslavia and other programs that House-Senate 
bargainers agreed to Thursday: 
</P>
<P>
	--Defense: $11.8 billion for the Yugoslavia attacks, caring for  
refugees and other military programs. This includes $6 billion 
requested by President Clinton, plus $2.5 billion for operations 
and maintenance of equipment, $1.8 billion for a military pay raise 
and $919 million for refugees and the Balkan countries to which 
they have fled. 
</P>
<P>
	--U.S. farmers: $566 million to help corn, hog and other  
commodities producers cope with plummeting prices. 
</P>
<P>
	--Central America: Nearly $1 billion to help recover from natural  
disasters, mostly to aid Honduras, Nicaragua, El Salvador and Costa 
Rice in rebuilding from last October's Hurricane Mitch. 
</P>
<P>
	--U.S. disasters: $900 million for the tornadoes in Oklahoma and  
other states and to rebuild coffers of the Federal Emergency 
Management Agency. 
</P>
<P>
	--Jordan: $100 million to aid.  
</P>
<P>
	--Tobacco: Federal government cannot get any of $246 billion  
tobacco companies owe states under a legal settlement. 
</P>
<P>
	--Japanese interns: $4.3 million to pay some Japanese living in  
South America who were forced into U.S. internment camps during 
World War II. 
</P>
<P>
	--Mines: Stricter Interior Department cleanup rules for mining  
companies using federal lands delayed through Sept. 30. Effort to 
block Interior Department from limiting number of mill sites used 
by hard-rock mining companies on public lands limited to Crown 
Jewel mine in Washington state plus other companies that have 
already applied for permits. 
</P>
<P>
	--Oil, gas royalties: Higher royalties owed by oil and gas  
companies using public lands delayed. 
</P>
<P>
	--Alaska: Phase out of fishing in Glacier Bay National Park would  
continue, $26 million to buy out fishermen and others. 
</P>
<P>
	--Dropped from final agreement: Provisions aimed at providing  
reparations to families of victims of Marine plane that destroyed 
an Italian ski gondola; reducing refunds owed by some Kansas 
natural gas producers; guaranteed loan programs for steel, oil, gas 
companies; 
</P>
<P>
	--Financing: The bill would be paid for almost completely from  
the federal surplus. About $1.6 billion would be paid for by 
cutting domestic programs, mostly unused food stamps and public 
housing funds and foreign aid. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
