<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-13 06:36:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> SEC Targets Internet Fraud </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Federal regulators have charged 18 people and  
eight companies with using the Internet to sell bogus securities, 
extending their crackdown on investment fraud in cyberspace. 
</P>
<P>
	It was the Securities and Exchange Commission's third nationwide  
``sweep'' against online investment scams, which have cost ordinary 
investors millions of dollars in recent years. The agency announced 
the action Wednesday, alleging that 14 separate schemes deceived 
investors in this country and around the world. 
</P>
<P>
	All told, the investors lost around $2.25 million, the SEC said.  
</P>
<P>
	The allegedly fraudulent investments included interests in gold  
mines, computer software, prefabricated hospitals in Turkey and a 
product described as a new way of processing gold. Eight of the 
cases involved the sale of so-called ``prime bank'' notes -- 
nonexistent securities promoted as providing guaranteed high rates 
of return. The names of well known U.S. or foreign banks are 
sometimes fraudulently added to the securities' names to bolster 
credibility. 
</P>
<P>
	The market watchdog agency made the allegations in eight civil  
lawsuits and six administrative actions. All 14 cases involved 
people allegedly selling or marketing phony securities using the 
World Wide Web and making ``outrageous'' promises to investors, 
such as annual returns exceeding 100 percent or even 2000 percent 
of an initial investment. 
</P>
<P>
	The SEC also charged several individuals with acting as  
unregistered brokers and selling unregistered securities. 
</P>
<P>
	In some of the cases, the agency said its 200-member Internet  
surveillance team discovered the questionable offerings before any 
securities were sold, preventing any potential investors from 
losing money. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is in many respects a pre-emptive strike,'' SEC  
Enforcement Director Richard Walker told reporters. 
</P>
<P>
	In other cases, however, it was too late.  
</P>
<P>
	In one scam, a Dutch man, an Indiana man and a Missouri woman  
allegedly bilked thousands of people out of at least $1.25 million 
in seven schemes that promised investors risk-free returns of up to 
400 percent a month. 
</P>
<P>
	Nancy Smith, director of the SEC's Office of Investor Education  
and Assistance, said, ``People spend more time choosing a computer 
than they spend researching Internet investments. Investors can 
take their own pre-emptive strikes against Internet fraud simply by 
checking out investments before they buy.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The SEC was seeking civil fines and court orders against the  
investment promoters and companies, compelling them to refrain from 
the allegedly fraudulent activity. In two of the cases, federal 
judges have granted temporary restraining orders against the 
promoters and companies. One of the cases was settled, with the 
person charged neither admitting nor denying wrongdoing. 
</P>
<P>
	The actions were seemingly mild, but the regulators' options are  
limited. They do not have legal authority to shut down investment 
promoters' Web sites, for example. 
</P>
<P>
	The civil enforcement actions were brought by SEC's headquarters  
in Washington and by its offices in Atlanta; Boston; Denver; Fort 
Worth, Texas; New York; Philadelphia and San Francisco. 
</P>
<P>
	The actions were the latest moves in a nationwide crackdown  
against investment fraud in cyberspace started by the SEC last 
October. In ``sweeps'' in October and February, the agency targeted 
people promoting legitimate stocks over the Internet who don't 
disclose they are paid to do so by the companies. Such stock 
promotions are known as ``touting.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sen. Judd Gregg, R-N.H., chairman of a Senate Appropriations  
subcommittee, recently proposed increasing the SEC's budget, now at 
$337.4 million, by $5.5 million next year to fight investment fraud 
over the Internet. That would bring the agency's funding to the 
level requested by the Clinton administration. 
</P>
<P>
	``The cops won't catch every crook in cyberspace, so investors  
need to watch out for themselves,'' said Peter Hildreth, president 
of the North American Securities Administrators Association, which 
represents state securities regulators. 
</P>
<P>
	``Regulators will not allow con artists and charlatans to hijack  
... (the Internet) and turn it into the electronic equivalent of a 
restroom wall,'' he added. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	EDITOR'S NOTE: The SEC advises investors to read its guide  
titled ``Internet Fraud: How to Avoid Internet Investment Scams'' 
before buying any investment promoted on the Internet. The 
publication is available on the investor assistance and complaints 
link of the agency's Web site at http://www.sec.gov. It also is available 
by calling 1-800-SEC-0330. 
</P>
<P>
	Investors also are urged to report suspicious investment  
offerings to enforcement@sec.gov or to use the Enforcement 
Complaint Center at http://www.sec.gov/enforce/comctr.htm. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
