<DOCNO> APW19990513.0041 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-13 15:42:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Kosovo Bill Nears Completion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- House-Senate bargainers moved toward a  
compromise Thursday on a package financing the bombardment of 
Yugoslavia, aid to Central America and other programs after dealing 
a setback to Sen. Robert Byrd's loan program for ailing steel 
companies. 
</P>
<P>
	Negotiators from the two chambers were hoping to shake hands on  
a deal, then speed it through Congress and send it to President 
Clinton for his signature Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	The legislation contains $11.7 billion for the air campaign in  
the Balkans, the Kosovo's refugees and a general military buildup -- 
twice Clinton's spending request -- plus other items that have 
driven the total price tag toward $15 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton expressed optimism that progress was being made, despite  
White House veto threats over the amount of defense spending, 
planned domestic cuts, and other provisions. 
</P>
<P>
	``There is some effort to trim down the bill some and get it in  
a position where I can sign it, and I hope it will be done 
quickly,'' Clinton said. 
</P>
<P>
	The measure also contains nearly $1 billion to help Central  
American countries rebuild from last fall's Hurricane Mitch, plus 
$566 million to aid U.S. farmers harmed by low commodities prices. 
</P>
<P>
	Under pressure from House Speaker Dennis Hastert, R-Ill., two  
House Republicans reversed themselves Thursday, as House 
negotiators voted 12-11 to reject the steel language by Byrd, 
D-W.Va. The provision was one of the few unresolved matters. 
</P>
<P>
	Byrd's proposal faced an uncertain fate when the House and  
Senate consider the compromise, overall bill. 
</P>
<P>
	The House bargainers had voted 13-10 early Thursday to accept  
the steel provision, infuriating conservatives by adding to the 
bill's cost and jeopardizing passage of the overall measure. 
</P>
<P>
	After meeting with Hastert, Reps. Ralph Regula, R-Ohio, and Joe  
Skeen, R-N.M., switched and voted against Byrd when the issue was 
reconsidered in the afternoon. 
</P>
<P>
	``We had some discussions,'' Regula said of his meeting with  
Hastert. ``That's his role as leader, which is perfectly 
appropriate.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The provision, approved last month by the Senate, would provide  
$140 million to back $1 billion in loan guarantees for 
moderate-sized steel companies hurt by imports. Among them would be 
the Weirton Steel Corp. of Weirton, W.Va., which would be another 
victory for the 81-year-old Byrd, considered the Senate's 
craftiest, fiercest champion of home-state projects. 
</P>
<P>
	Byrd was promised that a steel loan program would be voted on  
separately by the House. But that did not satisfy him because while 
the Kosovo measure is certain to reach Clinton's desk, a separate 
measure might never get there. 
</P>
<P>
	``What I see here is a steamroller,'' he said of the vote  
against him, adding that he would keep fighting for his provision. 
</P>
<P>
	Also promising to continue battling was Sen. Pete Domenici,  
R-N.M., who saw his Senate-approved $500 million loan program for 
oil and gas companies rejected by House bargainers early Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Byrd, a 40-year Senate veteran, also faced pressure from Senate  
Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss. Lott said he would keep the 
bill from the Senate floor until the steel provision was gone and 
the bill slimmed down. 
</P>
<P>
	``Hard-headedness and caginess don't get you much if you don't  
have a bill to deal with,'' Lott said of Byrd. ``This bill is too 
big, too many riders. Back off.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Remaining in the bill was a Senate-approved provision providing  
up to $4.3 million to pay reparations for Japanese people interned 
during World War II, including some from Latin America who were 
placed in U.S. detention camps. 
</P>
<P>
	Leaders were considering reducing the $900 million the  
compromise would provide added funding for the Federal Emergency 
Management Agency following the tornadoes that hit Oklahoma and 
other states. 
</P>
<P>
	Most of the package was to be paid for from this year's expected  
$111 billion federal surplus. But Republicans were insisting on 
paying for about $1.6 billion of it by cutting domestic programs, 
mostly money for food stamps that they said was not going to be 
spent. Public housing and foreign aid would also be reduced. 
</P>
<P>
	Lott and Sen. Kay Bailey Hutchison, R-Texas, said they were near  
a deal aimed at easing Clinton's objections to a provision 
forbidding the federal government from taking any of the $246 
billion states have won in a pact with the tobacco industry. 
</P>
<P>
	They said the bill would say the states should -- but not must --  
use portions of the money for anti-smoking and health programs, 
which is how the administration wants the money used. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990513.0042 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-13 13:45:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Flu Season Was Deadlier Than Usual </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- The U.S. flu season was apparently deadlier than  
usual this year, the government reported Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	The flu season runs from October through mid-May. The Centers  
for Disease Control and Prevention does not know yet how many 
people died this season from the flu. 
</P>
<P>
	However, in an average flu season, there are about 20,000  
deaths, and about 30,000 when the Type A-H3N2 virus hits -- as it 
did this year, the CDC said. 
</P>
<P>
	The deadliest flu season in the past decade was 1989-90, when  
about 44,000 people died. 
</P>
<P>
	This year, the flu season got off to a slow start, with few  
cases until mid-January. By February, the flu was widespread in 40 
states. The outbreaks had tapered off by mid-April. 
</P>
<P>
	The strain most prevalent was Type A Sydney.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990513.0043 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-13 16:11:56 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  U.S. Campaign Tactics Helping Barak </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TEL AVIV, Israel (AP) -- James Carville is exhausted but  
optimistic. 
</P>
<P>
	His candidate, Ehud Barak, is ahead by 10 points and looks like  
a winner. Five months ago, the U.S. campaign strategist couldn't 
find anyone who thought the sincere, but uncharismatic Labor Party 
leader had a chance to defeat Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu. 
</P>
<P>
	Kicking his feet up onto a coffee table and leaning back in a  
lounge chair, the Louisiana native who helped get President Clinton 
elected smiles with satisfaction at the suggestion that American 
campaign techniques -- simple slogans, endless repetition, 
up-to-the-minute polling of voter whims -- travel well. 
</P>
<P>
	As Israel's '99 campaign heads into its final weekend before  
Monday's vote, American money and methods are reshaping Israeli 
politics. 
</P>
<P>
	Even Natan Sharansky, a former Soviet dissident who heads a  
Russian immigrants party, has an American pollster. 
</P>
<P>
	Netanyahu, whose reputation as a media king has been shaken in  
this contest, also has an American adviser -- strategist Arthur 
Finkelstein, who has helped Republican politicians get elected. 
</P>
<P>
	During Netanyahu's 1996 campaign, Finkelstein peppered campaign  
ads with shocking images of terror attacks and painted Palestinian 
leader Yasser Arafat as the main beneficiary of the peace process 
in order to portray Netanyahu as tougher than Labor on security. 
</P>
<P>
	That assault crippled the opposition.  
</P>
<P>
	Three years later, Labor went American, hiring Carville,  
Washington pollster Stanley Greenberg and media specialist Robert 
Shrum. 
</P>
<P>
	``It took the loss of the 1996 election for (Labor) to  
understand they needed to change their way of thinking,'' Carville 
said in an interview with The Associated Press. 
</P>
<P>
	He has so successfully introduced his famous one-liner from the  
1992 Clinton campaign -- ``It's the economy, stupid'' -- that 
security, once the No. 1 issue in Israel, has virtually vanished 
from discourse. 
</P>
<P>
	Carville has turned Barak's image from that of a slow-talking,  
TV turnoff into a leader tough on everything from peace to 
unemployment. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's amazing, the turnaround in five months,'' Carville said.  
``When I came here on the 14th of December, I couldn't find anybody 
who thought Barak had a chance.'' 
</P>
<P>
	At the same time, Netanyahu has suffered an erosion of support  
from among some of his Likud Party's key constituents, especially 
ex-Soviet Jews and Jews of Middle Eastern origin disgruntled over 
rising unemployment, recession and the faltering peace process. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite their successes, the American strategists have often  
found themselves in unfamiliar territory. ``It's hard for an 
outsider to understand how intense it is here and how quickly 
things happen,'' Carville said. 
</P>
<P>
	For Ron Dermer, a pollster from Miami Beach who runs the  
campaign for Sharansky's Israel B'Aliya, language is a barrier. 
</P>
<P>
	``You have to learn certain things and get used to translators  
for everything,'' he said, noting that all his polls are composed 
in English, conducted in Russian, the primary language of many of 
Sharansky supporters, and then translated back into English so he 
can analyze the results. 
</P>
<P>
	``But I think we bring a different approach to the elections  
here, and Israel seems ready for that,'' Dermer said. 
</P>
<P>
	Not everyone agrees.  
</P>
<P>
	Shmuel Sandler, a political scientist at Bar-Ilan University,  
said the outsiders shouldn't interfere. 
</P>
<P>
	``You have to go with your gut and understand your nation. For a  
foreigner that's hard. He can give advice on television but not on 
how our lives should be,'' Sandler said. 
</P>
<P>
	Israel's campaigns have been gradually transformed in the past  
decade, with the arrival of commercial TV. Candidates have mastered 
the 10-second soundbite and are comfortable with makeup. 
</P>
<P>
	With the arrival of the high-priced American talent, party  
activists have gradually found their roles diminished in the 
campaign. 
</P>
<P>
	The candidates, meanwhile, have learned to make the rounds at  
the homes of wealthy U.S. Jews in search of financing. Netanyahu, 
Barak and Centrist Party candidate Yitzhak Mordechai have all gone 
on U.S. fund-raising trips. 
</P>
<P>
	Under Israeli law, it's illegal to accept contributions from  
foreigners. But that hasn't stopped the money from rolling in from 
Hollywood, New York and Miami. 
</P>
<P>
	``There is ample evidence that wealthy American Jews circumvent  
election laws by funneling money to organizations which benefit 
candidates running for prime minister,'' said David Makovsky, an 
Israeli journalist who investigated campaign financing. 
</P>
<P>
	American Jews have been at odds over whether they should be  
involved in Israeli politics. 
</P>
<P>
	The American Jewish Congress, a U.S. lobbying group, opposes the  
idea. Members of the Reform and Conservative Judaism movements have 
urged their members to support candidates who will advance the 
rights of liberal Judaism in Israel. 
</P>
<P>
	Thousands of Israeli expatriates living in the United States are  
flying home for Monday's vote and an estimated 75,000 American 
immigrants living in Israel have the right to vote. 
</P>
<P>
	The Clinton administration, meanwhile, has been deafeningly  
silent, in contrast to its warm embrace of Labor's Shimon Peres in 
1996. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think they realized after 1996 what a boomerang effect this  
could have. Israelis don't like to see foreigners taking sides,'' 
Sandler said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990513.0044 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-13 16:11:56 </DATE_TIME>
