<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dishman Joins the Chiefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	KANSAS CITY, Mo. (AP) -- Vowing to prove he's still one of the  
NFL's top defensive backs, Cris Dishman has joined the Kansas City 
Chiefs, a team badly in need of a cornerback. 
</P>
<P>
	The 33-year-old former Pro Bowler signed a three-year deal and  
will replace former Pro Bowl cornerback Dale Carter, who signed a 
free agent deal with Denver. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've got something to prove,'' Dishman said. ``I'm going to  
show everybody I'm the same player I was two years ago and before 
that. The Chiefs were 13-3 two years ago and slipped a little (7-9) 
last year. I think they can get back to where they were.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Washington Redskins released Dishman last month, partly to  
save on his $2.7 million salary and partly because he had the worst 
season of his 11-year career. 
</P>
<P>
	But Dishman impressed the Chiefs with a strong workout. He made  
the Pro Bowl as recently as 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	``Cris Dishman is the veteran cornerback that completes our  
search in the free agency market,'' Chiefs president Carl Peterson 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	If Dishman becomes the Chiefs' other starting corner, they will  
have plenty of experience at that position. The other starter, 
James Hasty, also is 33. Dishman will compete with Carlton Gray for 
the starting job. 
</P>
<P>
	``With our returning cornerbacks, plus Carlton Gray and now Cris  
Dishman, I feel very good about this very important position on our 
team,'' Peterson said. ``We have a good combination of youth and 
experience.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Dishman spent nine seasons with the Oilers and two with the  
Redskins, making 140 starts in 172 career regular-season games. He 
has 37 interceptions and 17 forced fumbles. 
</P>
<P>
	He worked out with a personal trainer in San Diego for 1 1/2 months  
earlier this year in order to get into peak physical shape, and 
said he would go back in June to finish the program. 
</P>
<P>
	``Teams are going to test me because they think I've lost it,''  
Dishman said. ``I'll have to show a lot of people I haven't lost 
it.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
