<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Judge Upholds Union Dues Decision </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A federal judge has reaffirmed his October  
decision that the Communications Workers of America failed to 
inform about 50,000 affiliated workers that they didn't have to pay 
full dues. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. District Judge Royce Lamberth on Thursday stuck with the  
ruling that awarded nominal damages to workers who pay a fee to the 
union for collective bargaining representation but don't become 
full union members. 
</P>
<P>
	The union had appealed the decision in the class-action suit,  
which was sponsored by the National Right to Work Foundation. 
</P>
<P>
	Any of those workers who now say they didn't want to pay for  
work the union did outside of collective bargaining -- such as 
political advocacy -- between 1987 and 1995 can request 
reimbursement for a portion of their dues. 
</P>
<P>
	In his October ruling, Lamberth said the violation was a  
technical matter, not intentional wrongdoing. Nevertheless, he 
ordered the union to pay $1 to each worker in the class and granted 
workers who were paying the union the fees the right to object to 
such expenditures retroactively. 
</P>
<P>
	The union estimates that the ruling will only affect about  
20,000 members. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
