<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Latin American Briefs /  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PUESTO CAHUIDE, Peru (AP) -- The presidents of Peru and Ecuador  
met Thursday at a remote jungle camp to formally put into effect a 
peace treaty that ended their long-standing border dispute. 
</P>
<P>
	In a ceremony at the border juncture of the Yaupi and Santiago  
rivers, Peruvian President Alberto Fujimori and Ecuadorean 
President Jamil Mahuad signed an act sealing the frontier. 
</P>
<P>
	The ceremony at the border post Puesto Cahuide, 680 miles north  
of the Peruvian capital, Lima, was the culmination of an October 
treaty that ended a dispute between the Andean neighbors that 
erupted into wars in 1941, 1985 and 1995. 
</P>
<P>
	A 1942 treaty signed by the nations left 49 miles of the border  
undefined, leading to frequent clashes. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	SAO PAULO, Brazil (AP) -- A Brazilian real estate developer is  
planning to build the world's tallest building in South America's 
biggest city, local media reported Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Brasilinvest said it had established a joint venture with the  
Maharishi Global Development Fund of the Netherlands to build 
1,630-foot, 103-story building called the Sao Paulo Tower. 
</P>
<P>
	The $1.65 billion building would be 139 feet taller than the  
Petronas twin towers in Kuala Lumpur, Malaysia, currently the 
tallest buildings in the world. 
</P>
<P>
	Plans are for the building to include a five-star hotel,  
shopping mall and convention facilities. Construction, expected to 
take five years, is scheduled to get under way in late 2000. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	MEXICO CITY (AP) -- Mexican labor leaders have criticized a  
supreme court ruling allowing government workers to choose which 
union will represent them. 
</P>
<P>
	The ruling threatens ruling-party political control over  
government workers -- the only ones covered by the Tuesday court 
decision -- but does not augur widespread changes in Mexico's labor 
groups. 
</P>
<P>
	The Federation of State Workers has long supported the ruling  
Institutional Revolutionary Party, which has held the nation's 
presidency without interruption since 1929. 
</P>
<P>
	The union's influence over its members has been used in the past  
to help the party by using government resources in election 
campaigns. 
</P>
<P>
	Joel Ayala, a leader of the federation, pledged to resist any  
changes in labor laws as a result of the supreme court ruling. 
</P>
<P>
	``We will take other kinds of action to overturn this (the  
ruling), such as protest marches or the right to strike,'' Ayala 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Workers at private companies already have the right to choose  
among competing unions. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	MEXICO CITY (AP) -- Dented cars with bashed-out windshields lined  
up at repair shops in the northern Mexican city of Monterrey after 
the area was pelted by balls of hail the size of eggs. 
</P>
<P>
	The hailstorm, which struck Tuesday, caused insurance damage  
claims for an estimated 1,800 cars, the newspaper Reforma reported. 
The balls of ice also shattered windows at homes and schools in the 
city 435 miles north of the capital. 
</P>
<P>
	Electrical power to 13,000 customers was temporarily knocked out  
by the storm, and billboards were toppled. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) -- Risking new friction with Colombia,  
Venezuelan President Hugo Chavez said Thursday he wanted to meet 
with the neighboring country's top leftist rebel leader. 
</P>
<P>
	Chavez said in a TV interview that he wanted to be ``face to  
face'' with Manuel Marulanda -- chief of the Revolutionary Armed 
Forces of Colombia, or FARC. 
</P>
<P>
	In the interview with Colombia's Caracol television network,  
Chavez said he had been invited to visit Marulanda in Colombia's 
southern jungles, but would only attend if President Andres 
Pastrana grants permission. 
</P>
<P>
	Diplomatic tensions flared between Colombia and Venezuela in  
March, after Chavez declared himself ``neutral'' in Colombia's 
35-year civil conflict. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
