<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Crude Rises on OPEC Optimism  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Crude oil futures posted their first gains in three days  
Thursday on the New York Mercantile Exchange amid renewed optimism 
oil producer cuts will boost cash prices and on reports of a Texas 
refinery problem. 
</P>
<P>
	On other markets, silver futures surged nearly 4 percent, while  
palladium also rocketed higher. 
</P>
<P>
	Crude gained after Saudi Arabia said in was in continued  
consultations with other world oil producers in an effort to boost 
cash crude prices to about $20 a barrel by year's end. 
</P>
<P>
	The Organization of the Petroleum Exporting Countries said its  
members made 82 percent of their promised cuts in the first month 
of heavy production reductions. While that report was generally in 
line with other recent estimates, the news helped reinforce ideas 
that prices should not fall drastically unless there is some 
indication of widespread cheating. 
</P>
<P>
	Analysts said crude prices could show dramatic gains in key  
producers continue to hold their quotas over the next six months. 
</P>
<P>
	Crude prices also were supported by news Coastal shut a 10,000  
barrel-a-day unit in Corpus Christi, Texas, because of a refinery 
explosion. While such a small unit is unlikely to have a major 
effort on inventories, market participants noted any sign of 
slowing production is good going into the peak driving season that 
begin on Memorial Day. 
</P>
<P>
	Light, sweet crude for June delivery rose 46 cents to $18.03 a  
barrel; June heating oil rose 1.14 cents to 43.57 cents a gallon; 
June unleaded gasoline rose .72 cent to 52.34 cents a gallon; June 
natural gas rose .92 cent to $2.282 for each 1,000 cubic feet. 
</P>
<P>
	Silver futures jumped 3.7 percent on the New York Mercantile  
Exchange in a technically driven rally tied to ideas that demand 
for the metal is on the rise in the important Asian sector. 
</P>
<P>
	July silver rose 18.7 cents to $5.57 an ounce.  
</P>
<P>
	Palladium futures rocketed higher as political turmoil in Russia  
once again caused uncertainty about when that country will export 
more of the industrial metal in bulk. 
</P>
<P>
	Russia produce about three-quarters of the world's palladium  
supply and is the second-largest platinum producer behind South 
Africa, but supplies of the industrial metal have largely been kept 
off the market since December amid bureaucratic wrangling. 
</P>
<P>
	Market participants fear Russia President Boris Yeltsin's  
decision to fire Prime Minister Yevgeny Primakov and his Cabinet 
and his subsequent impeachment hearings will lead to even greater 
export delays to Western manufacturers, who use the metals in 
automobile emission control devices. 
</P>
<P>
	Palladium prices have virtually been set over the past three  
years by the availability of Russian supplies. When they've been 
held off the market, prices soar. When they're shipped, prices fall 
sharply. Automobile manufacturers now are moving to lower their 
reliance on the metal, but palladium also is experiencing a 
resurgence in demand from the jewelry-making sector. 
</P>
<P>
	June palladium rose $5.25 to $342.25 an ounce; July platinum  
rose $2.30 to $358.60 an ounce. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990513.0064 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-13 01:45:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Settlement Sought in Diet Drug Case </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DALLAS (AP) -- Lawyers representing millions of people who used  
the diet drug combination fen-phen are negotiating a national 
settlement of health claims against the manufacturer, The Dallas 
Morning News reported today. 
</P>
<P>
	The talks with pharmaceutical giant American Home Products Corp.  
follow last month's settlement in the first trial over alleged 
heart-valve damage from fen-phen. American Home reportedly agreed 
to pay $500,000 to settle that case. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think it's a good sign both for the company and for  
consumers that lawyers are sitting down and are discussing how the 
litigation can be brought to a prompt and efficient conclusion and 
a fair conclusion,'' Houston lawyer J. Graham Hill, whose partners 
attended a settlement meeting in New York last week, told the 
newspaper. 
</P>
<P>
	Through its Wyeth-Ayerst Laboratories subsidiary, American Home  
marketed fenfluramine -- half of the fen-phen combination -- and 
Redux, a similar product. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1997, the Madison, N.J.-based company pulled fenfluramine and  
Redux off the market at the Food and Drug Administration's request. 
A Mayo Clinic study had linked the drugs to potentially fatal heart 
valve damage. 
</P>
<P>
	Since then, the drug maker said it has been hit with more than  
2,600 lawsuits. 
</P>
<P>
	The other half of fen-phen, phentermine, was never associated  
with that damage when taken alone and is still on the market. 
</P>
<P>
	The company must put between $3 billion and $5 billion into a  
settlement before it is acceptable, according to some lawyers and 
Wall Street analysts. 
</P>
<P>
	``The company knows one thing for sure,'' said Houston attorney  
John Eddie Williams, who represents 1,166 fen-phen users. ``If they 
have to try each and every one of these cases, we'll bankrupt 
them.'' 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990513.0065 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-13 09:25:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Religion Briefs / Religion Briefs  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	KANSAS CITY, Mo. (AP) -- The Fellowship of Christian Athletes is  
asking chapters in 7,100 public schools to circulate petitions for 
campus reconciliation as a tribute to victims in the Littleton, 
Colo., school killings. 
</P>
<P>
	The student pledge is named for Cassie Bernall, an FCA member  
and one of 12 students killed at Columbine High School by two 
schoolmates. She was shot after saying she believed in God. The 
organization notes that athletes as well as outspoken Christians 
were targets of the attacks. 
</P>
<P>
	The FCA, acknowledging that athletes ``can cause emotional  
hardship to those outside of their groups,'' asks pledges to treat 
fellow students with respect and dignity. 
</P>
<P>
	The petition also denounces ``racism, hatred and persecution of  
individuals because of their race or religious beliefs,'' and says 
weapons and violence don't solve conflicts. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
 *Don't rush the millennium    	
</P>
<P>
	NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) -- The National Association of Free Will  
Baptists says there's no rush to celebrate the new millennium. 
</P>
<P>
	The denomination won't mark its arrival until Jan. 1, 2001.  
</P>
<P>
	``We always like to be different,'' joked Melvin Worthington,  
executive secretary of the denomination based in Nashville. 
</P>
<P>
	Different? Maybe. Accurate? Definitely.  
</P>
<P>
	Some 1,500 years ago, the monk Dionysius Exiguus was directed by  
Pope John I to compile tables of dates to help local Roman priests 
and bishops determine the correct date for Easter. 
</P>
<P>
	Dionysius counted the year of Jesus' birth as 0001, not 0000.  
Thus it follows that the second millennium ends with the year 2000, 
and the third starts with 2001. 
</P>
<P>
	Official keepers of time at the U.S. Naval Observatory and  
England's Royal Greenwich Observatory concur. Yet most Christians 
will mark the arrival of the millennium Jan. 1, 2000. 
</P>
<P>
	``The number resonates in people's minds,'' says Darren Sherkat,  
associate professor of sociology and religious studies at 
Vanderbilt University. 
</P>
<P>
	Not, however, for the Free Will Baptists, a fundamentalist  
Baptist denomination started in 1727 by a group in North Carolina 
who broke off from the Calvinists. Unlike the Calvinists, they 
believed it's possible to forfeit salvation by sinning. 
</P>
<P>
	The denomination now has about 215,000 members, primarily in the  
Southeast. 
</P>
<P>
	Worthington said the church's millennium-related plans will  
likely include a series of workshops to renew faith, and efforts to 
attract new members, particularly among immigrants. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
 *Both sides win this debate    	
</P>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- The Unitarian Universalist Association can once  
again present religious medals to Boy Scouts. 
</P>
<P>
	The UUA, whose 250,000 members espouse widely varying beliefs  
including forms of Buddhism and feminist-inspired ``Earth-centered 
spirituality,'' has a more liberal view of homosexuality than the 
Boy Scouts of America. 
</P>
<P>
	While the two groups will remain divided on the issue, the UUA  
will remove from the ``Religion in Life'' award manual any 
reference to concerns about the Boy Scouts' ``homophobic and 
discriminatory attitudes.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Instead, it will convey the message in pamphlets mailed with the  
manual. 
</P>
<P>
	``We agreed to delete from our manual the language that the Boy  
Scouts objected to,'' said John Hurley, a spokesman for the 
Boston-based association of churches. ``But we are still going to 
be sending this material to scouts.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Boy Scouts teach traditional family values, said BSA  
spokesman Greg Shields, adding, ``An avowed homosexual wouldn't be 
a role model for those values.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Many denominations bestow religious medals on scouts. They  
differ from merit badges but may still be worn on scout uniforms. 
</P>
<P>
	The dispute between the Unitarians and the Boy Scouts came to a  
head a year ago. In April the BSA agreed to the revised manual. 
</P>
<P>
	In a letter to church members describing the agreement, UUA  
President John A. Buehrens wrote that, ``it is not homosexuality 
but homophobia which is a sin.''	   ------ 
</P>
<P>
 *Cell power in prayer tower    	
</P>
<P>
	LEXINGTON, Ky. (AP) -- Three telecommunications companies will  
get more cell power with the extended prayer tower under 
construction at Centenary United Methodist Church. 
</P>
<P>
	The church agreed to the $275,000 addition and to lease the  
tower for cellular-phone antennas. The tower, which will nearly 
double in height to 133 feet, will be topped by a lighted cross 10 
feet tall. 
</P>
<P>
	According to the agreement, each company will pay the church  
$4,000 a year for six years. They could extend the agreement for 
five years. 
</P>
<P>
	Cellular-phone companies have been seeking sites around the  
country, including church steeples, flagpoles, clock towers and 
farm silos. 
</P>
<P>
	The prayer tower was built in 1992 with a small meditation room  
at the base. It was rendered unusable when the tower was usurped as 
a pigeon roost. 
</P>
<P>
	Centenary will put the lease money aside for special projects  
such as new ministries or emergency relief, said the Rev. David R. 
Thomas, senior pastor. 
</P>
</TEXT>
