<HEADLINE> Tokyo Stocks Higher in Early Trading / Japanese Stocks  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- The dollar was higher against the yen in early  
trading Friday, while Japanese stocks advanced on yet another 
record close on Wall Street. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar bought 121.74 yen in early trading, up 0.16 yen from  
late Thursday in Tokyo but lower than its late New York level of 
121.85 yen. 
</P>
<P>
	The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average rose 73.86 points,  
or 0.44 percent, to 16,925.11 in the first 30 minutes of trading. 
On Thursday, the index lost 96.11 points, or 0.57 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	In currency dealings, the dollar was well-supported by U.S.  
economic data released late Thursday, which indicated inflation is 
still nascent in the United States. 
</P>
<P>
	It prompted growing expectations that the U.S. Federal Reserve  
Open Markets Committee will leave interest rates unchanged at its 
meeting Tuesday, traders said. 
</P>
<P>
	In other currencies, the euro bought 129.90 yen in early  
trading, up from 129.36 yen late Thursday in Tokyo. 
</P>
<P>
	On the stock market, prices rose moderately following another  
record close in New York. The Dow Jones industrial average closed 
at 11,107.19 points, up 106.82. 
</P>
<P>
	But gains in Tokyo stocks were limited early Friday as  
participants grew cautious about pushing prices higher before a 
series of closely watched earnings reports for last fiscal year, 
which ended March 31, are released in coming weeks, traders said. 
</P>
<P>
	The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the  
first section was up 2.08 points, or 0.15 percent, to 1,354.05. The 
TOPIX fell 9.18 points, or 0.67 percent, the day before. 
</P>
<P>
	The yield on the benchmark 10-year Japanese government bond fell  
to 1.260 percent from 1.275 percent late Thursday, driving its 
price up to 102.14 yen from 102.01 yen. 
</P>
</TEXT>
