<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Politics at Cannes Film Festival </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CANNES, France (AP) -- Proving that even the dream world of films  
isn't immune to harsh realities, the first day of the Cannes Film 
Festival was full of reminders of the conflict in Kosovo. 
</P>
<P>
	The strongest message came from the Oscar-winning Russian  
director whose film was honored with the festival's opening slot. 
</P>
<P>
	Nikita Mikhalkov, director of ``The Barber of Siberia,'' used  
his news conference Wednesday to castigate NATO -- and especially 
the United States -- over the airstrikes on Yugoslavia. 
</P>
<P>
	``The NATO action is a tragic, tragic error,'' Mikhalkov said in  
a long, impassioned response to a question. 
</P>
<P>
	He described NATO pilots pushing buttons -- as in a video game --  
as they fired their missiles. 
</P>
<P>
	``After 10 seconds, the plane goes back to its base,'' Mikhalkov  
said, speaking in Russian. ``The missiles are still falling. What 
happens on the ground, the pilot doesn't know. Maybe the bomb has 
hit the Chinese Embassy.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He reserved his strongest criticism for the Americans.  
</P>
<P>
	``The United States never fought on its own territory,'' said  
the director, one of the best-known figures in Russia, who has even 
spoken of running for president. ``It never dug trenches on its own 
land.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In the familiar juxtaposition of glitter and substance that  
seems to characterize Cannes, Mikhalkov appeared hours later in a 
tuxedo, accompanying Faye Dunaway on the festival palace stage to 
declare the 52nd annual Cannes festival open. 
</P>
<P>
	British actress Kristin Scott Thomas, who hosted the ceremony,  
also made a reference to Kosovo. ``What is happening just a few 
hours away by plane,'' she said, ``makes cinema all the more 
precious, as an antidote.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mikhalkov spent 10 years on ``The Barber of Siberia,'' which  
opened the 12-day festival. The film, not among the 22 in 
competition for awards, is a lavish period drama recalling the era 
of Czar Alexander III in the late 1800s. 
</P>
<P>
	Starring British actress Julia Ormond and Russian star Oleg  
Menshikov, it premiered in February at the Kremlin in front of some 
5,000 people, among them starlets, Cabinet ministers and tycoons. 
</P>
<P>
	The movie focuses on a romance between a Russian cadet and an  
American woman. Although much of it is played too broadly and some 
dialogue is leaden, Menshikov gives an affecting performance as the 
cadet. 
</P>
<P>
	The 53-year-old Mikhalkov, considered a nationalist, won an  
Oscar for best foreign-language film in 1995 with ``Burnt By the 
Sun,'' a story of Stalinist repression told through one family's 
experiences. 
</P>
<P>
	The son of the author of the Soviet anthem, he was a successful  
director in Soviet times, and managed to maintain his popularity 
even after the 1991 collapse of the Soviet Union. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
