<DOCNO> APW19990513.0073 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-13 01:32:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Lukas Ready to Rumble at Preakness </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BALTIMORE (AP) -- As he crossed the street and walked toward his  
waiting car, D. Wayne Lukas couldn't help but flash a huge smile. 
</P>
<P>
	The Hall of Fame trainer had just attended the post-position  
draw for Saturday's Preakness, and his Kentucky Derby winner 
Charismatic ended up in a perfect spot -- No. 6 in a full 14-horse 
field. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're in the zone,'' Lukas said Wednesday night. ``I'm tickled  
to death with the draw. Things are falling into place.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Cat Thief, Lukas' other 3-year-old colt, fared well, too, with  
the trainer selecting the No. 3 slot for his third-place Derby 
finisher. 
</P>
<P>
	``I feel great about Charismatic. I think he's peaked at the  
right time,'' Lukas said, even though the Derby winner was fourth 
choice at 6-1 in the early-morning line. ``And I expect Cat Thief 
to keep everyone honest. It won't surprise me if he wins.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The biggest jolt was reserved for trainer Bob Baffert, who was  
hoping his star fillies would draw favorable posts. Excellent 
Meeting did and is definitely in; Silverbulletday didn't and may be 
out. 
</P>
<P>
	Excellent Meeting, fifth in the Derby after a strong finish,  
ended up with the No. 7 post, while Silverbulletday, a winner in 10 
of 11 career starts -- none against males -- got the outside No. 14 
spot. 
</P>
<P>
	``We'll just mull it over and committee-icize over crabcakes and  
lite beer,'' Baffert said. ``I'm not angry, just disappointed.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Silverbulletday drew the rail for Friday's Black-Eyed Susan, and  
Baffert has until the day of the race to decide where to send the 
Mike Pegram-owned filly. He said if Silverbulletday drew anywhere 
from posts 4-10, or the No. 1 slot, she's be a definite Preakness 
starter. 
</P>
<P>
	``But now we have to think about this filly,'' Baffert said.  
``One like this comes along so rarely. Mike and I talk about it a 
lot, and maybe that (the draw) was a signal to tell us not to 
run.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Menifee, runner-up in the Derby by neck to the 31-1 shot  
Charismatic, was the 5-2 favorite, while the fillies were next -- 
Silverbulletday at 7-2 and Excellent Meeting at 5-1. 
</P>
<P>
	The 14-horse field, which includes a record 10 Derby horses,  
matches the largest in the 1 3-16th-mile Preakness since 1993. 
</P>
<P>
	Winning Colors, Lukas' 1988 Derby winner, was the last filly to  
run in the Preakness, finishing third. Four fillies have won the 
Preakness, but none since Nellie Morse in 1924. 
</P>
<P>
	Lukas may have a little history on his side, too, as he shoots  
for his fifth Preakness win -- the No. 6 gate has produced 13 
winners of the second leg of the Triple Crown, the most of any post 
position. 
</P>
<P>
	He's also got the only Triple Crown contender in Charasmatic.  
</P>
<P>
	``I've won a Triple Crown, but I needed two horses to do it,''  
Lukas said, referring to 1995, when Thunder Gulch won the Derby and 
Belmont, but stablemate Timber Country took the Preakness. ``Maybe 
one of these days, we'll win all three with one horse.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Charismatic might be the one, even though his reputation suffers  
because he was put in claiming races twice -- the last on Feb. 11 -- 
and could have been purchased for $62,500 after either. 
</P>
<P>
	``I know the story all week will be he's a claimer, and  
everything went his way in the Derby,'' Lukas said. ``But don't 
discredit the horse because I was foolish enough to run him in a 
claiming race.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Charismatic, owned by Bob and Beverly Lewis, might be light on  
victories, but he's the most seasoned Preakness starter of all. 
He'll be racing for the 16th time -- fourth since the Santa Anita 
Derby on April 3. 
</P>
<P>
	``He seems to be a two-week horse,'' Lukas said. ``I think he's  
had a little attitude adjustment from the Derby. He's kind of 
focused. He's been laid back all spring. He ran a good Derby, never 
turned a hair. I think he's ready to run.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Preakness draw was handled the same way as the Derby draw --  
a draft order was selected and trainers picked their spots based on 
that order. Baffert had the 13th pick with Silverbulletday and 
trainer Carl Nafzger had the 14th pick. When it came time for them 
to make their picks, they held an impromptu coin toss, and Nafzger 
won, taking the 13th post. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was Bob's idea,'' Nafzger said. ``I ain't that smart.''  
</P>
<P>
	The 10 Derby horses running Saturday are Charismatic, Menifee,  
Cat Thief, Excellent Meeting, Kimberlite Pipe, Worldly Manner, 
Stephen Got Even, Valhol, Adonis and Vicar. The newcomers are 
Badge, Patience Game, Silverbulletday and Torrid Sand. 
</P>
<P>
	The last Preakness winner who did not run in the Derby was  
Deputed Testamony in 1983. 
</P>
<P>
	The field, from the rail out, is Torrid Sand (Tim Duhey, 60-1);  
Kimberlite Pipe (Shane Sellers, 20-1); Cat Thief (Mike Smith, 8-1); 
Badge (Mike Luzzi, 50-1); Menifee (Pat Day, 5-2); Charismatic 
(Chris Antley, 6-1); Excellent Meeting (Kent Desormeaux, 5-1); 
Patience Game (Corey Nakatani, 30-1);l Adonis (Jorge Chavez, 30-1); 
Worldly Manner (Jerry Bailey, 12-1); Stephen Got Even (to be named, 
10-1); Valhol (Edgar Prado, 99-1); Vicar (Robby Albarado, 30-1); 
and Silverbulletday (Gary Stevens, 7-2). 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
