<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> 49ers Owner Demands Sale Recision </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- Suspended San Francisco 49ers co-owner  
Eddie DeBartolo Jr. asked a judge Thursday to rescind his sale of 
the team to the family-held corporation run by his sister. He also 
asked for more than $650 million in damages. 
</P>
<P>
	The complaint filed in San Francisco Superior Court was a reply  
to the lawsuit filed last month by Denise DeBartolo York seeking to 
oust her brother from any management role with the team and 
demanding he repay $94 million to the Edward J. DeBartolo Corp. 
</P>
<P>
	DeBartolo said his sister broke promises she made in writing in  
October 1997 that if he stopped playing any management role in the 
company, his financial interests would be preserved. The siblings 
each own a 50 percent stake in the family business, a Youngstown, 
Ohio-based real estate development firm that is also the nominal 
owner of the 49ers. 
</P>
<P>
	``All this was done with one purpose, not a fair, equitable  
sharing of our father's legacy, but a squeeze play to force me out 
of the family business at a price well below my lawful due,'' 
DeBartolo said in a statement. ``I will not compromise what I built 
with my father, nor surrender what he left to me and my children.'' 
</P>
<P>
	York spokesman Sam Singer said Thursday night ``there's  
literally not a single true thing anywhere in Eddie's complaint.'' 
</P>
<P>
	DeBartolo said York promised that once his troubles in a  
Louisiana gambling fraud scandal were resolved, he would regain 
control of the team and corporation. The corporation and the 49ers 
have been run by York and her husband, John York, since DeBartolo 
became enmeshed in the scandal. 
</P>
<P>
	But in March, NFL commissioner Paul Tagliabue forbade DeBartolo  
from exercising any authority over the 49ers' operations, saying he 
was guilty of conduct detrimental to the league for his involvement 
in the gambling fraud case. He sanctioned DeBartolo and fined him 
$1 million, and extended DeBartolo's NFL banishment until at least 
February 2000. 
</P>
<P>
	``Eddie's answer to the lawsuit is completely unfounded and  
untruthful,'' Singer said. ``I think that the crux of this matter 
is that Eddie ran up a $94 million debt, he got convicted of a 
felony in the state of Louisiana and now he's looking to blame his 
sister, his brother-in-law, the corporation when he has no one to 
blame but himself.'' 
</P>
<P>
	DeBartolo also said Thursday his sister diminished his lawful  
holdings in the corporation, refused to hold shareholder meetings 
and demanded he make payments on obligations that were not due or 
owed, among other allegations. 
</P>
<P>
	No one immediately returned calls Thursday seeking additional  
comment from DeBartolo. 
</P>
<P>
	York on Wednesday asked a federal judge in Ohio to dismiss a  
$150 million lawsuit her brother filed against her for breach of 
contract, alleging she reneged on a deal to turn the team over to 
him as part of an August 1998 agreement. 
</P>
<P>
	That deal would have divided the assets of their jointly owned  
business, with DeBartolo gaining sole possession of the team in 
return for $350 million. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
