<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Angels' Salmon To Be Out 5 Weeks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ANAHEIM, Calif. (AP) -- The Anaheim Angels have been bitten  
severely by the injury bug yet again. 
</P>
<P>
	The Angels, who have had a rash of injuries in recent years,  
will be without right fielder Tim Salmon for at least five more 
weeks because of a sprained left wrist. 
</P>
<P>
	Salmon joins center fielder Jim Edmonds and shortstop Gary  
DiSarcina on the sidelines for an extended period. The Angels have 
also been without right-handed pitchers Jack McDowell, Jason 
Dickson and Mike James all season, and none are expected back any 
time soon. 
</P>
<P>
	An arthrogram taken late Wednesday revealed Salmon's injury is  
worse than originally thought. He hurt himself diving for a fly 
ball in the fourth inning of a game against the Chicago White Sox 
on May 3. 
</P>
<P>
	Salmon, hitting .347 with seven homers and 25 RBIs, was  
originally listed as day to day, but finally went on the 15-day 
disabled list Tuesday -- eight days after being injured -- when the 
pain persisted. 
</P>
<P>
	Even then, it was believed Salmon would probably return to  
action next week, but now, it won't be until sometime next month, 
or later. 
</P>
<P>
	Salmon's wrist was placed in a short-arm cast, where it will  
remain for three weeks, and he will then need at least a couple 
weeks to rehabilitate the wrist before playing again. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's frustrated, but he knows you can't risk long-term  
injury,'' Angels vice president of communications Tim Mead said 
from New York before the Angels and Yankees met in the finale of a 
three-game series Thursday night. ``That's why he needs to take 
care of it now.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Salmon, 30, has averaged nearly 30 homers per year since  
becoming a regular in 1993, when he was voted AL Rookie of the 
Year. He entered the season with a lifetime batting average of 
.294. 
</P>
</TEXT>
