<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dow Closes at Record 11,107.19 / Wall Street Report  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks were mostly higher Thursday on reports  
showing moderate inflation, with the Dow Jones industrial average 
and the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 pushing to new records. 
</P>
<P>
	But weakness in some technology shares pulled the Nasdaq Stock  
Market lower. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dow Jones industrial average climbed 106.82 to 11,107.19,  
breezing past its previous closing record of 11,031.59 posted last 
Friday. The Dow is up nearly 21 percent so far this year. 
</P>
<P>
	The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index rose 3.56 to 1,367.56, topping  
its previous closing high of 1,364.00 set Wednesday. But the 
technology-heavy Nasdaq composite index declined 24.54 to 2,582.00. 
</P>
<P>
	IBM almost single-handedly led the Dow higher after Merrill  
Lynch raised its prediction for how much the stock would rise over 
the next 12 months. That came after an analyst meeting Wednesday 
during which chairman Louis Gerstner said the Internet would play a 
large part in the company's future, and that a quarter of IBM's 
1998 revenues came from electronic commerce. 
</P>
<P>
	``The bull beat goes on, led by Big Blue,'' said Alfred E.  
Goldman, chief market strategist at A.G. Edwards &AMP; Sons Inc. in St. 
Louis. IBM shares soared 20 1/2 to a record 246, accounting for a rise 
of more than 93 points on the Dow. 
</P>
<P>
	Computer shares rose initially with IBM but later bowed to  
profit-taking. Internet stocks were lower on profit-taking as well; 
America Online dropped 5 13/16 to 132 5/8 and was the most active 
issue on the NYSE. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dow transportation average fell 30.99, or 0.82 percent, to  
3,752.51, after the Justice Department said it was investigating 
American Airlines for antitrust violations. The shares of 
American's parent, AMR Corp., dropped 5/16 to 74. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, the market got a boost from a government report that  
wholesale inflation was in line with expectations. The Labor 
Department said the producer price index rose 0.5 percent in April 
as the price of gasoline jumped significantly. But the index's core 
rate, which strips away volatile food and energy costs, was up a 
mere 0.1 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Separately, the department said first-time claims for  
unemployment benefits held steady at a moderate 303,000 last week. 
A more reliable four-week moving average of jobless claims dropped 
by 4,000 to 304,250, suggesting that unemployment will remain at 
4.3 percent this month, near a 29-year low. 
</P>
<P>
	In a third report, the Commerce Department said retail sales  
rose 0.1 percent in April, as consumers reacted to higher energy 
costs by pulling in their purse strings. That was a smaller 
increase than many analysts had expected. 
</P>
<P>
	Investors are now turning their attention to Friday's expected  
release of consumer price data. Taken together, the producer- and 
consumer-price data could give them clues about the Federal 
Reserve's policy meeting next Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Most investors don't expect the Fed to raise interest rates,  
though it might if it feels the need to slow the economy and head 
off inflation, said Larry Rice, chief investment officer at 
Josephthal &AMP; Co. ``Most people think (central bankers) are more 
inclined to raise rates in August, after they get more indication 
of recovering global economies,'' Rice said. 
</P>
<P>
	Bond prices rose, with the yield on the 30-year Treasury bond --  
which moves in the opposite direction from price --falling to 5.75 
percent from 5.82 late Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Financial services stocks rose early in the day but then dropped  
back, with Citigroup down 1/2 at 73 7/16, and American Express down 
1 1/4 at 124 3/4. J.P. Morgan shares, however, rose 7 5/8 to 146 3/4 on 
takeover speculation. 
</P>
<P>
	Declining issues outnumbered advancers by a 6-to-5 margin on the  
New York Stock Exchange, where consolidate volume totaled 975.2 
million shares, down from Wednesday's pace. 
</P>
<P>
	The NYSE composite index rose 3.67 to 651.35, and the American  
Stock Exchange composite index rose 2.04 to 800.39. The Russell 
2000 index of smaller companies rose 1.58 to 450.84. 
</P>
<P>
	In overseas trading, the Nikkei index in Tokyo declined 0.57  
percent. In Europe, the DAX index in Frankfurt eased 0.02 percent, 
the FT-SE 100 index in London climbed 1.79, following New York's 
lead, while the CAC in Paris rose 0.11 percent. 

</P>
</TEXT>
