<HEADLINE> Chung Says He Got Invite From Gore </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Johnny Chung says he recently received some  
unwanted mail from Vice President Al Gore: an invitation to attend 
a fund-raiser. 
</P>
<P>
	Chung testified Thursday in a case brought by a conservative  
group that he received the invitation about a month ago for an 
event in Los Angeles from the vice president by mail and by fax, at 
his home and at his office. 
</P>
<P>
	He also said he was solicited by the Democratic Congressional  
Campaign Committee in the past seven to 10 days. 
</P>
<P>
	Judicial Watch deposed Chung regarding the alleged sale of  
Commerce Department trade mission seats in exchange for campaign 
donations. 
</P>
<P>
	On Thursday, Chung testified that he told his wife, ``This is  
not the kind of mailings I like to receive any more.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gore spokesman Roger Salazar acknowledged that Chung did receive  
a direct mailing, because his name was on a list used for fund 
raising. 
</P>
<P>
	``Once the campaign found out that his name was on one of the  
lists that we purchased, he was immediately removed from the 
list,'' Salazar said. 
</P>
<P>
	Chung was sentenced to five years' probation after admitting  
that he made $30,000 in illegal contributions, including $20,000 to 
the 1996 Clinton-Gore re-election campaign. On Tuesday, he 
testified before the House Government Reform Committee. 
</P>
</TEXT>
