<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Pirates' Meares, Christiansen on DL </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PITTSBURGH (AP) -- For the second time in three years, a newly  
signed Pittsburgh Pirates shortstop is on the disabled list -- and 
probably for an extended period. 
</P>
<P>
	The Pirates, who were idle Thursday, put shortstop Pat Meares  
(tendon injury) and left-handed reliever Jason Christiansen 
(sprained neck) on the disabled list. They recalled shortstop 
Abraham Nunez from Triple-A Nashville. 
</P>
<P>
	Right-hander Francisco Cordova, who hasn't pitched since April  
10 because of shoulder inflammation, is expected to be activated 
off the disabled list this weekend. 
</P>
<P>
	Meares has an injured tendon in his left hand that may need  
surgery, which would sideline him until at least mid-August. 
</P>
<P>
	The injury is not related to the left wrist sprain that put him  
on the disabled list at the start of the season. However, it is 
related to the left little finger injury that kept him out of a May 
3 game against San Francisco. 
</P>
<P>
	At the time, a hand specialist told Meares he would ultimately  
need surgery, but Meares hoped to postpone the operation until the 
season ended. 
</P>
<P>
	But Meares had trouble gripping the bat and tried unsuccessfully  
to compensate by taping his left little finger to his ring finger. 
</P>
<P>
	``It wasn't doing me any good to play,'' Meares said.  
</P>
<P>
	The injury worsened only two weeks after Meares agreed to a $15  
million, four-year contract extension. 
</P>
<P>
	Coincidentally, shortstop Kevin Elster was injured in mid-May  
two years ago, not long after signing with the Pirates. He did not 
play again that season and did not re-sign with Pittsburgh. 
</P>
<P>
	Nunez began the season with the Pirates and was 5-for-18 (.278)  
with three RBIs in six games. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
