<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Mistrial Declared for Former Judge </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NORFOLK, Va. (AP) -- The trial of a former judge accused of  
donning a mask and pistol-whipping a political rival has ended in a 
mistrial. 
</P>
<P>
	Luther C. Edmonds was accused of attacking William P. Robinson  
Jr., a member of the state House of Delegates, outside Robinson's 
law office in 1997. Robinson's attacker bashed his face with a gun, 
forcing him to get 30 stitches on his head. 
</P>
<P>
	Edmonds and Robinson, both 56, were once friends and political  
allies. They parted ways when Robinson publicly disputed the reason 
Edmonds gave for resigning from the bench during a misconduct 
inquiry. 
</P>
<P>
	Edmonds, a judge for eight years, also is running against  
Robinson in a June Democratic primary for Robinson's House seat. 
</P>
<P>
	Edmonds was charged with malicious wounding, use of a gun in a  
felony and the unlawful wearing of a mask. He could have faced 28 
years in prison if convicted. 
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutors, who said they will retry the case, contended that  
DNA tests showed blood on a gun seized from Edmonds' apartment 
matched Robinson's blood. 
</P>
<P>
	But defense attorneys said at least 18 people had access to the  
police locker where the gun and blood sample were kept. Jurors 
deliberated 10 hours before the mistrial was declared Thursday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
