<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Man Arrested in Mosque Threat Probed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LITTLETON, Colo. (AP) -- Police were investigating the military  
and medical history of a man who allegedly wanted to torch a mosque 
and was found with bomb components, four guns and two machetes. 
</P>
<P>
	Jack M. Modig, 39, was being held on $500,000 bond Thursday  
after being arrested on charges of possession of explosives, 
attempted vehicular assault and ethnic intimidation. 
</P>
<P>
	Investigators said Modig told them he is ``an enemy of the  
Islamic nation'' and wanted to ``kill Iraqis.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Police arrested Modig early Wednesday after he was spotted in a  
white Oldsmobile Cutlass parked with the lights off near the 
entrance of the Islamic Center in eastern Denver. Police said a 
sergeant approached Modig, but the car sped off and a chase ensued. 
</P>
<P>
	Modig allegedly tried to ram the officers' cars and struggled  
with police when they caught up with him in Denver. 
</P>
<P>
	In the trunk of his car, authorities discovered 30 gallons of  
gasoline and other bomb components, as well as four guns, two 
22-inch machetes, 850 rounds of ammunition, a black ski mask and 
tactical goggles. 
</P>
<P>
	``He wanted to burn the mosque because of the Iraqis associated  
with it,'' Arapahoe County Sheriff Pat Sullivan said. 
</P>
<P>
	Bill McCarthy, the suspect's second cousin, said Modig lived in  
the basement of his south Denver home and kept to himself. He had 
served four years in the Army. 
</P>
<P>
	McCarthy said Modig has had mental problems since a military  
motorcycle accident in Germany several years ago. 
</P>
<P>
	``The poor guy has paid the price ever since then,'' McCarthy  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	McCarthy said Modig has been in and out of VA hospitals. He said  
he has never heard Modig utter defamatory remarks about religious 
or ethnic groups. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's very sad, he's such a beautiful person,'' McCarthy said.  
</P>
<P>
	Saul Rosenthal, regional director of the Anti-Defamation League,  
said Modig was known for having ties to Colorado Common Law Courts, 
a spin-off of the militia movement. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
