<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Japan's Dall Porpoises Endangered </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Japanese fishermen are hunting too many dolphins in  
the Sea of Japan, endangering a population of Dall's porpoises, an 
environmental group charged today. 
</P>
<P>
	Dall's porpoises are being harvested heavily off Japan's shores  
and sold misleadingly as whale meat, a delicacy that earns 
fisherman considerable profit, the Environmental Investigation 
Agency said. 
</P>
<P>
	The hunts, which kill about 18,000 porpoises a year, imperil the  
species' ability to sustain its population, which Japan estimates 
at 440,000, the group said. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is the biggest hunt of any cetaceans species anywhere in  
the world,'' EIA chairman Alan Thornton told reporters. 
</P>
<P>
	The London-based environmental group urged the Japanese  
government to comply with a 1990 recommendation by the 
International Whaling Commission to regulate catches so they fall 
below 1985 levels of 10,000 a year. 
</P>
<P>
	Thornton said hunting of Dall's porpoises increased dramatically  
after the introduction of a 1986 moratorium on large whale hunting. 
</P>
<P>
	The Japanese government insists that its quota on dolphin  
catches of 22,180 a year is sufficient to ensure the survival of 
the Dall's porpoise. 
</P>
<P>
	Dall's porpoise hunting peaked in 1987, after the whale hunting  
moratorium sent dolphin prices soaring in Japan. More than 40,000 
porpoises were caught that year. 
</P>
<P>
	But the government has since imposed regulations on dolphin  
hunting, said an official for Japan's Fisheries Agency, who only 
gave his surname, Hyugaji. 
</P>
<P>
	Hajime Ishikawa, an expert at the Institute of Cetacean  
Research, was skeptical about the EIA's claims. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't understand why they are getting upset about dolphin  
hunting right now,'' said Ishikawa. ``If fishermen were taking 
40,000 porpoises like they were ten years ago it would indeed be 
serious, but that's not the case.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ishikawa said it was well known that porpoise meat is often sold  
as whale meat, but that the practice was not illegal as porpoises 
are considered a type of whale in Japan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
