<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Two Sponsors Interested in Olympics </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SALT LAKE CITY (AP) -- Organizers of the scandal-bruised 2002  
Winter Games plan to ask for concessions from the International 
Olympic Committee in meetings here next week. 
</P>
<P>
	The Salt Lake Organizing Committee wants to renegotiate the  
contract with the IOC to reduce Salt Lake's costs; to defer royalty 
payments on merchandise, sponsorships and tickets; and the chance 
to go after technology sponsors, chief executive officer Mitt 
Romney said Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	``What we're looking for from our other stakeholders is some  
help,'' Romney told the SLOC board's management committee. 
</P>
<P>
	The IOC Coordination Commission will meet Monday through  
Thursday, the group's first meeting here since this winter's 
scandal over Salt Lake's excessive wooing of IOC members during its 
bid. 
</P>
<P>
	Eighteen IOC members and members of the Lausanne,  
Switzerland-based organization's staff will review the city's 
preparations for the games, less than three years away. 
</P>
<P>
	Anita DeFrantz, an IOC vice president from Los Angeles and a  
member of the SLOC board's management committee, said the IOC is 
open to discussion, if not agreement, on concessions. 
</P>
<P>
	``We will work with them. We always have,'' DeFrantz said  
Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Salt Lake is $350 million short of meeting its $1.45 billion  
budget, and though two corporations this week began flirting with 
the SLOC, the committee isn't counting on sponsor wariness 
evaporating any time soon. 
</P>
<P>
	No new companies have signed on for the 2002 Winter Games since  
last summer, even before the scandal left corporations wondering 
about the value of Olympics sponsorship. 
</P>
<P>
	Romney on Thursday reviewed some $84 million that could be  
sliced from the budget, including expenses related to the IOC as 
well as no lunches for volunteers and a $2 million cut in his own 
budget, ensuring he gets no paycheck. He first discussed the cuts 
in March, and staffers are scrutinizing the budget in more detail 
before proposing specific reductions. 
</P>
<P>
	The SLOC could save $1.5 million to $2 million if the IOC will  
allow it to defer paying royalties on merchandise, sponsorships, 
tickets and cash contributions, Romney said. 
</P>
<P>
	By paying the IOC later, the SLOC can match the payments to its  
revenue stream and avoid borrowing from a line of credit. It would 
save on interest expenses, bank fees and premiums for games 
cancellation insurance. 
</P>
<P>
	It's not a lot of money, Romney conceded, but such a gesture  
would have value, he said. ``It ... communicates that the IOC is 
with us,'' Romney said. 
</P>
<P>
	He declined to specify which parts of the SLOC contract with the  
IOC he wants to renegotiate, but said he plans to ask for the same 
concessions Sydney received. 
</P>
<P>
	The IOC Coordination Commission for the 2002 Summer Games last  
month agreed to let Sydney provide less in the way of such services 
as travel, accommodations and transportation. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. Olympic Committee also is being asked to accept later  
payments of royalties and a renegotiated contract, Romney said. 
</P>
<P>
	In neither case is the Salt Lake committee trying to reduce the  
amount of money it owes the IOC as the local franchisee for the 
games, Romney said. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're not in an adversarial relationship. We are in a  
collaborative relationship.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Potentially more important to the SLOC is persuading the IOC to  
let the U.S. Olympic Committee and Salt Lake organizers go after 
certain types of technology sponsors. 
</P>
<P>
	IBM for years has had a lock on all aspects of technology  
sponsorship through its contract with the IOC. 
</P>
<P>
	That changes after the 2002 Summer Games. The IOC has chosen the  
European company Sema as the information technologies systems 
integrator beginning in 2001, and is in negotiations for a computer 
hardware sponsor. 
</P>
<P>
	But it is still grappling with the question of what categories  
of technology sponsorship to keep as its own and which to turn over 
to national Olympic committees. Some possible categories include 
suppliers of routers, switches, instantaneous Internet games 
results and Internet ticket sales. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're trying to pry some of these things loose from the big  
umbrella,'' Romney said. ``We would have the potential to sell in 
each of those categories if they released them to us. Today we 
can't do that.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
