<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Grains Rise on Export Hopes / Board of Trade  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Grain futures advanced today on the Chicago Board  
of Trade amid signs the export outlook for corn and wheat is 
improving. Soybeans retreated. 
</P>
<P>
	Corn futures rose after the U.S. Agriculture Department reported  
corn exports last week of 1.336 million metric tons, the fifth 
consecutive week that sales have topped 1 million metric tons. The 
unexpectedly strong demand has raised expectations the government 
will boost annual export projections and lower estimates for ending 
stocks. 
</P>
<P>
	Corn also was supported by continued rains across Midwest  
growing regions, which was delaying fieldwork as time runs out for 
getting crops into the ground. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat futures advanced after the USDA reported weekly exports of  
436,400 metric tons for the current and upcoming marketing year. 
The combined total came in above expectations and lent support to 
expectations that Asian demand may be on the rise. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat also saw continued support from the government projections  
that the winter wheat crop will be far smaller than last year's. 
</P>
<P>
	Soybeans moved lower amid worry that smaller corn acreage could  
translate into larger soybeans acreage, at a time when the 
government already is predicting a record crop. Market participants 
also were concerned about the coming competition for exports from 
the competing Brazilian bumper crop. Soybeans found some support 
from strong weekly export sales. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat for July delivery rose 1 cent to $2.71 1/2 a bushel; July  
corn rose 1 cent to $2.24 1/4 a bushel; July oats rose 1 cent to $1.27 
a bushel; July soybeans fell 1 1/4 cents to $4.74 1/4 a bushel. 
</P>
<P>
	Pork and live cattle futures advanced on the Chicago Mercantile  
Exchange, while feeder cattle retreated. 
</P>
<P>
	June live cattle rose .22 cents to 61.30 cents a pound; August  
feeder cattle fell .75 cent to 72.85 cents a pound; June lean hogs 
were unchanged at 59.875 a pound; July pork bellies rose .75 cent 
to 59.025 cents a pound. 
</P>
</TEXT>
