<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> The Nation's Weather  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	A slow-moving storm system dumped rain on the Midwest and South  
early today, while showers lingered over the northern Rockies and 
Northwest. It was generally fair and dry elsewhere. 
</P>
<P>
	Heavy rain was expected into tonight across the Great Lakes  
region, Illinois, Indiana and the Ohio Valley. The storms prompted 
sightings of funnel clouds on Wednesday in parts of Illinois. 
</P>
<P>
	Rain and thunderstorms were also predicted from Tennessee to  
Florida and the Carolinas. 
</P>
<P>
	The Northeast, southern Plains and Southwest were expected to  
remain mostly dry. But up to 3 inches of snow were possible in the 
mountains of Washington state as a storm system moves to the east. 
</P>
<P>
	The highest temperature reported in the continental United  
States on Wednesday was 99 degrees at Blythe, Calif. The low was 19 
at Gunnison, Colo. 
</P>
<P>
	Highs today were expected to reach the 40s and 50s in the  
Northwest, northern Rockies and Great Lakes; the 60s in the 
Northeast and Midwest; and the 70s and 80s in the West, southern 
Plains and Southeast. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
