<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at Midnight EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Bargainers Complete Kosovo Bill  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A compromise package financing the bombardment  
of Yugoslavia and aid to Central America was agreed upon by 
House-Senate bargainers Thursday night, but the deal drops 
controversial proposals to create loan guarantee programs for 
ailing steel and energy companies. The House and Senate planned to 
vote on the wide-ranging spending measure next week and ship it to 
President Clinton. Working into the night, negotiators from the two 
chambers capped their third day of bargaining by agreeing to 
consider the proposed loan programs in a separate bill in coming 
weeks. 

</P>
<P>
	NATO Planes To Strike From Turkey  
</P>
<P>
	ANKARA, Turkey (AP) -- The Turkish military is preparing bases in  
western Turkey for NATO planes conducting airstrikes against 
Yugoslavia, officials said Thursday. The use of Turkish bases for 
NATO attacks completes what alliance officials say is a strategy to 
``encircle Yugoslavia 360 degrees.'' Hungary announced last week 
that NATO combat missions would operate from its soil. Turkey's 
military general staff said in a statement that ``some NATO planes 
will take part in the operation from bases in western Anatolia 
following the completion of our work.'' It did not give a 
timeframe. The Cabinet authorized the military to make arrangements 
for NATO planes Tuesday. 

</P>
<P>
	China, U.S. May Have Talks  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton and Chinese President Jiang  
Zemin agreed Thursday to a future talk, as tensions with China over 
NATO's bombing of the Chinese Embassy in Belgrade appeared to be 
easing. Jiang had avoided talking to Clinton since Saturday's 
bombing, which killed three people. His readiness to talk was 
conveyed by Chinese Ambassador Li Zhaoxing, who took a condolence 
book to the White House for Clinton to sign. 

</P>
<P>
	Child Stuck in Well in Kansas  
</P>
<P>
	MULVANE, Kan. (AP) -- A toddler has fallen more than 15 feet into  
a narrow well and firefighters are trying to dig a tunnel to rescue 
the boy. Firefighters could hear the 17-month old boy crying 
Thursday night, but he was out of the reach of rescue equipment, 
Sedgwick County Fire Marshal Greg Thompson said. The well is 20 to 
25 feet deep and only 8 to 10 inches wide. The boy, who was playing 
in a backyard, fell at least 15 feet and may have gotten stuck, 
Thompson said. 

</P>
<P>
	GOP Reconsidering Gun Control  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Facing increased pressure for the vote against  
gun control measures at gun shows, Senate Republicans indicated 
Thursday they may be ready to make concessions on the issue. 
Republicans called for fresh restrictions on sales at gun shows 
less than 24 hours after rejecting them despite public outrage over 
last month's high school shootings in Colorado. But Democrats 
denounced the new offer, saying it contained numerous loopholes. 
``It's the most Swiss-cheesy bill I've ever seen,'' said Sen. 
Charles Schumer, D-N.Y. 

</P>
<P>
	Bus Driver Had Been Fired for Drugs  
</P>
<P>
	NEW ORLEANS (AP) -- The driver of a charter bus that crashed and  
killed 22 people was fired from bus companies in 1996 and 1989 
after testing positive for marijuana four times, authorities said 
Thursday. A federal investigator also confirmed a report that Frank 
Bedell, 46, tested positive for marijuana when he was hospitalized 
Sunday after the bus veered off a highway and plunged into an 
embankment. 

</P>
<P>
	Netanyahu Losing Some Support  
</P>
<P>
	JERUSALEM (AP) -- Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu's  
traditional support among ex-Soviet Jews is faltering, the former 
dissident who leads a powerful immigrants party said Thursday. 
Natan Sharansky, the industry and trade minister in Netanyahu's 
government, also refused to endorse the prime minister -- who is 
trailing badly in the polls ahead of Monday's election. Netanyahu 
had been lobbying Sharansky to make a declaration of support, 
reportedly offering his Israel B'Aliya party three ministries if he 
did so. 

</P>
