<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Silverbulletday Out of Preakness </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BALTIMORE (AP) -- As he crossed the street and walked toward his  
waiting car, D. Wayne Lukas couldn't help but flash a huge smile. 
</P>
<P>
	The Hall of Fame trainer had just attended the post-position  
draw for Saturday's Preakness, and his Kentucky Derby winner 
Charismatic ended up in a perfect spot -- No. 6 in what is expected 
to end up as a 12-horse field after the filly Silverbulletday was 
withdrawn today and Vicar was expected to be withdrawn Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're in the zone,'' Lukas said Wednesday night. ``I'm tickled  
to death with the draw. Things are falling into place.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Cat Thief, Lukas' other 3-year-old colt, fared well, too, with  
the trainer selecting the No. 3 slot for his third-place Derby 
finisher. 
</P>
<P>
	``I feel great about Charismatic. I think he's peaked at the  
right time,'' Lukas said, even though the Derby winner was the 
third choice at 6-1 in the early-morning line. ``And I expect Cat 
Thief to keep everyone honest. It won't surprise me if he wins.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The biggest jolt was reserved for trainer Bob Baffert, who was  
hoping his star fillies would draw favorable posts. Excellent 
Meeting did and is definitely in; Silverbulletday didn't and is 
definitely out. 
</P>
<P>
	``Silverbulletday will run Friday in the Black-Eyed Susan,''  
Mike Pegram, the filly's owner said today at the Preakness' 
traditional ``alibi breakfast.'' ``I think Bob will be well 
represented in the Derby with Excellent Meeting. We're disappointed 
because we came here to run in the Preakness.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Excellent Meeting, fifth in the Derby after a strong finish,  
drew the No. 7 post, while Silverbulletday, a winner in 10 of 11 
career starts -- none against males -- got the outside No. 14 spot. 
No Preakness winner ever came out of the No. 14 post. 
</P>
<P>
	Silverbulletday drew the rail for the Black-Eyed Susan, and will  
face seven other fillies. Baffert said Wednesday that 
Silverbulletday needed to draw a post from 4-10, or the No. 1 slot 
to get a shot at the boys for the first time. 
</P>
<P>
	``Somebody's trying to tell us not to run,'' Baffert said after  
the draw. ``She's a great filly. The Preakness is a great race. But 
these fillies come around rarely. I have to be careful what I do.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Vicar, who had a rough trip in finishing 18th in the Derby, also  
was expected to be withdrawn by trainer Carl Nafzger. Vicar drew 
the No 13 post, and Nafzger said: ``I will not be starting from the 
No. 13 hole.'' 
</P>
<P>
	With Silverbulletday out of the Preakness, jockey Gary Stevens  
became available and will now ride Stephen Got Even on Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	Menifee, runner-up in the Derby by neck to the 31-1 shot  
Charismatic, was the 5-2 favorite, while Excellent Meeting was next 
at 5-1. 
</P>
<P>
	The expected 12-horse field for the 1 3-16th-mile Preakness  
would include a record nine Derby horses. 
</P>
<P>
	Winning Colors, Lukas' 1988 Derby winner, was the last filly to  
run in the Preakness, finishing third. Four fillies have won the 
Preakness, but none since Nellie Morse in 1924. 
</P>
<P>
	Lukas might have a little history on his side, too, as he shoots  
for his fifth Preakness win -- the No. 6 gate has produced 13 
winners of the second leg of the Triple Crown, the most of any post 
position. 
</P>
<P>
	He's also got the only Triple Crown contender in Charismatic.  
</P>
<P>
	``I've won a Triple Crown, but I needed two horses to do it,''  
Lukas said, referring to 1995, when Thunder Gulch won the Derby and 
Belmont, but stablemate Timber Country took the Preakness. ``Maybe 
one of these days, we'll win all three with one horse.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Charismatic might be the one, even though his reputation suffers  
because he was put in claiming races twice -- the last on Feb. 11 -- 
and could have been purchased for $62,500 after either. 
</P>
<P>
	``I know the story all week will be he's a claimer, and  
everything went his way in the Derby,'' Lukas said. ``But don't 
discredit the horse because I was foolish enough to run him in a 
claiming race.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Charismatic, owned by Bob and Beverly Lewis, might be light on  
victories, but he's the most seasoned Preakness starter of all. 
He'll be racing for the 16th time -- fourth since the Santa Anita 
Derby April 3. 
</P>
<P>
	``He seems to be a two-week horse,'' Lukas said. ``I think he's  
had a little attitude adjustment from the Derby. He's focused. He's 
been laid back all spring. He ran a good Derby, never turned a 
hair. I think he's ready to run.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Preakness draw was handled the same way as the Derby draw --  
a draft order was selected and trainers picked their spots based on 
that order. Baffert had the 13th pick with Silverbulletday and 
Nafzger had the 14th pick. When it came time for them to make their 
picks, they held an impromptu coin toss, and Nafzger won, taking 
the 13th post. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was Bob's idea,'' Nafzger said. ``I ain't that smart.''  
</P>
<P>
	The nine Derby horses running Saturday are Charismatic, Menifee,  
Cat Thief, Excellent Meeting, Kimberlite Pipe, Worldly Manner, 
Stephen Got Even, Valhol and Adonis. The newcomers are Badge, 
Patience Game and Torrid Sand. 
</P>
<P>
	The last Preakness winner who did not run in the Derby was  
Deputed Testamony in 1983. 
</P>
<P>
	The field, from the rail out, is Torrid Sand (Tim Doocy, 60-1);  
Kimberlite Pipe (Shane Sellers, 20-1); Cat Thief (Mike Smith, 8-1); 
Badge (Mike Luzzi, 50-1); Menifee (Pat Day, 5-2); Charismatic 
(Chris Antley, 6-1); Excellent Meeting (Kent Desormeaux, 5-1); 
Patience Game (Corey Nakatani, 30-1); Adonis (Jorge Chavez, 30-1); 
Worldly Manner (Jerry Bailey, 12-1); Stephen Got Even (Gary 
Stevens, 10-1); Valhol (Edgar Prado, 99-1), and Vicar (Robby 
Albarado, 30-1). 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
