<DOCNO> APW19990513.0103 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-13 05:52:46 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> China's Entry to WTO Said On Track </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- The furor in Beijing over NATO's bombing of the  
Chinese Embassy in Yugoslavia should not affect talks on Beijing's 
entry into the World Trade Organization, a top American trade 
official said today. 
</P>
<P>
	``I remain optimistic ... that we can bring China into the WTO  
on a commercially strong basis ... this year,'' U.S. Trade 
Representative Charlene Barshefsky said. 
</P>
<P>
	Barshefsky said bringing China into the world's leading trade  
organizations would be an important step in moving the country 
toward international norms, including the rule of law. 
</P>
<P>
	``We must continue to engage China (despite) whatever  
difficulties, whatever setbacks there are, and bring it toward the 
global community,'' Barshefsky said. 
</P>
<P>
	Barshefsky also it is important to move forward on other  
applications for WTO membership, including those of Taiwan and some 
former Soviet republics. 
</P>
<P>
	The trade representative was in Tokyo for meetings with  
officials from the European Union, Japan and Canada on an upcoming 
round of world trade talks scheduled to begin next year in Seattle, 
Washington. 
</P>
<P>
	NATO's bombing of Beijing's embassy in Belgrade last Friday,  
which killed three Chinese journalists, set off waves of protests 
in China and prompted Beijing to cut off discussions on military 
relations and other affairs with the United States. 
</P>
<P>
	In a speech at the Tokyo American Center, Barshefsky said  
Japan's foot-dragging on implementing trade pacts with the United 
States was fanning tensions between the two countries. 
</P>
<P>
	``On flat glass, autos and auto parts, insurance and government  
procurement, we have serious concerns about implementation of our 
trade agreements,'' she said in a copy of her speech. 
</P>
<P>
	``Full adherence to their spirit and letter is essential to  
trust and progress in the bilateral relationship,'' Barshefsky 
said. ``Failures of implementation lead to rapid erosion of trust 
and rising tension.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Barshefsky pointed to the case of steel, which the U.S.  
government has accused Japanese producers of dumping in the 
American market at below-market prices. 
</P>
<P>
	Japanese steel exports to the United States soared last year,  
and President Clinton has threatened action unless the exports drop 
to pre-1998 levels. 
</P>
<P>
	Turning to the rest of Asia, Barshefsky said Japan should take a  
stronger hand in helping its neighbors recover from the regional 
financial crisis by opening up its markets. 
</P>
<P>
	She said the United States increased its imports of East Asian  
products by $6 billion last year, while Japan's purchases from the 
region fell by $19 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	``Japan, the world's second largest economy, has not played the  
leadership role it should in supporting Asian recovery or in the 
Asia-Pacific Economic Cooperation forum,'' Barshefsky said. 
</P>
<P>
	On the trade talks next year, Barshefsky said the WTO needs to  
be reformed to meet challenges of financial crisis, trade barriers 
and developing countries' access to industrial markets. 
</P>
<P>
	The United States, the EU, Japan and Canada agreed Wednesday to  
try to conclude the upcoming world trade talks in three years, less 
than half the time the last round took. 
</P>
<P>
	But an agreement on how to conduct the round eluded the  
minister-level trade officials. 
</P>
<P>
	Japan and the EU want concurrent negotiations on a sweeping  
range of trade issues, but the United States favors an 
issue-by-issue approach. Canada has proposed a compromise plan of 
grouping together related issues to speed up the Seattle round. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
