<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> CNN Loses Equipment Covering War </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- CNN is taking a financial beating in Yugoslavia,  
estimating that $1.1 million of its equipment has been stolen, 
damaged or destroyed since the NATO bombing began. 
</P>
<P>
	That includes five CNN-owned vehicles and a rental car. The  
single biggest item, a $400,000 satellite transmitter located next 
to the Serb TV facility in Belgrade, was destroyed when NATO bombed 
the building. 
</P>
<P>
	``In CNN's existence of nearly 20 years, we've never encountered  
anything like this,'' said Eason Jordan, CNN's president of 
newsgathering and international networks. ``It's unprecedented for 
us and, as far as I know, it's unprecedented for any news 
organization. And the tally continues.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The losses are on top of the day-to-day expenses of covering the  
conflict, which Jordan estimated were an average of $150,000 per 
day initially. Those costs are now somewhat lower. 
</P>
<P>
	CNN's losses dwarf those of other networks. Executives believe  
CNN is often targeted specifically because the network is seen in 
Yugoslavia. 
</P>
<P>
	A Serbian mob that attacked correspondent Brent Sadler before  
they left Kosovo destroyed or damaged three of the vehicles, a 
camera, a night scope and other equipment worth more than $250,000. 
</P>
<P>
	Authorities have seized CNN equipment at various locations,  
including a hotel in Belgrade, a roadblock in Montenegro, the 
Yugoslavian-Croat border and an Internet work site raided by 
Belgrade police, the network said Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	At one point, Yugoslavian authorities handed a CNN crew a  
receipt for confiscated items. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's not necessarily stolen equipment,'' Jordan said, ``but I  
doubt we will ever see it again.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Serbian authorities ordered journalists from NATO countries out  
when the bombing started, but then allowed many to trickle back in. 
</P>
<P>
	CNN won't talk about security arrangements for its personnel,  
but admit to concern about statements put out by authorities that 
the network is a ``factory of lies'' and that its leaders should be 
put on trial for war crimes, Jordan said. CNN reporter Christopher 
Burns left Yugoslavia in the early days of the attack after the 
network was told his life might be in danger. 
</P>
<P>
	CNN can cover some of its monetary losses through insurance, and  
it often charges higher advertising rates during news crises 
because viewership shoots up. But Jordan was not certain how much 
this would make up for what CNN has lost. 
</P>
<P>
	CBS ``has not lost anything of value,'' spokeswoman Sandra  
Genelius said, with the exception of a mobile uplink machine. ABC 
had some tapes confiscated but, along with NBC, said equipment loss 
hadn't been a problem. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
