<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990513.0106 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-13 13:55:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Reeve Helps California Researchers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Paralyzed star Christopher Reeve believes he  
will someday walk again, but a video of him in a walking motion in 
an experimental therapy session shouldn't be misconstrued. 
</P>
<P>
	The ``Superman'' star was videotaped recently suspended in a  
harness while researchers moved his feet and legs in a walking 
motion on a treadmill. He's participated in research at the 
University of California, Los Angeles, aimed at regenerating nerves 
in the spinal cord. 
</P>
<P>
	Reeve has been paralyzed since 1995 when he was thrown from a  
horse. The video was shared with TV stations on Wednesday, and UCLA 
researchers have been besieged with requests for interviews ever 
since. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's experimental and researchers don't want to give the  
impression Christopher Reeve is going to be walking anytime soon,'' 
said UCLA spokesman Warren Robak. 
</P>
<P>
	Researchers have refused media interviews, saying the research  
is too preliminary and would send the wrong message to others with 
spinal cord injuries, Robak said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
