<HEADLINE> Belo Corp. To Establish Online Unit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DALLAS (AP) -- Media company Belo Corp. has announced plans to  
form an online division and a separate entity for future 
investments. 
</P>
<P>
	The online division will be called Belo Online Inc., giving the  
company, which owns The Dallas Morning News, the ability to combine 
its online operations to better track its financial performance, 
officials said Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dallas-based company also announced plans to form Belo  
Enterprises, which will serve as an investment vehicle for future 
partnerships with Internet and other newspaper and television 
companies. 
</P>
<P>
	``Belo Enterprises will allow us to be flexible and to take  
advantage of opportunities as we can see them,'' said spokesman 
Harold Gaar. 
</P>
<P>
	Executive Vice President James Moroney, 42, will assume the  
additional roles of president of both Belo Online and Belo 
Enterprises. 
</P>
<P>
	Dunia Shive, 38, Belo's senior vice president and chief  
financial officer, will be in charge of the corporation's treasury 
and investor relations operations. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to The Dallas Morning News, Belo owns 16 network  
television stations, six newspapers and four local or regional 
cable channels, including Texas Cable News. 
</P>
</TEXT>
