<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Wesleyan Reviews Pornography Course </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MIDDLETOWN, Conn. (AP) -- The president of Wesleyan University  
has ordered a review of a class that he says may be too liberal for 
the liberal arts college. 
</P>
<P>
	The course, ``Pornography: Writing of Prostitutes,'' examines  
pornography as a cultural and political practice. Its reading list 
includes the Marquis de Sade and academic critiques of Hustler 
magazine. As a final project, students must produce their own work 
of pornography. 
</P>
<P>
	One student in Professor Hope Weissman's class submitted a short  
film that focused on a man's eyes while he masturbated. In another, 
a female student acted out a scene of sexual bondage. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Weissman, a self-described feminist who helped develop the  
women's studies program at the school, told The Hartford Courant 
that she puts no constraints on her students' project ideas. 
</P>
<P>
	``I push people over the line, whatever their line is, but only  
when I think they can go there and come back,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	The projects caught the attention of university President  
Douglas Bennett, who in a memo dated Tuesday and distributed to 
faculty questioned ``the appropriateness of this course in the 
Wesleyan curriculum.'' He ordered a review of the course. 
</P>
<P>
	Brian Edwards-Tiekert, a junior majoring in English and American  
studies, complained the review was spurred by media reports -- and 
not complaints from students or alumni. He said the school is 
sacrificing academic freedom for public image. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's taken the faculty out of the equation,'' Edwards-Tiekert  
said. ``It just seems like a very dangerous trend.'' 
</P>
<P>
	William Holder, a spokesman for Wesleyan, denied that the  
university is compromising academic standards. He said the class 
went through the traditional approval process when it debuted last 
year, but university officials had no way of knowing every aspect 
of the curriculum. 
</P>
<P>
	``By asserting responsibility for the content of our curriculum,  
we are strengthening it,'' Holder said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
