<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Sabres Poised To Eliminate Bruins / Hockey Game Story  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BUFFALO, N.Y. (AP) -- Don't talk to the Boston Bruins about  
pressure. They know all about it. 
</P>
<P>
	``The pressure is on us now and we've been a team that's  
responded to it pretty well throughout the season,'' Boston 
goaltender Byron Dafoe said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Bruins trail the Buffalo Sabres 2-1 in the best-of-7 Eastern  
Conference semifinals, with Game 4 set for Friday night in Buffalo. 
</P>
<P>
	The Bruins say they can handle the pressure of being behind;  
they've done it before. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think we're in a panic situation yet, but the next  
game is the game,'' Bruins captain Ray Bourque said Thursday. 
``We've got to find a way to put them away. We don't want to go 
home down 3-1.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Added coach Pat Burns: ``This is not the end of the world. It's  
not how you get knocked down. It's how you get back up.'' 
</P>
<P>
	For weeks now the Bruins have been bouncing back. They surged to  
make the playoffs. They ousted Carolina after losing two of the 
first three games. 
</P>
<P>
	Now they're faced with an another uphill climb, thanks to their  
3-2 loss to the Sabres on Wednesday night. 
</P>
<P>
	``They've got a lot of fight left in them,'' said Sabres coach  
Lindy Ruff, whose team won Game 3 with forechecking and a barrage 
of shots in the third period. ``They're not going to go away.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Sabres faded in the first two periods Wednesday after  
winning the second game in Boston. But they rediscovered their 
physical game just in time. 
</P>
<P>
	``We just didn't seem like we were fully prepared for it,''  
Sabres defenseman Jay McKee said. ``I don't know why we came out 
that way, but hopefully we can sort it out and come out better 
(Friday).'' 
</P>
<P>
	Dafoe insists he's not intimidated by the guy at the other end  
of the ice, Buffalo's two-time league MVP, Dominik Hasek. But Dafoe 
was shaky in Game 3, often losing the handle on rebounds and losing 
track of teammates. 
</P>
<P>
	``A couple times I had a little miscommunication with my players  
behind the net, and a couple of times we got into a little bit of 
trouble,'' Dafoe said. 
</P>
<P>
	But the Bruins will need a nearly flawless game from Dafoe to  
even the series. 
</P>
<P>
	``When you're going against Dominik Hasek there's extra  
pressure, because you know you're not going to get a lot of goals 
by him,'' Dafoe said. ``But I'm not the one who scores goals on 
Dominik, and all I can do is keep them off the board as long as 
possible.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Dafoe did that for two periods in Game 3. But the Sabres won it  
with two goals in the third. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have to have a better first and second period this time,''  
McKee said. ``Another start like we had the other night could kill 
us. We were lucky.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Sabres have received balanced scoring without their leading  
scorer, injured Mirosalv Satan. Defensemen Jason Woolley and Rhett 
Warrener scored goals in Game 3. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's important to get contributions from everybody and that  
includes the defense,'' said Sabres forward Dixon Ward, who scored 
the winner. ``We're missing Miro, who provided a lot of spark for 
us, and we have to find it somewhere else.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hasek, who stonewalled the Bruins for the final 51 minutes,  
threw a scare into Buffalo's fans when he crumpled to the ice and 
allowed Boston's go-ahead goal by Anson Carter after being struck 
by a slap shot. 
</P>
<P>
	Hasek took Thursday off, but is expected to play Friday.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
