<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Woman Said Shot by Mom Seeks Death </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ORLANDO, Fla. (AP) -- Paralyzed from the neck down by a bullet,  
Georgette Smith wants to die, and if she gets her wish, her mother 
could be charged with her murder. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Smith, 42, is asking a judge to let doctors disconnect the  
ventilator keeping her alive. She was paralyzed after being shot by 
her 68-year-old mother, who apparently got upset after overhearing 
talk of putting her in a nursing home. 
</P>
<P>
	At an emergency hearing Wednesday, Judge Richard Conrad said he  
wants to talk to Ms. Smith in person before deciding whether she 
can compel Lucerne Medical Center to let her die. The judge said he 
will rule next week. 
</P>
<P>
	``All I can do is wink my eyes and wiggle my nose, wiggle my  
tongue. I can't move any other part of my body,'' Ms. Smith said in 
a deposition. ``God, don't leave me this way. ... I can't live like 
this.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Smith's mother, Shirley Egan, is charged with two counts of  
attempted murder and aggravated battery. Prosecutors plan to pursue 
murder charges if Ms. Smith is allowed to die. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Egan's lawyer, Bob Wesley, said Thursday that Ms. Egan is  
confused but understands her daughter wants to be taken off the 
ventilator. He would not elaborate. 
</P>
<P>
	``It certainly was not her intention to shoot her daughter,''  
Wesley said. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Smith and her boyfriend were taking care of Ms. Egan at the  
time of the March 8 shooting. The mother apparently became upset 
after hearing that the two planned to move her to a nursing home. 
She fired at both of them, missing the boyfriend, investigators 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	The bullet entered Ms. Smith's neck and severed her spine. She  
can speak with some effort, but she cannot swallow and needs a 
feeding tube. She has no control over her bladder or bowels and 
will always run a high risk of pneumonia, infections, ulcers and 
bedsores. 
</P>
<P>
	``I want to die because I can't live this way,'' Ms. Smith said  
in the deposition. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Smith's daughters, 22-year-old Candace Smith and 19-year-old  
Joeleen Hill, support their mother's decision to end her life. 
</P>
<P>
	``She's prepared herself because she knows she's lived a good  
life and she doesn't want to finish her life in this way,'' Candace 
Smith said in court Wednesday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
