<DOCNO> APW19990513.0114 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-13 15:42:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Doctor Testifies in Lewis Case </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- The world-renowned cardiologist who told Boston  
Celtics player Reggie Lewis that he suffered from a minor fainting 
disorder conceded Thursday that the player showed signs of heart 
problems before he dropped dead shooting baskets in 1993. 
</P>
<P>
	Dr. Gilbert Mudge, answering questions publicly for the first  
time since the NBA star's death at age 27, testified during his 
malpractice trial that he never discounted the possibility Lewis 
had a potentially fatal heart condition -- even as he told the 
player and the world that Lewis had a less serious neurological 
ailment. 
</P>
<P>
	At least one of Lewis' many tests showed a potential sign of  
``life-threatening arrhythmia,'' Mudge said under intense 
questioning by Robert Harley, a lawyer for the player's widow. 
</P>
<P>
	That was the initial diagnosis of 12 doctors at New England  
Baptist Hospital, where Lewis was taken after he collapsed during a 
playoff game in April 1993. 
</P>
<P>
	The Lewises turned to Mudge at Brigham and Women's Hospital for  
a second opinion, and he initially agreed. But after further tests, 
Mudge revised the diagnosis and told Lewis he had neurocardiogenic 
syncope, a condition that causes fainting spells. 
</P>
<P>
	Three months later, the player died of cardiac arrhythmia while  
practicing jump shots at Brandeis University. 
</P>
<P>
	Donna Harris-Lewis sued Mudge and consultants Mark Creager and  
Peter Friedman, claiming they misdiagnosed and mistreated her 
husband's heart condition. A third consultant later settled for an 
undisclosed amount. 
</P>
<P>
	On Thursday, Harley suggested that Mudge, suddenly in charge of  
care for ``the most famous patient in Boston,'' was under pressure 
to tell Lewis, his wife, the Celtics and the public what they 
wanted to hear: that Lewis' condition was not as serious as first 
believed, and that he would play professional basketball again. 
</P>
<P>
	Mudge did just that during a news conference the day Lewis was  
discharged from Brigham and Women's, and his words came back to 
haunt him Thursday as Harley played a videotape. 
</P>
<P>
	``After extensive testing, evaluation and review of all data, I  
believe that Mr. Lewis has a normal athlete's heart with normal 
functions. Our testing showed no evidence of cardiomyopathy or 
abnormal life-threatening arrhythmias,'' Mudge said during the May 
10, 1993 event. 
</P>
<P>
	Mudge later said, ``I am optimistic that under medical  
supervision Mr. Reggie Lewis will be able to return to professional 
basketball without limitation.'' 
</P>
<P>
	When Harley asked Mudge if he lied during the news conference,  
Mudge replied, ``What I did say was very limited.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier on the witness stand, Mudge insisted he had been  
considering possible cardiac problems and said neurocardiogenic 
syncope -- which is not related to the heart -- was not a 
``definitive diagnosis.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Under questioning by Harley, Mudge said that after discharging  
Lewis, he saw him eight times and physically examined him once. He 
also said Lewis' heart rhythms were monitored for a total of one 
hour, 17 minutes between his discharge and his death 11 weeks 
later. 
</P>
<P>
	In a heated exchange characterisic of Mudge's day-long  
testimony, Harley asked the doctor about Friedman's statements that 
he had shared with Mudge his belief that Lewis suffered from a 
defective heart. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't believe he actually said to me that sentence,'' Mudge  
said. After pressing from Harley, he added, ``He conveyed the 
thought we had to take it seriously.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Absent from Thursday's questioning was the issue of drugs,  
expected to play a central role in the trial. 
</P>
<P>
	Mudge, who runs the cardiac transplantation unit at Brigham and  
Women's, has said Lewis confided in him two weeks before his death 
about cocaine use and that the late admission kept him from making 
an accurate diagnosis. 
</P>
<P>
	Harris-Lewis has denied her husband ever used drugs.  
</P>
<P>
	But Mudge's lawyer has pointed out that such activity would  
threaten insurance and contract money Harris-Lewis received after 
her husband died. 
</P>
<P>
	Harris-Lewis, who lives in the Boston area with her 6-year-old  
son and 5-year-old daughter, is suing to recover money Lewis would 
have made had he lived, estimates of which have ranged from $40 
million to more than $100 million. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
