<HEADLINE> Star-Hub Eyes Singapore </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SINGAPORE (AP) -- International consortium StarHub aims to  
control up to 40 percent of Singapore's corporate and government 
telecommunications markets, an official from the group said today. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'd be very disappointed if we didn't get 30-40 percent of the  
market over three years,'' Graham Moore, StarHub senior vice 
president said at a news conference. 
</P>
<P>
	StarHub's entry into the Singapore market on April 1, 2000, will  
bring an end to powerful Singapore Telecommunications' long 
monopoly on fixed-line telephone services in the wealthy 
city-state. 
</P>
<P>
	Singapore's corporate telecommunications market is estimated to  
be worth more than 1 billion Singapore dollars ($588 million) a 
year. 
</P>
<P>
	StarHub is jointly owned by Singapore's ST Telemedia, Singapore  
Power, British Telecommunications, and Nippon Telegraph and 
Telephone Corp. of Japan. 
</P>
<P>
	StarHub says it has invested more than $235.29 million in  
Singapore to date. 

</P>
</TEXT>
