<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Reps. Want More Border Patrol Agents </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Angered by the administration's failure to  
hire 1,000 new Border Patrol agents this year, as ordered by 
Congress, lawmakers accused President Clinton on Wednesday of 
lacking commitment to border enforcement. 
</P>
<P>
	``Occasionally, in a political speech the president takes credit  
for the progress we've made in expanding the size of the Border 
Patrol,'' said Sen. Phil Gramm, R-Texas. ``But the plain truth is 
that Bill Clinton has never, ever supported this effort, has fought 
us every step of the way, and seems intent to override a clear 
congressional majority that is committed to the principle that we 
ought to gain control of our borders.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gramm and five other border lawmakers appeared at a Capitol news  
conference to release a letter to Clinton signed by a bipartisan 
roster of 61 members of Congress, most from Texas, New Mexico, 
Arizona and California. The lawmakers urged Clinton to work with 
Congress to improve Border Patrol hiring. 
</P>
<P>
	``There is no indication that your border strategy recognizes  
the emergency situation caused by low Border Patrol recruitment and 
high attrition or is animated by any sense of urgency,'' they wrote 
in a letter organized by Rep. Lamar Smith, R-Texas, chairman of 
Judiciary's immigration subcommittee; and Rep. Silvestre Reyes, 
D-Texas. ``The past three months have seen significant 
deterioration, not improvement, in border security.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The White House rejected the criticism.  
</P>
<P>
	``This administration has been the first to take seriously the  
need to control our borders, and we have devoted enormous resources 
to that effort,'' said White House spokesman Barry Toiv. 
</P>
<P>
	For months, congressional Republicans have attacked the White  
House for omitting 1,000 agents in its 2000 budget. In 1996, 
Congress directed the administration to add 1,000 agents in each of 
the next five years. 
</P>
<P>
	The rhetoric has become increasingly harsh in recent weeks as it  
has become clear that the Immigration and Naturalization Service, 
which is the Border Patrol's parent, will fall well short of its 
order to add 1,000 agents this year despite receiving $93 million 
from Congress to do so. 
</P>
<P>
	The Border Patrol's chief, Gus de la Vina, told a Senate panel  
recently that only 200 to 400 agents will be hired this year. He 
blamed the recruitment and retention problems on a tight labor 
market and said the agency is taking new steps to improve hiring. 
</P>
<P>
	But congressional critics contend the INS has done little to  
widen its pool of applicants and has not availed itself of existing 
authority to provide recruitment bonuses and other incentives. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
