<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Penguins' Goalie's Dad Has Cancer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PITTSBURGH (AP) -- Tom Barrasso had more on his mind than  
stopping the Toronto Maple Leafs. The Pittsburgh Penguins goalie 
has learned his father is suffering from brain cancer and the 
outlook is grim. 
</P>
<P>
	Barrasso said tests have disclosed that his father's cancer is  
in an advanced state of malignancy. 
</P>
<P>
	The elder Barrasso, whose first name also is Tom, is undergoing  
treatment in Boston where he lives. 
</P>
<P>
	The Penguins are playing the Toronto Maple Leafs in their  
conference semifinals. 
</P>
<P>
	The cancer was diagnosed after Barrasso's father became ill  
April 23, when the Penguins were in New Jersey for the first round 
of the playoffs. An MRI at St. Barnabas Hospital there revealed a 
mass on the right frontal lobe of his brain. 
</P>
<P>
	The goalie's Barrasso's daughter also has been seriously ill  
with cancer. In 1989, Ashley was 3 years old when she was diagnosed 
with neuroblastoma. Barrasso missed 29 games of the 1989-90 season 
while she was being treated. She is surviving the cancer and lives 
with her parents in suburban Pittsburgh. 
</P>
</TEXT>
