<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-13 21:41:30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Wolverines' Hoop Team Probed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- Federal agents are investigating allegations that  
a now-banned University of Michigan booster made improper payments 
to basketball players, including members of the Fab Five. 
</P>
<P>
	Ed Martin, the booster, also is the target of an investigation  
of illegal gambling at Ford Motor Co. plants that has led to the 
seizure of $150,000, according to the Detroit Free Press, which 
broke the story Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Martin was a target in a 1997 investigation of the Ann Arbor  
school's basketball program. It led to minor NCAA sanctions and the 
firing of coach Steve Fisher. 
</P>
<P>
	``As a result of that investigation, we put in place numerous  
safeguards that we hope have insulated our program from such 
corrupting influences,'' school president Lee Bollinger said 
Thursday in a written statement. 
</P>
<P>
	The current FBI investigation involves possible improper  
payments to players going back ``many years,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Obviously, if this turns out to be true, it is extremely  
embarrassing to the university,'' the president said. ``We have 
been told by the FBI that the investigation to date does not 
implicate or involve our current coaching staff and does not 
suggest any gambling or improper activity related to athletic 
games.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A federal grand jury in Detroit has issued subpoenas to former  
players and others, the Detroit Free Press reported in Friday 
editions, quoting people familiar with the case. 
</P>
<P>
	Wiretaps on Martin recorded conversations with several former  
Wolverines basketball players, including Chris Webber, Louis 
Bullock, Robert Traylor and Maurice Taylor, the Free Press reported 
an unidentified person close to the investigation as saying. 
</P>
<P>
	Those recordings provided the basis for search warrants executed  
last month on Martin and nine other homes and one office, the 
source said. 
</P>
<P>
	``It involved very large amounts of money, and it may end up  
that a current player or two had taken money,'' an unidentified 
source told the Free Press. ``It started with the Fab Five and 
reaches major proportions.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Agents for the players are saying little.  
</P>
<P>
	``There is a grand jury going on,'' said L. Fallasha Erwin, an  
attorney and agent for former Fab Five star Webber, who now plays 
for the NBA's Sacramento Kings. 
</P>
<P>
	Asked whether Webber had been subpoenaed or interviewed by the  
FBI, Erwin said only that Webber would cooperate with the 
investigation. 
</P>
<P>
	Other players who are coming under scrutiny, the Free Press  
sources said, include Taylor, Traylor, Bullock and Jalen Rose. 
</P>
<P>
	In previous interviews, Traylor has denied accepting money from  
Martin. 
</P>
<P>
	When reached at his parents' Maryland home, Bullock said of the  
suspected payments to players: ``I didn't have anything to do with 
it.'' He said he had not been interviewed by federal agents or, 
apparently, subpoenaed to appear before the grand jury. 
</P>
<P>
	As for Martin, Bullock said: ``I never accepted anything from  
him. That's all you need to write. My parents are well off. We've 
never taken anything from him; we've never needed anything from 
him.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bollinger said the university ``will follow this investigation  
carefully and will do everything we can to find out what has 
happened and what needs to be done further to ensure that Michigan 
sports meet the highest standards of integrity all Michigan fans 
expect of us.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Athletic director Tom Goss, who took over after the 1997 probe,  
said the Wolverines have taken strong steps in the past two years 
to shield athletes from Martin. 
</P>
<P>
	University officials did not say whether the school was  
conducting its own investigation of possible NCAA rules violations. 
</P>
<P>
	The NCAA is aware of the allegations, spokeswoman Jane Jankowski  
said Thursday from its Mission, Kan., headquarters. 
</P>
<P>
	The FBI, IRS and federal prosecutors in Detroit also would not  
discuss the investigation. 
</P>
<P>
	According to the Free Press, FBI and IRS agents investigating a  
possible numbers operation at Detroit-area area Ford plants 
searched Martin's house on April 28. Authorities later searched an 
office and nine other houses, ultimately confiscating more than 
$150,000 cash. 
</P>
<P>
	In a story Friday, The Detroit News quoted law enforcers,  
eyewitnesses and Ford officials as alleging that Martin has run a 
lottery-style gambling ring at the Ford Rouge Complex's engine 
plant for more than a decade. 
</P>
<P>
	None of the workers or investigators indicated Martin's gambling  
activities involved college sports, the News reported. 
</P>
<P>
	Martin's lawyer, Neil Fink, said, ``I am confident that my  
clients will be exonerated.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In October 1997, Goss fired Fisher after a school investigation  
found three rules violations between September 1994 and Feb. 17, 
1996, all involving Martin and deemed ``minor'' by the school and 
the NCAA. 
</P>
<P>
	The NCAA said Martin was present during a home visit by Fisher  
to then-recruit Traylor and provided Traylor and his grandmother 
with food totaling $80.50. Martin also provided transportation for 
Traylor's grandmother to high school games and, later, Michigan 
games. 


</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
