<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Soybeans Fall; Grains Rise a Bit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Soybean futures fell sharply Thursday on the  
Chicago Board of Trade as soybean oil prices plunged. Grain futures 
edged higher amid signs the export outlook for corn and wheat is 
improving. 
</P>
<P>
	Soybeans fell in step with sharply declining soybean oil values.  
That complex was pressured by a steep drop in competing Malaysian 
palm oil prices, which indicated that demand for vegetable oils on 
the world market is waning. 
</P>
<P>
	Corn futures rose after the U.S. Agriculture Department reported  
corn exports last week of 1.336 million metric tons, the fifth 
consecutive week that sales have topped 1 million metric tons. The 
unexpectedly strong demand has raised expectations the government 
will boost annual export projections and lower estimates for ending 
stocks. 
</P>
<P>
	Corn also was supported by continued rains across Midwest  
growing regions, which was delaying fieldwork as time runs out for 
getting crops into the ground. Gains were trimmed late, however, on 
the weakness in the soybean market. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat futures advanced after the USDA reported weekly exports of  
436,400 metric tons for the current and upcoming marketing year. 
The combined total came in above expectations and lent support to 
ideas that Asian demand may be on the rise. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat also saw continued support from the government projections  
that the winter wheat crop will be far smaller than last year's. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat for July delivery was unchanged at $2.70 1/2 a bushel; July  
corn rose 3/4 cent to $2.24 a bushel; July oats fell 3/4 cent to $1.25 1/4 
a bushel; July soybeans fell 5 1/2 cents to $4.69 3/4 a bushel. 
</P>
<P>
	Live cattle and pork bellies futures advanced on the Chicago  
Mercantile Exchange. Feeder cattle retreated, while lean hogs 
finished mixed. 
</P>
<P>
	June live cattle rose .30 cent to 61.40 cents a pound; August  
feeder cattle fell .42 cent to 72.50 cents a pound; June lean hogs 
rose .20 cent to 60.05 cents a pound; July pork bellies rose .07 
cent to 59.02 cents a pound. 
</P>
</TEXT>
