<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Univ. of Chicago Courses Go Online </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- The University of Chicago will soon become one of  
the first major universities to offer business courses to corporate 
managers via the Internet, according to a report in today's Chicago 
Tribune. 
</P>
<P>
	Citing the potential to gain revenue of at least $20 million in  
the next five years, university officials say they will soon sign a 
contract with UNEXT.com, a Deerfield-based online education firm. 
</P>
<P>
	The plan calls for professors from the university's graduate  
business school and potentially the Graham School of General 
Studies and the university's Little Red Schoolhouse writing 
programs to develop courses that would be sold to companies to use 
for employee training. 
</P>
<P>
	UNEXT also hopes to eventually offer certificates and perhaps  
even degree programs, said Edwin Eisendrath, a former Chicago 
alderman and federal housing official who is UNEXT's deputy chief 
operating officer. 
</P>
<P>
	Columbia University recently became the first to sign with  
UNEXT. Other top-flight universities -- including Stanford, Cornell 
and Harvard -- also are considering offering their courses using 
commercial vendors. 
</P>
<P>
	The University of Chicago deal is not without its critics, who  
fear a conflict of interest between the venture and U of C faculty 
and board members. 
</P>
<P>
	UNEXT is headed by Andrew Rosenfield, a university trustee, and  
funded in part by a corporate affiliate of felon financier Michael 
Milken. Rosenfield recently sold the economic consulting firm 
Lexecon Inc. to Milken's education company, Knowledge Universe. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition, the university's law school dean, Daniel Fischel,  
is an investor in UNEXT and, by coincidence, wrote the book 
``Payback: The Conspiracy to Destroy Michael Milken and His 
Financial Revolution.'' Gary Becker and Merton Miller, both 
University of Chicago economists, also have financial interests in 
UNEXT. 
</P>
<P>
	Some faculty members say Rosenfield's dual roles, in particular,  
represent a conflict of interest. 
</P>
<P>
	``My view is that it is unhealthy for members of the board of  
trustees to profit from being board members,'' said Richard 
Shweder, a member of the Council of the University Senate, the 
faculty governing body to which the administration recently 
presented the pending deal. 
</P>
<P>
	``And the more people there are on the faculty who are involved  
in the deal, the more entangled we become in an arrangement that 
will be very difficult to get out of,'' he added. 
</P>
<P>
	Critics also note that maintaining a Web site would take some  
top faculty members away from students on campus. 
</P>
<P>
	University officials say they would expect full disclosure of  
financial interests from trustees and faculty members to avoid 
conflict-of-interest problems. They also say they simply can't 
ignore the potential for profit, especially if other big 
universities get into the online game. 
</P>
<P>
	``For us, this is a defensive measure,'' said Geoffrey Stone, U  
of C provost. ``If we didn't get involved with something that's 
likely to become part of higher education's future, we could be at 
a big disadvantage.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Then there's the question of who has rights to the material  
provided on the Web -- and, thus, the profits. 
</P>
<P>
	At Princeton University, a discussion of whether professors  
should have exclusive rights to material they produce on the Web 
has led to a pending written policy. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think some professors are cognizant of the potential to make  
a significant amount of money from these projects,'' said Mary 
Caffrey, a Princeton spokeswoman. 
</P>
<P>
	Eisendrath said Rosenfield would not be available for comment  
about the University of Chicago deal or plans for UNEXT. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
