<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Redskins' Westbrook Breaks Silence </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ASHBURN, Va. (AP) -- In his first full news conference since his  
bloody attack on teammate Stephen Davis 19 months ago, Washington 
Redskins receiver Michael Westbrook compared the beating to a 
``hockey fight'' and said he did not need counseling for it. 
</P>
<P>
	``Hockey players have fights every day, all day,'' Westbrook  
said Thursday. ``What did I need counseling for? Because I had a 
fight?'' 
</P>
<P>
	Westbrook also explained his decision to resume talking to the  
media. Except for an appearance on teammate Brian Mitchell's talk 
show on WTEM-AM last season and an interview on WJLA-TV earlier 
this week, he has virtually ignored reporters since the Aug. 19, 
1997, attack on Davis. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm just tired of playing the little childish games that you  
all have been playing with me and I've been playing with you,'' 
Westbrook said. ``It's time for all of us to grow up. It's time to 
be more mature in that aspect of that life.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Westbrook said he stopped talking to the press because he felt  
the Davis matter was blown out of proportion. The Redskins fined 
Westbrook $50,000 for attack, suspended him for one exhibition 
game, told him to apologize and ordered him to undergo counseling. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was more so to please the public,'' Westbrook said of the  
counseling. ``I don't think anything was mentally wrong with me, 
and I'm the still the great friend to my friends and great family 
member to my family members and a respectable human being to people 
that just walk past me every day. 
</P>
<P>
	``The fight itself shouldn't have happened. After it happened, I  
don't think the media should have ran with it the way it did. It 
sold papers, but it made my fans and family miserable, and I 
thought that was a bigger price to pay than the $50,000.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Westbrook would not say what provoked him to hit Davis, who  
threw no punches but took several and was left face down with a 
bloody nose. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's strictly between me and Stephen,'' Westbrook said. ``We  
had a fight, and it was for a reason. I apologized to him. We sat 
down and talked since, and we're really good friends now.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Since he was selected No. 4 overall in the 1995 draft, Westbrook  
has been suspended twice, fined twice and benched three times for 
various infractions on and off the field. He has missed 16 games 
due to injuries. 
</P>
<P>
	Last year, he was enjoying his best season -- 44 catches, 736  
yards -- before suffering a neck injury Dec. 6 against San Diego. He 
had surgery in January is expected to fully recover. 
</P>
<P>
	When healthy, Westbrook has been criticized by coaches for  
running bad pass routes and for his lax work ethic. Westbrook 
offered other explanations for his disappointing numbers. 
</P>
<P>
	``The offensive line hasn't been healthy. I haven't been  
healthy,'' he said. ``The quarterbacks didn't know if they wanted 
to play quarterback or not. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think that I've done the best that I can do on the field  
when the opportunity has presented itself. ... If I can just play 
16 games. Judge me on 16 games, 16 healthy games.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
