<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dollar Falls Against Euro </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The dollar fell against the euro and other major  
Western currencies Thursday as a faint possibility of peace in 
Kosovo emerged with the partial withdrawal of Yugoslav troops. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar's lone increase against major currencies occurred  
against the yen as an International Monetary Fund official 
discounted Japan's ability to quickly recover from its recession. 
</P>
<P>
	The euro was quoted at $1.0660 in late trading in New York, up  
from $1.0653 late Wednesday. Also, the dollar was quoted at 1.5027 
Swiss francs, down from 1.5056, and 1.4583 Canadian dollars, down 
from 1.4592. The British pound rose to $1.6205 from $1.6176. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, the dollar rose to 121.85 Japanese yen from 120.95  
yen. 
</P>
<P>
	Traders bought major Western currencies and sold the U.S.  
dollar, traditionally seen as a safe haven, as Yugoslav troops 
began leaving Kosovo. The televised withdrawal followed a Yugoslav 
army withdrawal order Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar fell even though Western authorities said the troop  
movement possibly was a sham to counter disbelief over Sunday's 
withdrawal order. 
</P>
<P>
	But the euro is the currency of 11 European countries that are  
expected to bear the brunt of rebuilding Yugoslavia once the NATO 
airstrikes cease the pounding that started at the end of March. The 
bill increases each time another building is bombed, so the euro 
rises at each whiff of the conflict ceasing. 
</P>
<P>
	``The euro's strength against the dollar was in response to  
increasing prospects for a Yugoslavian troop withdrawal,'' said Jim 
Collins, a currency futures analyst at Salomon Smith Barney Inc.'s 
Chicago office. Trading in Europe, however, was light with most of 
the continent closed for Ascension Day. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar's rise against the yen began during Asian trading  
when IMF deputy director for research Flemming Larsen warned 
reporters in Tokyo that the worst parts of Japan's recession may 
not be over and it could take years of massive stimulus spending 
for the economy to recover. 
</P>
<P>
	That counters recent reports from Japanese officials that  
Japan's worst recession since World War II had seemed to hit 
bottom. 
</P>
<P>
	Currencies of the euro countries are no longer traded separately  
and are tied to the euro by a fixed rate. 
</P>
<P>
	Based on the euro's exchange rate, the dollar was worth: 1.8349  
German marks, down from 1.8359; 6.1538 French francs, down from 
6.1576; and 1,814.88 Italian lire, down from 1,818.18. 
</P>
</TEXT>
