<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Religious Groups Endorse FCC Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Religious organizations endorsed a Federal  
Communications Commission plan Thursday to create a new very local 
radio service that could be used by churches, students and 
community groups. 
</P>
<P>
	FCC Chairman Bill Kennard has been building grass-roots support  
for his plan, which the broadcasting industry and some key 
Republican telecommunications lawmakers oppose. 
</P>
<P>
	The proposal would create thousands of licensed low-tech FM  
radio stations from 1 watt to 1,000 watts. It would reverse a 
roughly 20-year-old ban against such licenses. 
</P>
<P>
	Opponents fear that the low-power service would create  
interference to existing FM radio broadcasts and jeopardize plans 
for the radio industry to switch to higher-quality digital 
technology. 
</P>
<P>
	But representatives from the National Council of Churches of  
Christ, the United Church of Christ and U.S. Catholic Conference 
said it would be a low-cost way to give churches and minorities a 
voice on the airwaves. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have fought for this for nearly 50 years,'' said Rev.  
Everett Parker of the United Church of Christ. 
</P>
<P>
	``There is a crying need for people to be able to get accurate,  
unbiased news and information about their localities,'' said Rev. 
Joan Campbell, general secretary to the National Council of 
Churches. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
