<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> RJR Spinoff Pension Plan Augmented </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The federal pension insurance agency announced  
an agreement Wednesday with RJR Nabisco for protecting underfunded 
pensions of its spinoff tobacco company. 
</P>
<P>
	The Pension Benefit Guaranty Corp. said the pension plan  
covering both Nabisco and R.J. Reynolds Tobacco employees will be 
split into two plans when the spinoff is finalized. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the agreement, the new RJR Reynolds Tobacco will provide  
more than $400 million of financial protection for the plan 
covering about 21,000 tobacco workers and retirees. The PBGC said 
that plan otherwise would be underfunded by nearly $500 million. 
</P>
<P>
	RJR Nabisco announced in March its intention to spin off its  
U.S. cigarette business from its food interests after selling its 
international tobacco business for nearly $8 billion to Japan 
Tobacco Inc. The international tobacco sale was completed 
Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The spinoff of the domestic tobacco business, which makes  
Winston, Camel and Salem cigarettes, is expected to be completed by 
June 15. 
</P>
<P>
	PBGC is a federal agency created by Congress in 1974 to  
guarantee payment of basic pension benefits earned by some 42 
million workers and retirees. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
