<DOCNO> APW19990513.0152 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-13 05:59:49 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Sponsor: Public Wary on Olympics </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SALT LAKE CITY (AP) -- A survey for Olympics sponsor John Hancock  
concluded that public confidence in the sponsors dropped 
dramatically since the Salt Lake City bribery scandal. 
</P>
<P>
	``Phooey,'' responded Salt Lake Olympics chief Mitt Romney.  
</P>
<P>
	The Hancock survey of 500 people found 20 percent ``have now  
lost faith in not only the Olympics but in the companies that 
sponsor the Olympics and their products,'' company President David 
D'Alessandro said Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Romney, meanwhile, cited surveys made for the U.S. Olympic  
Committee. 
</P>
<P>
	About two-thirds of the 1,000 respondents consistently have said  
their feelings for Olympic sponsors have not changed, and 11 
percent said they were even more supportive of sponsors. The 
Hancock survey found only 3 percent to 4 percent said they were 
more likely to buy an Olympic sponsor's product. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a case of dueling polls,'' Romney said. ``And in my  
view the duel was decided when General Motors voted with their 
dollars.'' 
</P>
<P>
	On Tuesday, General Motors Corp. said it wasn't letting the  
scandal stand in the way of its $1 billion Olympics marketing 
campaign. 
</P>
<P>
	D'Alessandro said the figure in the Hancock poll indicating only  
3 percent to 4 percent were more likely to buy a sponsor's product 
was down dramatically from surveys taken after the 1998 Nagano 
Games. Those surveys found 30 percent were more likely to buy a 
company's products because of its Olympic association. 
</P>
<P>
	``When you put $40 million into this type of venture, you don't  
expect it to go the other way on you. You're spending money to club 
yourself over the head,'' D'Alessandro said. John Hancock paid $40 
million for a Sydney sponsorship. 
</P>
<P>
	John Krimsky, who recently announced he was resigning as USOC's  
marketing chief, said D'Alessandro ``exaggerated some very narrowly 
focused data that he and only he is privy to. It's inaccurate, and 
it's done to further his position, which has been to chill the 
Olympic sponsorship market.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Asked why D'Alessandro would purposely devalue a cause his  
company supports -- Krimsky told The Salt Lake Tribune, ``To get his 
name back on the front page.'' 
</P>
<P>
	D'Alessandro has removed the Olympic symbols from company  
stationery, billboards and its annual report. John Hancock also 
canceled negotiations for $20 million in Olympic television ads. 
</P>
<P>
	Romney predicted the company's attitude would thaw in the coming  
months. 
</P>
<P>
	``My bet is he will end up supporting the athletes and the Salt  
Lake Games when all this is over,'' Romney said. ``He has a beef 
with the IOC, not with Salt Lake and not with the Olympics.'' 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990513.0153 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-13 18:05:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Rangers' Gonzalez May Be Put on DL </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ARLINGTON, Texas (AP) -- Juan Gonzalez's most recent home run  
could land him on the disabled list. 
</P>
<P>
	The reigning AL MVP was out of the Texas Rangers' lineup  
Thursday night against Baltimore and could miss several more games 
because of a strained right hamstring suffered while hitting a home 
run Tuesday night. 
</P>
<P>
	Gonzalez left the game in Chicago after the fourth-inning homer  
and got the day off Wednesday because of a rainout. When he arrived 
at The Ballpark on Thursday, Gonzalez still wasn't comfortable 
enough to play. 
</P>
<P>
	``Juan is feeling a little better, but he's a little bit sore,''  
Rangers trainer Danny Wheat said. ``We're looking at three to five 
days (off). Then when Juan tell us he can go, he's going to go.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Texas manager Johnny Oates said the team won't consider putting  
Gonzalez on the DL before next Friday's game in Baltimore. Until 
then, the Rangers have four games against Baltimore and three 
against Tampa Bay, all at home. 
</P>
<P>
	``If we have to go this homestand without him, we do,'' Oates  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Ivan Rodriguez moved into Gonzalez's cleanup spot from No. 6 and  
Roberto Kelly started in right field. Second baseman Mark McLemore 
became the team's only reserve outfielder. 
</P>
<P>
	The Rangers don't have the luxury of using Gonzalez as the  
designated hitter because Rafael Palmeiro, who has been there all 
but once this season, is recovering from two knee operations and 
has yet to play in the field. If necessary, Palmeiro could play 
first and Lee Stevens could move to the outfield. Stevens played 
seven games there last year and 22 games in 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	Texas isn't anxious to put Gonzalez on the DL because the  
obvious move would be to recall top propect Ruben Mateo. Although 
Mateo is probably ready to hit big-league pitching, the team is 
adamant about wanting him to play a full season at Triple-A. 
</P>
<P>
	Should Gonzalez have to go on the DL, it might not be for very  
long. 
</P>
<P>
	If the Rangers don't make the move until next Friday and make it  
retroactive to Wednesday, he'd be eligible to return May 28 at home 
against Minnesota after missing only six games. 
</P>
<P>
	Gonzalez, who has been on the DL each of the last three seasons,  
had played the first 33 games this year and 77 straight since last 
August. 
</P>
<P>
	Gonzalez had been hot lately, going 7-for-11 over his last three  
games to raise his average to .323. Going into Thursday's games, he 
was tied for ninth in the AL with eight homers and fifth with 29 
RBIs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990513.0154 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-13 22:41:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Former Richmond Mayor Sentenced </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	RICHMOND, Va. (AP) -- Former mayor Leonidas B. Young has been  
sentenced to two years in federal prison for obstruction of 
justice, filing a false tax return and two counts of mail fraud. 
</P>
<P>
	Assistant U.S. Attorney James B. Comey recommended a light  
sentence because Young is cooperating in a continuing investigation 
of criminal activity in Richmond. Young could have received up to 
23 years in prison. 
</P>
<P>
	``My presence here today is a result of my own personal  
misjudgment and, I shudder to say, stupidity,'' Young said 
Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	A Baptist pastor who held public office in Richmond for seven  
years, Young was indicted last fall on 19 felony counts. 
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutors said Young peddled influence during his term as  
mayor and defrauded members of his Fourth Baptist Church 
congregation to support extramarital liaisons. 
</P>
<P>
	He pleaded guilty to four counts in a plea agreement Feb. 1.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
