<DOCNO> APW19990513.0155 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-13 16:41:32 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Giants' Safety Out To Prove Himself </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. (AP) -- While most of his buddies were  
talking about old times, learning new plays and seemingly enjoying 
themselves during the New York Giants minicamp this week, safety 
Percy Ellsworth was kicking things. 
</P>
<P>
	Every time he failed to pick off a pass in his zone, dropped one  
or got beat on a play, something got booted -- the ball, a sideline 
marker, whatever. 
</P>
<P>
	Call it a product of the NFL marketplace.  
</P>
<P>
	Ellsworth went there in the offseason and it really didn't treat  
him right. Despite sharing the team lead over the last three 
seasons with 12 interceptions, the safety who started nine of 16 
games last season wasn't able to land a big contract for his fourth 
season. 
</P>
<P>
	So he is stuck with the offer extended by the Giants after last  
season -- one-year tender for $429,000, the league minimum. 
</P>
<P>
	The offer gave Ellsworth the right to test free agency, but also  
gave the Giants the right of first refusal on any deal he signed. 
</P>
<P>
	Some teams offered a little more money, but no one came through  
with big bucks. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was really, really upset at first,'' Ellsworth said Thursday  
as the Giants finished a three-day minicamp. ``It was more anger 
than disappointment. But over time, and after talking to different 
teams and hearing what they felt like, I'm not really at peace, but 
close.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A generally easygoing guy on the field, Ellsworth seemed more  
intense during the minicamp. Not only is he looking to win one of 
the starting jobs at safety, he also wants to put up big numbers 
this year on the field. 
</P>
<P>
	``Most of the people interested in me let me know they would  
still be watching all year long,'' said Ellsworth, who earned a 
spot on the Giants as a free agent in 1996. ``I feel better now 
that I've had a chance to talk to some people. It eased my mind. At 
first, I thought: `Nobody wants me. What's wrong?''' 
</P>
<P>
	Most of the teams that expressed an interest in Ellsworth said  
they liked what they saw, but would have been more willing to offer 
him a big contract had he played more. 
</P>
<P>
	Giants coach Jim Fassel can understand Ellsworth's frustration,  
but he said the former Virginia product has worked hard instead of 
sulking. 
</P>
<P>
	``Percy is a competitor. He doesn't take a back (seat) to  
anyone,'' Fassel said. 
</P>
<P>
	Ellsworth's chances of moving into the starting lineup aren't  
bad with Tito Wooten coming off a sub-par season and in danger of 
being a salary-cap victim next month. If that happened, Ellsworth 
and Shaun Williams, the Giants' 1998 first-round draft pick, would 
compete for the starting spot. 
</P>
<P>
	After next season, Ellsworth will be an unrestricted free agent  
if the Giants don't re-sign him by Feb. 15. 
</P>
<P>
	``I just didn't want to leave for the sake of leaving,''  
Ellsworth said. ``I have a lot of friends and love the city. I just 
want to do all I can to help the team win and I'll see what 
happens.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990513.0156 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-13 21:51:38 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Payton Might Leave Seattle </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SEATTLE (AP) -- Gary Payton is unhappy that his Seattle  
SuperSonics are on the outside looking in at the NBA playoffs. But 
he says he's made no trade demand should the team not improve next 
season. 
</P>
<P>
	``They didn't hear me say that. Nobody's heard me say that,''  
Payton said Thursday night from Atlanta, where he was an analyst 
for coverage of NBA playoff games on TNT and TBS. 
</P>
<P>
	Payton was reacting to reports that the Seattle Times quoted him  
as saying he would demand a trade if the Sonics don't improve next 
year. 
</P>
<P>
	``All I said was we had to make some changes,'' Payton said.  
</P>
<P>
	``I don't really deal with the media anymore. It's all crazy and  
they say what they want to say,'' Payton said. ``If I wanted a 
trade, I would have had a news conference and said I wanted to be 
traded.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``We have the comments on tape. The quotes are accurate,'' Don  
Shelton, assistant sports editor of The Seattle Times, said. ``We 
don't know how the Times' story was characterized to Payton but 
we're confident that when he sees his comments in context he'll 
realize the Times' story was fair and accurate.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In the Times story, Payton said he plans to meet soon with team  
president and general manager Wally Walker. 
</P>
<P>
	``If you don't want to listen, then get me out of here,'' Payton  
said he would tell Walker. ``If things don't improve, I'm done with 
it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Payton averaged 21.7 points -- the second-best mark of his  
nine-year NBA career -- this season, but the Sonics missed the 
playoffs with a 25-25 record. He helped the Sonics reach the NBA 
Finals three years ago. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've had articles written about me, saying I'm a joke for  
this, a joke for that,'' Payton told the newspaper. ``Take me off 
this team and we'll see what the joke is. People are blaming me -- 
as always.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Later Thursday, Payton said acting as an analyst while other  
teams play for the NBA title was ``weird.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Things happen,'' Payton said. ``You can't stop playing  
basketball or stop living. You do everything possible next year to 
make sure it doesn't happen again. 
</P>
<P>
	``We should be fine (next season). I'm not worried as long as it  
doesn't become a repeat thing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Payton was chosen to the NBA All-Defensive team for the sixth  
time Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	In the newspaper story, Payton said he wants Walker and Sonics  
owner Barry Ackerley to make major improvements to the Sonics in a 
hurry. He plans to become more vocal in the future. He thinks he's 
earned that right. 
</P>
<P>
	``Fans know ... I've been good to Seattle, good to my  
teammates,'' Payton said. ``I've never said anything negative. I've 
been keeping quiet, trying to be the good guy, and it's backfired 
on me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Payton was upset about the makeup of this season's Seattle team.  
He said the players openly bickered more than any other team he's 
played for with the Sonics. 
</P>
<P>
	He said he was unfairly pinpointed as the team malcontent after  
a practice blowup with Vin Baker and an outburst in Portland. He 
said both were overblown. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm the only one who doesn't complain,'' he said. ``I just  
come into the locker room, and I don't talk to the media. If I say 
the wrong thing, they'll put it in the papers and say I'm 
complaining about it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Payton met with Walker after last season, but didn't make any  
specific demands. He will be specific this time. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm only going to be around for four or five more years and I  
want to win,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	According to Payton, the Sonics' biggest needs are a backup  
point guard, another shooter and a competent big man. 
</P>
<P>
	Payton wants his friend, Baker, to return. Baker and Payton have  
the same representatives, brothers Aaron and Eric Goodwin. 
</P>
<P>
	Baker, who had a subpar season, averaging 13.8 points, is  
expected to opt to become a free agent. If the Sonics are to keep 
him, they might have to offer him a maximum contract of $87 million 
for seven seasons. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990513.0157 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-13 13:55:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Lands' End Profits Increase </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DODGEVILLE, Wis. (AP) -- Catalog and Internet retailer Lands' End  
reported a 6 percent gain in first-quarter earnings from a year 
ago, boosted by strong sales from the liquidation of its Willis &AMP; 
Geiger outdoor-clothing catalog. 
</P>
<P>
	Lands' End earnings from continuing operations were $5.7  
million, or 18 cents a share, for the quarter ended April 30, 
compared with $5.2 million, or 17 cents a share, in the same period 
a year ago. 
</P>
<P>
	The results topped Wall Street analysts' estimates. Lands' End  
stock was up $3.68 3/4 at $42 on the New York Stock Exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	Sales for the quarter were $289.6 million, up from $268.6  
million a year ago. 
</P>
<P>
	The company said that sales growth came primarily from increased  
liquidations, about half of which was from the liquidation of the 
Willis &AMP; Geiger catalog. The closing was part of a restructuring 
plan put in place earlier this year to cut costs and boost profits. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition, the company's specialty business segment,  
represented by the kids, corporate sales and Coming Home catalogs 
showed strong growth. Internet sales were also solid. 
</P>
<P>
	But Lands' End said that sales at its core catalog, which is  
about 60 percent of its total business, remains weak. 
</P>
<P>
	Net income for the first quarter was $6.5 million, or 21 cents a  
share, including a gain of $800,000, or 3 cents, for reversing part 
of a previous charge for Willis &AMP; Geiger's closing. The reversal 
was because liquidation sales at the unit were better than 
expected. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990513.0158 </DOCNO>
