<DOCNO> APW19990513.0160 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-13 19:21:39 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AMA Says Doctors' Income Declining </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- The median income for the nation's doctors  
declined for the fourth consecutive year in 1997, in part because 
of managed care, according to a survey released Thursday by the 
American Medical Association. 
</P>
<P>
	However, last year the AMA said doctors' average income was on  
the rise. The group refused to release the average figure this 
year. 
</P>
<P>
	The median income in 1997 was $164,000, meaning half the  
physicians surveyed earned more than that and half earned less. The 
median income the year before was $166,000, the AMA said. 
</P>
<P>
	The AMA gathered its information in a telephone survey last year  
of 4,000 doctors. It said the numbers show median net income has 
fallen 1.4 percent each year since 1993 when adjusted for 
inflation. 
</P>
<P>
	``The median income figure is the best representative number,''  
said AMA spokesman Robert Mills. ``The mean figure is artificially 
high because the doctors who make a million dollars a year really 
skew the overall number when you consider that there are many 
doctors who make way less.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Dr. Joel Shalowitz, director of the health services management  
program at Northwestern University's business school, said earnings 
are suffering because managed care firms are forcing doctors to 
justify services and negotiate fees. 
</P>
<P>
	``For example, the allowable reimbursement for cataract surgery  
went from $1,500 to $1,600 down to $900 over the past decade,'' 
Shalowitz said. 
</P>
<P>
	Dr. James Foody, a professor at the University of Chicago  
medical school, said salaries have also decreased at teaching 
hospitals. 
</P>
<P>
	``We haven't increased starting salaries in internal medicine  
for the last four years,'' Foody said. 
</P>
<P>
	According to another AMA survey done more recently, physicians  
worked a median of 48 hours a week in 1998, down from 56 in 1997. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990513.0161 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-13 00:22:57 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Star Wars Tickets Go On Sale </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- The Force was kind to those who waited.  
</P>
<P>
	Advance tickets for the first ``Stars Wars'' movie since 1983  
went on sale Wednesday amid a frenzied demand matched only by the 
film's hype. And ``Star Wars: Episode I -- The Phantom Menace,'' a 
prequel to the earlier George Lucas trilogy, doesn't even open 
until May 19. 
</P>
<P>
	That didn't stop fans across the country from putting up with  
driving rain, long lines, busy signals and clogged Web sites to 
become the first to buy tickets. 
</P>
<P>
	After waiting a week in line -- and enduring the barbs of passing  
hecklers -- Johnny Shipman's faithfulness paid off: The 25-year-old 
welder was the first to buy tickets at a theater in Augusta, Ga. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was just intense,'' Shipman said. ``Cameras all in front of  
me, news crews and everything ... It was more than I expected.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Despite the film's early mixed reviews, tickets to the debut  
showings sold out within minutes and fans scrambled to get seats 
for later dates. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've been waiting 16 years for this,'' said Lee Dahlhauser,  
who bought the first tickets sold in Ames, Iowa, after spending all 
night in line in a driving rain covered with blankets and sheets of 
plastic. 
</P>
<P>
	Director-producer George Lucas initially barred advanced ticket  
sales to prevent scalping, but relented under pressure from theater 
owners. In a compromise, theaters restricted sales to a maximum of 
12 tickets per person. 
</P>
<P>
	There were no early reports of scalping problems -- just  
thousands of fans eager to get tickets. 
</P>
<P>
	At Mann's Chinese Theatre in Hollywood, where the original  
``Star Wars'' premiered in 1977 -- and where fans have been camping 
out for weeks -- the line stretched along Hollywood Boulevard, down 
a side street and to the next block over. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's important we see it on opening day at Mann's Chinese  
Theatre,'' explained Susanna Modjallal, 30. ``If Lucas thought it 
was good enough to premiere here, it's good enough for me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In Baltimore, the crowd outside the Senator Theater was three  
blocks long; Pete Levin, 32nd in line, had camped out with his 
sister and friend since 9 a.m. Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	``I didn't want anyone to spoil it for me,'' Levin said of his  
determination to get tickets to the very first showing. ``I want to 
be surprised. I didn't want anyone to tell me the ending.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Those who thought it would be a bit more sane buying tickets by  
phone or over the Internet were in for a surprise. 
</P>
<P>
	So many people called MovieFone for tickets that circuits were  
jammed, even though the ticket service added lines. MovieFone's Web 
site was also swamped. 
</P>
<P>
	``The demand has been even greater than we expected,'' said  
Christine Fakundiny, director of marketing for MovieFone. ``But 
people are getting through and we are processing them. The advice 
to the war weary is keeping trying.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Cody Hoffman, 13, of New York said his mother had allowed him to  
skip school and wait in line all day for tickets. He said his 
mother ``knows how important it is to me.'' And his teachers? 
</P>
<P>
	``For all I know my teacher is on line at some other theater,''  
he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Outside the Eastgate Theatre in Portland, Ore., Gabe Elliot  
complained about people ahead of him who sang music from ``Star 
Wars'' and recited quotes from the ``Monty Python and the Holy 
Grail'' comedy film while he stood in line. 
</P>
<P>
	Said Elliot: ``I'm surrounded by psychos.''  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990513.0162 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-13 10:34:53 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Settlement Sought in Diet Drug Case </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DALLAS (AP) -- Lawyers representing millions of people who used  
the diet drug combination fen-phen are negotiating a national 
settlement of health claims against the manufacturer, American Home 
Products Corp., a lawyer confirmed today. 
</P>
<P>
	The talks are in the earliest stages, but American Home Products  
hopes to reach an out-of-court deal in cases scheduled for trial in 
Texas this spring and summer, said Houston lawyer Graham Hill, 
whose partners, representing plaintiffs, attended two settlement 
meetings. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dallas Morning News, which first reported the negotiations  
today, said American Home Products would pay billions of dollars 
under such a deal. Hill, however, said it was too early to put a 
price tag on a possible settlement. 
</P>
<P>
	``There have been several meetings, and a number of different  
proposals and scenarios have been discussed, but there are some 
difficult issues that are going to have to be agreed upon before 
anything of this magnitude can be concluded,'' Hill added. 
</P>
<P>
	American Home Products spokesman Lowell Weiner declined comment  
on the report this morning. 
</P>
<P>
	Last month, the company reached a settlement in the first trial  
over heart-valve damage from fen-phen, reportedly agreeing to pay 
$500,000 to one plaintiff. 
</P>
<P>
	Thousands of people contend they developed heart problems after  
taking the drugs. Some 6 million people in the United States used 
the drug. 
</P>
<P>
	The company wants ``to avoid letting any of these cases go to  
trial and risk a really huge verdict,'' another Houston lawyer, Don 
Bowen, told the Morning News. 
</P>
<P>
	A large jury verdict, he said, would ``considerably inflate'' a  
national settlement's price tag. 
</P>
<P>
	Through its Wyeth-Ayerst Laboratories subsidiary, American Home  
Products marketed fenfluramine -- half of the fen-phen combination -- 
and Redux, a similar product. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1997, the Madison, N.J.-based drug maker pulled fenfluramine  
and Redux off the market at the Food and Drug Administration's 
request. A Mayo Clinic study had linked the drugs to potentially 
fatal heart valve damage.The other half of fen-phen, phentermine, 
was never associated with that damage when taken alone and is still 
on the market. 
</P>
<P>
	Settlements in at least nine cases, including those of four  
Texans, have resulted in amounts of up to $4.6 million. The company 
must put between $3 billion and $5 billion into a settlement before 
it is acceptable, some lawyers and Wall Street analysts told the 
Morning News. 
</P>
<P>
	The drug maker, in a filing with the U.S. Securities and  
Exchange Commission, stated it was aware of 2,615 lawsuits over 
fen-phen as of March 22. Class-action lawsuits are certified in 
Illinois, New Jersey, Pennsylvania, Texas, Washington and West 
Virginia. 


</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990513.0163 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-13 14:25:47 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Tobacco Industry Wins Again in Court </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	KANSAS CITY, Mo. (AP) -- A federal jury handed the tobacco  
industry its second victory in four days Thursday, deciding Brown &AMP; 
Williamson Tobacco Corp. was not at fault in the case of a smoker 
who died of lung cancer in 1995. 
</P>
<P>
	Charles Steele's family had sued for $26 million, claiming the  
nation's third-largest tobacco company sold him an unreasonably 
dangerous product. The factory worker picked up the habit in his 
late teens or early 20s, smoked 1 1/2 to two packs a day -- mostly 
Kools -- and died at 55. 
</P>
<P>
	Jury foreman Gary White said Steele ``was quite aware of the  
dangers, but the pleasures outweighed the dangers.'' 
</P>
<P>
	On Monday, a jury in Memphis, Tenn., cleared B&AMP;W and two other  
tobacco companies of liability in the deaths of three smokers. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. juries have awarded damages in smoking liability cases only  
five times -- twice in Florida and once in New Jersey, Oregon and 
California. The Florida and New Jersey verdicts were overturned on 
appeal, while the $51.5 million award in California was halved by a 
judge. Lawyers are preparing an appeal of the Oregon verdict. 
</P>
<P>
	In the Missouri case, B&AMP;W argued that Steele never tried to quit  
smoking and that he was exposed to a host of cancer-causing 
chemicals through jobs at an aluminum foundry and at a brick-making 
plant. 
</P>
<P>
	The verdict ``reflects recognition by the jury that Brown &AMP;  
Williamson acted responsibly in the processes of researching, 
testing and designing our products,'' said B&AMP;W attorney Steven 
McCormick. 
</P>
<P>
	``The jury's conclusions are consistent with the majority of  
court decisions, agreeing that smoking is a matter of personal 
choice.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The family's attorney, J. Michael Cronan, said there will be no  
appeal. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990513.0164 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-13 16:11:58 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Netanyahu Losing Some Support </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	JERUSALEM (AP) -- Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu's traditional  
support among ex-Soviet Jews is faltering, the former dissident who 
leads a powerful immigrants party said Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Natan Sharansky, the industry and trade minister in Netanyahu's  
government, also refused to endorse the prime minister -- who is 
trailing badly in the polls ahead of Monday's election. 
</P>
<P>
	Netanyahu had been lobbying Sharansky to make a declaration of  
support, reportedly offering his Israel B'Aliya party three 
ministries if he did so. 
</P>
<P>
	Sharansky steadfastly refused Thursday, saying neutrality was  
crucial for a party seeking the best possible post-election deal. 
</P>
<P>
	``I believe that if I change this decision the party will simply  
fall apart,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Showing figures from polls commissioned by Israel B'Aliya,  
Sharansky said Netanyahu had lost support in recent weeks among 
immigrants from the former Soviet Union, who make up a crucial 15 
percent of the electorate. 
</P>
<P>
	``Netanyahu was dominating on the Russian street for a long  
time,'' Sharansky said. In recent days, however, his support among 
immigrants has dropped from 65 percent to 55 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Netanyahu had counted on solid support from former Soviet Jews  
to make up for lost votes in his Likud Party among members 
disillusioned with his leadership. 
</P>
<P>
	Sharansky warned that the immigrant vote was ``fluid'' and most  
supporters of his party had not changed the nationalistic views 
that led them to support Netanyahu's hard-line policies in the 
past. 
</P>
<P>
	``The situation will not be clear I think until the last day,''  
Sharansky said. 
</P>
<P>
	Polls show Netanyahu's main rival, Labor Party leader Ehud  
Barak, drawing support in the mid-40 percent range. Should he 
garner enough support among Russian immigrants he may win more than 
half the vote Monday even if three other minor party candidates 
stay in the race. 
</P>
<P>
	If no candidate gets more than 50 percent of the vote, the  
election goes to a runoff June 1. Netanyahu is seeking a second 
round, hoping to use the grace period to stage a comeback. 
</P>
<P>
	His chances appeared to be bolstered when Centrist party  
candidate Yitzhak Mordechai announced plans to stay in the race 
despite only single-digit support. 
</P>
<P>
	Some of Mordechai's Centrist Party colleagues have urged him to  
withdraw since he has no chance of winning. 
</P>
<P>
	``Whoever wants to leave, let him get up and go,'' Mordechai was  
quoted as saying by the Yediot Aharonot daily after meeting with 
party leaders. ``My decision won't change.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mordechai helped create the Centrist party with the main goal of  
ousting the prime minister after Netanyahu fired him as defense 
minister earlier this year. 
</P>
<P>
	Two other minor party candidates said Thursday they were still  
in the race but reports said they may pull out over the weekend. 
</P>
<P>
	More good news for Netanyahu was that he has secured the  
endorsement of both ultra-Orthodox parties, which command at least 
6 percent of the vote. 
</P>
<P>
	Announcing their endorsement, the spiritual leaders of the  
United Torah Judaism party launched a new slogan: ``Netanyahu is 
good for Judaism.'' Shas, the other ultra-Orthodox party, endorsed 
Netanyahu on Wednesday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990513.0165 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-13 16:11:58 </DATE_TIME>
