<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-13 15:44:44 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Film Looks at Religion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CANNES, France (AP) -- In the opening moments of ``Kadosh,'' an  
Orthodox Jewish man awakes and recites his morning prayers. In one 
traditional prayer he thanks God ``for not making me a woman.'' 
</P>
<P>
	With that, Amos Gitai, director of the first Israeli film chosen  
for Cannes competition in 25 years, makes his point -- and then he 
keeps on making it. This is a film that starts out bleak and just 
gets bleaker. 
</P>
<P>
	``Kadosh'' -- the word means ``sacred'' -- is a brutal attack on  
Orthodox Jewish life and its treatment of women, by a filmmaker who 
says it's his way of voting against the religious right in Monday's 
elections in Israel. 
</P>
<P>
	Though the acting is often excellent and the film searing and  
painful, many scenes are unnecessarily, agonizingly slow. 
</P>
<P>
	The film is, however, fascinating to watch, mainly because it  
was shot in Mea Shearim, the ultra-Orthodox neighborhood in 
Jerusalem that is largely closed off to secular Israel and the rest 
of the world. Gitai managed to film the exteriors and some 
interiors there, providing an authentic view of a mysterious, 
shuttered world. 
</P>
<P>
	The story focuses on two sisters, Rivka and Malka, each  
struggling in her own way with the rules of her religion. 
</P>
<P>
	The beautiful Rivka loves her husband, Meir -- the man who prays  
in the film's opening. But after 10 years of trying, she has been 
unable to get pregnant. In the eyes of their community, this makes 
Rivka not a woman at all. 
</P>
<P>
	Worse, Meir tells his passionate wife that sex is now a sin for  
them, because it is not leading to procreation. 
</P>
<P>
	As Rivka's situation becomes more desperate, her younger sister,  
Malka, finds she has been condemned to an arranged marriage with a 
man she hates -- taking her away from the one she loves, Yaacov, who 
has left Mea Shearim. 
</P>
<P>
	Things get worse: Rivka is forced to leave home and live in a  
room somewhere, so Meir can have a child with another wife -- even 
though a secular doctor has told Rivka it may actually be Meir who 
is sterile. 
</P>
<P>
	As for Malka, she endures a loveless wedding and an absolutely  
awful wedding night -- presented graphically here -- and, when she 
slips off for a tryst with her true love, is discovered and beaten 
by her husband. 
</P>
<P>
	At the end, suffice it to say, things get worse, not better.  
</P>
<P>
	The film is written by Eliette Abecassis, a woman and a  
practicing Jew based in France who spent time living in Mea Shearim 
for her research. 
</P>
<P>
	The director makes no bones about his desire to make a strong  
political statement with the film, which opens in Israel on June 
10. A U.S. distributor has not yet been found. 
</P>
<P>
	``In this election, the choice is radical,'' says Gitai, who  
comes from a family that founded Israel's center-left Labor Party. 
``There has practically been a coup d'etat by the religious 
community. We must decide what kind of country we will be.'' 
</P>
<P>
	An interesting side story is that of the actress who plays  
Malka, 21-year-old Meital Barda. She grew up in an Orthodox family 
but left that life behind. She has several sexual scenes in the 
film. 
</P>
<P>
	``My family wasn't happy with the thought of me doing such  
scenes,'' she said. ``But in the end, they supported me. I think 
the hand of God was with us.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990513.0167 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-13 00:22:57 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
