<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Tornadoes Scatter Photos to Winds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MIDWEST CITY, Okla. (AP) -- The black-and-white photo of the  
young bride is stained with mud. Debris coats an image of a little 
girl cradling a newborn on her lap. 
</P>
<P>
	The photographs, dirty and torn, are among hundreds piling up at  
a lost-and-found site at the First Christian Church. Despite their 
blemishes, the pictures are sought-after treasures, crucial pieces 
of history for residents devastated by last week's tornadoes. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think it would mean so much to just get back one if I lost  
everything,'' said Shauna Becker, who started the photo retrieval 
site. 
</P>
<P>
	The May 3 twisters killed 44 people in Oklahoma, including a  
woman, missing since the storm, whose body was found Wednesday and 
identified today. It injured hundreds more and destroyed thousands 
of homes. But the statistics do not account for the sentimental 
treasures and precious keepsakes suddenly swept away. 
</P>
<P>
	In Moore, 73-year-old Thelma Pruegert picked through the heap of  
furniture, lumber and cars tossed where her house once stood. She 
had recovered other people's photographs, but the photos of her 16 
great-grandchildren were nowhere to be found. 
</P>
<P>
	Down the street, Barbara Sexton, 66, found her mother's wedding  
picture plastered against a wall. The rest of her photographs 
escaped damage inside an antique trunk. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was real happy,'' she said. ``That's our lives in there.''  
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Becker, a new mother at age 28, didn't know what to expect  
when she posted fliers offering the church as a repository. But she 
had to do something after finding a 1971 picture of a man posing 
with his car. 
</P>
<P>
	``I thought, what if that is someone's dad?'' she said. ``What  
if that's the only picture they have of him?'' 
</P>
<P>
	By Wednesday, hundreds of photographs had arrived at the church.  
It will be open weekly for residents searching for treasured 
keepsakes. 
</P>
<P>
	On the first night, a man was reunited with his patch from the  
Vietnam War, and a family found a photo of a niece. A couple whose 
grandson died in the tornado recognized his baby photos on a 
television broadcast and picked them up. 
</P>
<P>
	Other photos wait for their stories to be told: A family wearing  
leis poses on a Hawaiian beach. Four bridesmaids in pink dresses 
staring soberly toward an unseen bride. A woman standing in fresh 
snow, wearing a long black coat of another era. 
</P>
<P>
	Chris Abbott and her husband, Terry Hardy, came looking for  
scrapbooks that disappeared with most of their home. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Abbott's tears rolled down her cheeks and onto the floor as  
she described a particular photograph. It was a sonogram image 
taken by doctors who thought it would confirm an enormous ovarian 
cyst. Instead it revealed tiny hands and feet. It was the first 
picture to go in her son's baby book. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's the start of us being a family,'' she said.  
</P>
<P>
	``That's when we decided to be something,'' Hardy added softly  
at her side. 
</P>
<P>
	Their son George, who turns 8 today, is safe. But the  
photographs tracking him from womb to his last birthday could not 
be found in the debris of their neighborhood. 
</P>
<P>
	And so, they went to the church, hopeful.  
</P>
<P>
	Has anyone turned in any scrapbooks, they asked? Their eyes fell  
when Ms. Becker told them no. 
</P>
<P>
	``But come back,'' she said. ``I'm sure things will be rolling  
in all week long.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
