<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Consumers Fight Some Baby Bottles </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Consumer groups petitioned the government  
Wednesday to remove a chemical from certain plastic baby bottles 
that they say can leach into infants' food. 
</P>
<P>
	The Food and Drug Administration responded that parents  
shouldn't be alarmed. 
</P>
<P>
	The National Environmental Trust, in calling for safer bottles,  
cited studies that show bisphenol-A can leach out of plastic 
bottles when they're heated, particularly if the bottles are old or 
scratched. 
</P>
<P>
	A University of Missouri study suggests male babies of pregnant  
mice exposed to this chemical have slightly enlarged prostates and 
lowered sperm production. 
</P>
<P>
	The only baby bottles at issue are those made of hard, clear,  
shiny plastic called polycarbonate. They have been sold for 
decades. 
</P>
<P>
	Other baby bottles, those that appear more opaque and softer --  
as well as the disposable formula bags that many parents slip into 
bottles -- are made of a different type of plastic that does not 
contain bisphenol-A. 
</P>
<P>
	Parents who are unsure what type of bottle they have can contact  
the manufacturer. 
</P>
<P>
	Polycarbonate bottles don't appear to leach under everyday  
conditions, just when they're heated to high temperatures or for 
long periods, said the FDA's Dr. George Pauli, who noted that most 
infant formulas require only mild heating. 
</P>
<P>
	Also, they leach at levels considered too low for human harm,  
said Pauli, adding that other scientists who have repeated the 
Missouri animal study have not found evidence of harm. 
</P>
<P>
	So while the FDA will investigate Wednesday's petition,  
``there's no consensus in the scientific community at this stage 
that there's anything of significance here,'' Pauli said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
