<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> NRA Ordered to Pay $4.5 Million </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- The National Rifle Association has been  
ordered to pay $4.45 million to a former NRA board member and her 
husband who accused the organization of bullying and disparaging 
them. 
</P>
<P>
	The lawsuit by Sally and Kenneth Brodbeck of Des Moines, Iowa,  
was filed after an altercation with a security guard at the NRA's 
national convention in Philadelphia last year. 
</P>
<P>
	A federal jury awarded the couple damages for public  
disparagement and battery. Security guard Gordon Russell was 
ordered to pay $6,000. 
</P>
<P>
	NRA lawyers said they will appeal Thursday's verdict.  
</P>
<P>
	Brodbeck said he was sitting in a chair videotaping a speech by  
his wife, an NRA board member at the time, when Russell ordered him 
to stop taping and tackled him when he refused. 
</P>
<P>
	NRA lawyers said Mrs. Brodbeck was part of a faction opposing  
the group now in power at the NRA. They said the incident was 
staged to disrupt the convention last June 8. 
</P>
<P>
	Charlton Heston, who was elected NRA president the day of the  
altercation, testified that Brodbeck had faked a ``lousy fall'' by 
tumbling out of his chair. 
</P>
<P>
	The Brodbecks alleged their reputations were tarnished and sued  
after the NRA refused to apologize. 
</P>
<P>
	``We feel vindicated,'' Brodbeck said after the verdict. ``We  
just wanted our reputation back.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier this month, at the NRA's convention in Denver, Mrs.  
Brodbeck was defeated in her bid to keep her seat on the board. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
