<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Cop Testifies in NYC Torture Case </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- An officer testified that he saw a colleague  
brandishing a stick allegedly used to torture a black Haitian 
immigrant, but the defense today targeted an inconsistency in his 
story. 
</P>
<P>
	Breaking the alleged ``blue wall of silence,'' detective Eric  
Turetzky testified Wednesday that Officer Justin Volpe walked 
through a Brooklyn police station waving the stick, which Abner 
Louima claims was rammed into his rectum and mouth. 
</P>
<P>
	Turetzky said Volpe ``was swinging the stick around like a sword  
and hitting it against the wall.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Volpe and three other officers are charged with taking turns  
beating Louima because they believed -- mistakenly -- that Louima had 
punched Volpe in a melee outside a Brooklyn nightclub on Aug. 9, 
1997. A fifth officer is charged with covering up the assault. 
</P>
<P>
	Louima earlier testified that a raging Volpe tortured him with  
the stick while another officer held him down on the bathroom floor 
of the station. 
</P>
<P>
	On Wednesday, Turetzky testified that he saw only Volpe emerge  
from the bathroom with Louima. But during cross-examination today, 
Volpe's attorney, Marvyn Kornberg, confronted the detective with 
the transcript of an interview by police department investigators 
in which he indicated he may have seen a second, unidentified 
officer as well. 
</P>
<P>
	In the interview, Turetzky said, ``I'm not sure who removed  
(Louima) from the bathroom, but I distinctly remember Officer Volpe 
standing there with a stick.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A multimillion-dollar lawsuit filed on Louima's behalf alleges  
that rogue police were shielded by the ``blue wall of silence'' -- a 
supposed code among officers never to turn one another in. 
</P>
<P>
	Turetzky, 28, was made a detective for internal police  
department investigations after coming forward to report what he 
saw that night. Taking the witness stand Wednesday, the officer 
recounted helping arrest Louima as police dispersed a 
bottle-throwing crowd outside the nightclub. 
</P>
<P>
	When Turetzky returned to the station, he said, he saw Officer  
Charles Schwarz searching a handcuffed Louima in front of a desk 
sergeant. He testified that Schwarz, 33, forced the prisoner onto 
his toes by raising up his arms, then pushed him toward the 
direction of the bathroom. 
</P>
<P>
	Later, Turetzky spotted Volpe, 27, emerging from the bathroom  
with Louima and carrying the stick. He noticed that Volpe's uniform 
was ``a little messed up'' -- no badge, no name tag, his shirttail 
out and gun belt off. 
</P>
<P>
	Investigators never found the stick.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
