<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Safety Work at N.C. Track May Wait </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CONCORD, N.C. (AP) -- Officials at Lowe's Motor Speedway believe  
fans watching NASCAR races will be safe despite an accident that 
killed three spectators during an IRL event earlier this month. 
</P>
<P>
	Officials have been considering changes since the accident that  
sent debris into the stands on May 1. But track president H.A. 
``Humpy'' Wheeler said no changes will be made in time for this 
month's NASCAR races. 
</P>
<P>
	No NASCAR spectator has been killed in 40 years at the track, he  
said. A final decision on any changes will be made Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Indy Racing League cars have open-wheel bodies and are more  
likely to spray debris into the stands during a crash than the 
slower, closed-wheel stock cars. 
</P>
<P>
	The track's parent company, however, is considering raising the  
protective fence at its track in Texas, site of the next IRL event 
at a track it owns. 
</P>
<P>
	``I have a good feeling about our safety'' for NASCAR races,  
Wheeler said Wednesday. ``We don't want to overreact on anything.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He also said he doesn't want to do anything that would interfere  
with fans' view of the action during the speedway's biggest week of 
events, capped by the Coca-Cola 600 on May 30. 
</P>
<P>
	``They'll raise Cain if they can't see,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	Speedway Motorsports Inc., however, is looking at adding as much  
as 4 1/2 feet to the catch fences at Texas Motor Speedway in Fort 
Worth. Fences there are nearly identical to those at Lowe's. 
</P>
<P>
	The work in Texas, which would be done before the Longhorn 500  
on June 12, would make that speedway's fence as high above the 
track as the one at Indianapolis Motor Speedway and among the 
highest of any U.S. speedway. 
</P>
<P>
	On Wednesday, the lead investigator in the May 1 crash moved the  
inquiry to Indianapolis, where IRL drivers are preparing for the 
Indianapolis 500, also to be contested May 30. 
</P>
<P>
	Officials confirmed Wednesday that the right rear wheel from  
Stan Wattles' car ended up in the stands. His car crashed into the 
fourth-turn wall, spewing debris as it scraped along. 
</P>
<P>
	Officials hope to release a preliminary report on the crash  
investigation Friday. 


</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
