<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Gap Earnings Up More Than 50 Pct </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- Gap Inc.'s first-quarter earnings climbed  
by more than 50 percent from a year ago, fueled by strong results 
at its Old Navy stores. 
</P>
<P>
	The San Francisco-based retailer earned $202 million, or 34  
cents a share, in the quarter ended May 1, compared with $136 
million, or 22 cents a share, a year ago. 
</P>
<P>
	Sales were $2.28 billion, up from $1.72 billion a year ago.  
Sales at stores open at least a year, an industry gauge of 
performance, rose 11 percent, slowing from the previous year's 17 
percent increase. 
</P>
<P>
	Gap's results topped Wall Street analysts' estimates, but its  
stock was off 43 3/4 cents at $61.81 1/4 in early trading on the New York 
Stock Exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	Gap's president and CEO, Millard Dexter, praised his company's  
commitment to growth, ``even against challenging comparisons.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Fueling the better-than-expected results were strong sales at  
its Old Navy division, which continues to draw shoppers with its 
trendy, yet affordable clothes -- including this spring's must-have 
item -- drawstring pants. 
</P>
<P>
	The company operated 19.5 million square feet of retail space at  
the end of the quarter, up 22 percent from the 16 million square 
feet at the end the quarter last year. 
</P>
<P>
	Gap Inc. operated 2,529 stores at the end of the quarter, up  
from the 2,196 at the end of the same period last year. The 1999 
figure included 1,138 Gap, 676 GapKids, 295 Banana Republic, and 
420 Old Navy stores. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
