<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Refund Allegedly Used For Hit Man </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ALTOONA, Pa. (AP) -- A woman devised a deadly way to spend her  
income tax refund, police say: She paid a hit man to kill her 
husband's lover. 
</P>
<P>
	Carolyn Burke was enraged when her husband of 14 years left her  
and their two children in January to live with a woman in 
Massachusetts he had met over the Internet, police said. 
</P>
<P>
	She waited three months for the family's income tax refund to  
arrive, then paid $2,000 to a friend's 17-year-old stepson to have 
the woman killed, police said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Mrs. Burke was serious about having her husband's girlfriend  
killed,'' police Detective Anthony Sassano said Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The teen-ager, however, had other plans. Christopher Chaplin  
allegedly spent the money on parties and motel rooms but didn't 
carry out his end of the deal. When he told Mrs. Burke the money 
was gone, she was so upset that she called a mental health hot line 
and confessed the plot, Sassano said. The counselor told police. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Burke and the teen's mother, Susan Chaplin, both 31, were  
arraigned Tuesday for criminal solicitation to commit homicide and 
two counts of criminal conspiracy. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Chaplin had offered to find a hit man for Mrs. Burke and  
persuaded her stepson to take the job, police said. 
</P>
<P>
	Christopher Chaplin will be charged in juvenile court with  
theft, theft by deception and criminal conspiracy, Sassano said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
