<HEADLINE> Tobacco Verdict Still Largest Ever </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) -- A judge on Thursday slashed a $79.5  
million jury verdict against Philip Morris to $32 million, but it 
is still the largest judgment ever against a tobacco company. 
</P>
<P>
	Judge Anna J. Brown said her decision was not a criticism of the  
verdict. 
</P>
<P>
	``The U.S. Supreme Court said there are limits,'' she said. ``By  
no means is my personal point of view substituted for that of the 
jury.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The award was granted March 30 to the family of Jesse Williams,  
a former school janitor who died of lung cancer in 1997 at age 67. 
He had smoked Marlboro cigarettes for 42 years. 
</P>
<P>
	Jurors said they were infuriated by documents showing that  
Philip Morris executives had lied for decades about the link 
between smoking and cancer. 
</P>
<P>
	The jury awarded Williams' family $79.5 million in punitive  
damages and $821,485 in compensatory damages for medical costs and 
pain and suffering. The judge did not cut the compensatory damages 
but sliced the punitive award after reviewing decisions in other 
cases. 
</P>
<P>
	Attorneys for both the family and the cigarette company declined  
comment. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. juries have awarded damages in smoking liability cases only  
four other times -- twice in Florida and once in New Jersey and 
California. The Florida and New Jersey verdicts were overturned on 
appeal. A judge cut the $51.5 million award in California in half, 
and that case is also being appealed. 


</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
