<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Japan Recession May Not Be Over </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Despite two years of a shrinking economy, the worst  
of Japan's recession may not be over, an International Monetary 
Fund official warned Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Deputy director for research Flemming Larsen said Japan must  
continue with massive stimulus spending until its economy recovers, 
which could take years. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is important to maintain adequate stimulus for several  
years until the recovery becomes sustainable,'' Larsen said. 
</P>
<P>
	However, Larsen cautioned that over reliance on government  
spending may also be a bad thing. 
</P>
<P>
	Instead, Japan needs to strike a ``delicate balance between  
adequate stimulus but not too much stimulus as to crowd out the 
private sector,'' Larsen told reporters in Tokyo. 
</P>
<P>
	The IMF recently cut its forecast for Japan's gross domestic  
product, predicting it would shrink 1.4 percent this year. It had 
previously forecast a contraction of 0.5 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
