<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> N.M. Suspect May Have Killed More </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SOCORRO, N.M. (AP) -- A man already accused of kidnapping and  
sexually torturing three women admitted he killed as many as 14 
other people and disposed of the bodies, his girlfriend told 
investigators. 
</P>
<P>
	David Parker Ray, 59, and his girlfriend, Cynthia Lea Hendy, 39,  
were arrested March 22 after an Albuquerque woman said she escaped 
and ran away from Ray's mobile home, naked except for a padlocked 
collar. 
</P>
<P>
	Hendy told police after her arrest that Ray disposed of bodies --  
both men and women -- in ravines and in Elephant Butte Lake in 
south-central New Mexico, according to information released 
Wednesday by prosecutor Jim Yontz. 
</P>
<P>
	Since the arrests, authorities have followed leads in 10 states,  
using ground-penetrating radar and dogs trained to locate human 
remains. 
</P>
<P>
	Agents have combed gullies in Sierra County and searched the  
lake for bodies and other evidence. No bodies have been found. 
</P>
<P>
	Last month, two women testified that they were abducted,  
sodomized, shocked with electricity, sexually tortured and kept 
captive in padlocked collars in separate incidents in February and 
March. 
</P>
<P>
	Ray faces 25 charges involving the two women. He waived a  
preliminary hearing on 12 additional charges related to a third 
woman who says she was kidnapped by Ray and his daughter in July 
1996. 
</P>
<P>
	Both Ray and his daughter, Glenda Ray, 32, have said they are  
innocent. 
</P>
<P>
	Ray's attorney, Jeff Rein, said Hendy made the allegations after  
she had worked out a deal with prosecutors to reduce both the 
number of charges she faced and her potential prison sentence -- 
from 198 years to as few as 12. 
</P>
<P>
	``She told them what they wanted to hear,'' Rein said. ``I think  
if they would have found any bodies after 45 days, we would have 
seen some charges.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Hendy, initially charged with 25 counts, plans to plead  
guilty to five counts, including accessory and conspiracy charges, 
her lawyer has said. The agreement still needs a judge's approval. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
