<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Stocks in Record Area; Dow Up 113.98 / Wall Street Report  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks moved into record high territory today as  
IBM soared and new government economic data assuaged investors' 
fears of inflation. 
</P>
<P>
	At 2 p.m. on Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial average was  
up 113.98 at 11,114.35, topping its previous closing record last 
Friday of 11,031.59. 
</P>
<P>
	Broader stock indicators were higher as well, with the Standard  
&AMP; Poor's 500 index up 10.63 at 1,374.63 and topping Wednesday's 
record closing high of 1,364.00. The Nasdaq composite index was up 
21.93 at 2,628.47. 
</P>
<P>
	IBM led the Dow higher after chairman Louis Gerstner told  
analysts late Wednesday the Internet would play a large part in Big 
Blue's future, and that a quarter of the company's 1998 revenues 
came from electronic commerce. 
</P>
<P>
	``The bull beat goes on, led by Big Blue,'' said Alfred E.  
Goldman, chief market strategist at A.G. Edwards &AMP; Sons Inc. in St. 
Louis. IBM shares soared 16 1/16 to a record 241 9/16, accounting 
for more than 73 1/2 points on the Dow, and boosting the shares of 
other personal computer makers. Hewlett-Packard was up 4 5/8 at 87 7/8 on 
the New York Stock Exchange, and Dell was up 3/8 at 44 1/8 in Nasdaq 
trading. 
</P>
<P>
	Internet stocks bowed to profit-taking after a strong morning.  
America Online slid 1 15/16 to 135 1/2 and was the most active issue 
on the NYSE. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dow transportation average was down 39.15, or 1.03 percent,  
at 3,744.35, as shares of trucking company J.B. Hunt Transport 
Services dropped 3 17/32 to 19 3/8 in Nasdaq trading. Hunt said 
competition had cut into its shipping traffic and that April 
revenues, which did not meet expectations, will hurt second-quarter 
profits. 
</P>
<P>
	Stocks got a boost from a Labor Department report that wholesale  
prices rose 0.5 percent in April as the price of gasoline jumped 
significantly. But the core rate of the producer price index, which 
strips away volatile food and energy costs, was up a mere 0.1 
percent. Both numbers were in line with economists' expectations 
and showed that inflation remains tame. 
</P>
<P>
	Separately, the department said first-time claims for  
unemployment benefits held steady at a moderate 303,000 last week. 
A more reliable four-week moving average of jobless claims dropped 
by 4,000 to 304,250, suggesting that unemployment will remain at 
4.3 percent this month, near a 29-year low. 
</P>
<P>
	In a third report, the Commerce Department said retail sales  
rose 0.1 percent in April, as consumers reacted to higher energy 
costs by pulling in their purse strings. That was a smaller 
increase than many analysts had expected. 
</P>
<P>
	Investors are now turning their attention to Friday's expected  
release of consumer price data. Taken together, the producer- and 
consumer-price data could give them clues about the Federal 
Reserve's policy meeting next Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Most investors don't expect the Fed to raise interest rates next  
week in a bid to slow the economy and head off inflation, said 
Larry Rice, chief investment officer at Josephthal &AMP; Co. ``Most 
people think (central bankers) are more inclined to raise rates in 
August, after they get more indication of recovering global 
economies,'' Rice said. 
</P>
<P>
	Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by an 8-to-5 margin on  
the New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 538.69 million 
shares, down from Wednesday's pace. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990513.0189 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-13 15:31:54 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Body Found in Okla. Tornado Debris </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	OKLAHOMA CITY (AP) -- The body of a woman reported missing in  
last week's tornadoes has been found, bringing to 44 the number of 
people killed in Oklahoma during the storms. 
</P>
<P>
	Tram Thu Bui, 26, disappeared May 3 when a tornado sucked her  
from the arms of a man trying to hold on to her off an interstate 
in Moore. 
</P>
<P>
	Two women who were friends of Ms. Bui found her body Wednesday  
while searching along Interstate 35 near an overpass where Ms. Bui 
was last seen as she and her husband got out of their car with 
their two children. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Bui's husband, Thuanh, protected the children while a man  
tried to hold onto Ms. Bui, but she was pulled away by the tornado. 
Her body was found beneath a pile of debris. 
</P>
<P>
	The family was making a surprise visit from their home in Marlow  
to relatives in the Oklahoma City area when the tornadoes hit. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Bui was the last missing tornado victim in Oklahoma.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
