<DOCNO> APW19990513.0190 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-13 06:27:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Relief Efforts Hampered in Albania </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	KUKES, Albania (AP) -- A lack of coordination among NATO, aid  
groups and the Albanian government has bedeviled efforts to move 
100,000 Kosovo refugees out of this dusty, overcrowded border 
region, a U.N. official said today. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.N. relief agency launched a tent-to-tent information  
campaign this week to convince refugees to leave the camps in the 
northern town of Kukes for safer, less congested regions further 
south. 
</P>
<P>
	But most of the refugees want to stay close to the border,  
clinging to the hope that NATO troops will soon be inside Kosovo to 
guarantee their safety from the Yugoslav security forces. 
</P>
<P>
	``The information campaign has met with underwhelmingly modest  
success,'' said Ray Wilkinson, a spokesman for the United Nations 
High Commissioner of Refugees. 
</P>
<P>
	A successful day is when refugees departing Kukes outnumber  
those arriving across the nearby frontier with Kosovo. The 
scorecard Wednesday: 5,475 left, 3,900 arrived. 
</P>
<P>
	In theory, UNHCR is the overall coordinator for the refugee  
efforts. But in reality, the numerous aid groups, the militaries 
from NATO countries and the Albanian government often seem to be 
operating independently, with no one in charge. 
</P>
<P>
	``There is not a lot of coordinated information,'' Wilkinson  
acknowledged. 
</P>
<P>
	NATO trucks have been bringing food to Kukes, but at times the  
aid groups aren't aware of the deliveries in advance. The trucks 
may sit overnight before the aid groups learn of the deliveries. 
</P>
<P>
	``Multiply that by 200 examples and you have a much less  
efficient operation than you would like,'' said Wilkinson. 
</P>
<P>
	While welcoming aid from all quarters, the independent  
arrangements have resulted in widely varying standards at the 
camps. 
</P>
<P>
	The camp established by the army of the United Arab Emirates has  
facilities that are nearly on a par with a military operation and 
it is widely regarded as the best-run camp in Kukes. 
</P>
<P>
	But newly arrived refugees can spend days milling around the  
streets of Kukes and sleeping in the wagons hitched to their 
tractors before they can find decent shelter. 
</P>
<P>
	``There needs to be a lot more clear information for the  
refugees,'' said Samantha Bolton, spokeswoman for the aid group 
Doctors Without Borders. ``The refugees don't really know where 
they are going if they leave Kukes, and that's one reason that they 
are reluctant to move.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Still, aid workers say the operation has been able to meet the  
basic needs of the refugees. More than 780,000 ethnic Albanians 
have fled Kosovo in the past seven weeks, with more than 400,000 
coming to Albania. 
</P>
<P>
	The 100,000 refugees in Kukes represent by far the largest  
concentration in any one area. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990513.0191 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-13 06:27:10 </DATE_TIME>
