<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-13 15:56:46 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> SEC Targets Online Investment Fraud </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Securities and Exchange Commission has  
been called ``The Eagle on the Street'' for its supervision of Wall 
Street. These days, though, as it fights growing investment fraud 
on the Internet, the agency has sometimes appeared more like a 
tiger missing a few teeth. 
</P>
<P>
	In a bid to bolster its ability to fight online fraud, the SEC  
has turned to Congress for help, asking for an increase in its 
budget and greater leeway in the kind of enforcement actions it can 
take. 
</P>
<P>
	In a fairly unusual development, two Republican senators are  
very willing to assist. 
</P>
<P>
	Even if it gets the help the lawmakers are offering, however,  
the SEC's crime-fighting powers will continue to be hampered in 
several ways, including the fact that it can only file civil 
lawsuits against suspected violators. 
</P>
<P>
	Unlike the Justice Department, it cannot put anyone in jail, and  
unlike state securities regulators, SEC fraud-fighters don't have 
the legal authority to go undercover online, although they can and 
do conduct Internet surveillance. 
</P>
<P>
	There are other limits: The SEC can bar brokers who have  
violated the law from the brokerage industry, but not from other 
financial activities such as promoting stocks. And while it has 
aggressively gone after people and companies engaging in Internet 
fraud with civil fines and court orders compelling them to refrain 
from such activity, it doesn't have authority to shut down Web 
sites. 
</P>
<P>
	On top of that, enforcement attorneys and auditors have been  
leaving the agency at a worrisome pace for lucrative jobs in 
private practice. 
</P>
<P>
	Against this background, the SEC and state regulators are  
battling a new form of fraud that is proliferating in Internet junk 
mail, online newsletters, electronic ``chat rooms'' and World Wide 
Web sites. 
</P>
<P>
	Because the Internet is everywhere, unscrupulous stock promoters  
anywhere in the world can cloak themselves in anonymity and lure 
investors across the country, who have lost millions in such 
schemes in recent years. No longer do promoters have to give 
customers the hard sell over the telephone in unsolicited calls. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite the new possibilities for deceiving investors offered by  
the Internet, securities regulators still operate under the old 
rule book. 
</P>
<P>
	``There is a certain breed of bottom-feeders who are simply not  
deterred by the prospect of civil injunctions or even stiff 
monetary penalties,'' SEC Enforcement Director Richard Walker said 
recently. ``There is no other ... deterrence for them than the 
threat of a life behind bars.'' 
</P>
<P>
	To create that deterrent, the SEC has been working closely with  
criminal prosecutors from the Justice Department and the offices of 
state attorneys general and local district attorneys. 
</P>
<P>
	The market watchdog agency has nearly doubled the size of its  
``Cyberforce'' team, which prowls the Internet on the lookout for 
fraud, to 200 people. 
</P>
<P>
	Sen. Judd Gregg, R-N.H., chairman of a Senate Appropriations  
subcommittee, recently proposed increasing the SEC's budget, now at 
$337.4 million, by $5.5 million next year to fight Internet fraud. 
That would bring the agency's funding to the level requested by the 
Clinton administration. 
</P>
<P>
	Beyond manpower and money, the SEC is also looking to expand its  
enforcement reach. 
</P>
<P>
	Walker and other officials laid out the scope of Internet  
investment fraud at recent hearings by a Senate investigative 
subcommittee. 
</P>
<P>
	Walker acknowledged that with 850 attorneys and other  
enforcement employees nationwide to pursue all types of financial 
fraud, including the online variety, ``We are certainly challenged, 
if not strained.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Soon after the hearings, Sen. Susan Collins, R-Maine, the  
subcommittee's chairwoman, proposed legislation that would: 
</P>
<P>
	--Give the SEC legal authority to ban brokers who violate the law  
not just from the brokerage industry but also from promoting 
stocks. A significant amount of Internet fraud has come from 
promoters touting high-risk, small-company stocks without 
disclosing that they were paid to do so. 
</P>
<P>
	--Allow the SEC to bring ``follow-up'' cases based on enforcement  
actions by state securities regulators. 
</P>
<P>
	The proposals are ``tools that would be very valuable for the  
SEC to have,'' said Bradley Skolnik, Indiana's securities 
commissioner and president-elect of the North American Securities 
Administrators Association. ``They are long overdue.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In its third nationwide ``sweep'' against Internet fraud, the  
SEC on Wednesday announced it had charged 18 people and eight 
companies with using the Web to sell bogus securities. 
</P>
<P>
	Online investment fraud also can take the form of stock-price  
manipulation schemes, deceptive stock touting, investment pyramid 
schemes, insider trading and unlicensed brokering or advising on 
investments. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990513.0193 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-13 22:22:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ga, Ark. Rivals in Poultry Business </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	GAINESVILLE, Ga. (AP) -- Visitors are often puzzled at first.  
Then they begin cackling at the notion -- a park dedicated to 
chickens. 
</P>
<P>
	Many take the short stroll from a local motel to the green space  
featuring a monument topped by a bronze rooster. They can read 
about the history of poultry and about the park, established in 
1977 by industry and city officials and believed to be the only one 
of its kind in the world. 
</P>
<P>
	Folks can pause on benches to ponder poultry or watch traffic go  
by on Jesse Jewell Parkway, named for a Depression-era farmer who 
was a Georgia poultry industry pioneer. 
</P>
<P>
	And, for good measure, the park and several city signs declare  
Gainesville ``the poultry capital of the world.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Gainesville has really built up around the poultry business,''  
said Doug Carnes, vice president for poultry operations at Mar-Jac 
Poultry Inc., which grows, processes and sells chickens by the 
hundreds of thousands each day. 
</P>
<P>
	Besides jobs on the farms and in the processing plants, the  
industry is tied to numerous related equipment, food-service, 
transportation and other companies in the state in which poultry is 
the No. 1 revenue-producing agricultural product. 
</P>
<P>
	However, amid all the poultry pride, farmers and officials here  
often hop over one fact -- that Arkansas has also claimed to rule 
the industry roost. 
</P>
<P>
	``We readily admit that for many, many years, we were No. 1. We  
have to also admit that for a small time, we settled back into 
second,'' said Tommy Irvin, Georgia's agriculture commissioner for 
30 years. 
</P>
<P>
	``Now, our expertise has gotten us back to No. 1, solidly, and  
we will remain there,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's been a back-and-forth situation; pretty much a  
good-natured bantering that goes on,'' explained Randall Smallwood, 
publisher of the Poultry &AMP; Eggs News in Gainesville. 
</P>
<P>
	Arkansas industry officials downplay the competition.  
</P>
<P>
	``We're not running a race with them,'' said Randy Wyatt,  
executive vice president of the Arkansas Poultry Federation. 
</P>
<P>
	He explained that a more important concern for industry farmers  
and officials both there and in Georgia is working together on 
environmental issues, safety and disease control. 
</P>
<P>
	``As an industry, the companies all seem to lay aside their  
competitive differences and focus on the issues that affect us 
all,'' Wyatt said. 
</P>
<P>
	Like the chicken-or-the-egg, the question of which state's  
poultry industry ranks first has been a matter of long debate. 
There are various measures of the industry; statistics include 
eggs, laying hens and turkeys. 
</P>
<P>
	The major segment, though, is broilers -- the young chickens  
ticketed for quick trips to dinner tables or fast-food bags. 
</P>
<P>
	Chris Messer, deputy state agricultural statistician for  
Georgia, said for broilers, Georgia led the nation from the 1940s 
through the 1960s, with Arkansas taking the lead in the '70s and 
holding it until recent years. 
</P>
<P>
	Complicating the rankings is the fact that even the broiler  
segment is cut up -- by number, by weight, and by dollar value. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. Department of Agriculture figures show Arkansas led in all  
three categories in 1994; in 1995, Georgia led in pounds and value; 
in '96, Arkansas led in number and pounds produced. But in 1997, 
Georgia took the lead in all three broiler categories. 
</P>
<P>
	The latest federal figures showed Georgia retained its  
leadership in all three broiler categories, producing 1.2 billion 
birds in the 16th consecutive year of growth, with total weight of 
5.9 billion pounds and value of $2.4 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	Georgia poultry officials were elated on April 29, when 1998  
figures showed the state No. 1 in all three categories again. 
</P>
<P>
	Arkansas, however, has other things going for it, said Wyatt,  
who called attention to Arkansas being the home base of chicken 
giant Tyson Foods and of the world-class agricultural research 
carried out at the University of Arkansas. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't know of anyone in Arkansas that calls themselves that  
(the poultry capital of the world),'' Wyatt said, then paused. 
``That's fine.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Another Arkansas response is to simply talk turkey. Georgia  
produced only 175,000 turkeys statewide in 1997 while Arkansas 
production is nearly 30 million birds a year. 
</P>
<P>
	Frank Jones, a poultry official in the University of Arkansas  
cooperative extension service, noted recently that while Arkansas 
ranks third nationally in turkeys (behind North Carolina and 
Minnesota), ``Georgia is not even on the map.'' 



</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990513.0194 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-13 14:52:34 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
