<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Zimmer Calls Yankees Team Meeting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Don Zimmer has two rules as a manager: Don't be  
late and run hard on every play. 
</P>
<P>
	Apparently there now is a third: Don't call players-only  
meetings. Because after breaking up one of those Wednesday night, 
the New York Yankees interim manager called a meeting of his own 
before Thursday's game against the Anaheim Angels. 
</P>
<P>
	``If they want to have a meeting, they can rent a ballroom when  
we get to Boston,'' Zimmer said. ``I don't believe in team meetings 
without coaches or managers unless its about playoff shares. 
</P>
<P>
	``When I think it's time to have a meeting, I'll have one.  
Today, it's time. It's not anything big. I just want to get their 
attention. It won't take more than three or four minutes.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The players didn't appear fazed about Zimmer breaking up their  
meeting and calling one of his own a day later. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was the same meeting. He just wanted to postpone it,''  
Shane Spencer said. ``The message was to get back to basics and 
have fun. Show up on time and play hard. That was pretty much it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	What has bothered Zimmer most is a failure by a few players to  
run out grounders consistently. Two weeks ago he heard a television 
analyst praise the Yankees for always hustling. 
</P>
<P>
	Lately, maybe because of frustration caused by hitting slumps,  
some players have slacked off. 
</P>
<P>
	``Once in a while I'll overlook it. But after three or four  
times, that's the end of overlooking,'' Zimmer said. ``It's a hell 
of a thing to be talking about, because that's what players are 
supposed to do.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But according to Zimmer they haven't. After losing their second  
straight game to the Angels on Wednesday, the Yankees slipped to 
7-7 in their last 14 games. In last year's record-setting season, 
the Yankees didn't have that kind of slump until mid-August when 
they were 18 1/2 games in front. 
</P>
<P>
	Zimmer reiterated that it is unfair to expect this year's team  
to keep up the pace of the 1998 bunch, but he has noticed some 
disturbing signs the last few days. 
</P>
<P>
	``There is no way we could win 126 games this season. We want to  
win the Eastern Division and I don't care if it is by one game, 18 
games or 19 games,'' Zimmer said. ``We have to start playing 
better. This is a better team than the way we have been playing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Yankees players, reportedly led by Joe Girardi, called a meeting  
after Wednesday night's 1-0 loss to the Angels. Zimmer, already in 
the middle of his postgame news conference, got wind of it, kicked 
out reporters and addressed the team quickly before breaking up the 
meeting. 
</P>
<P>
	Zimmer chose not to address the team in more depth Wednesday  
because he learned early on in his managing career it is sometimes 
better to deliver a message not in the heat of battle. 
</P>
<P>
	``When I was in San Diego, I'd come in after a game, close the  
clubhouse and rant and rave,'' he said. ``Now I'd rather calm down, 
come back the next day and say what I want to say to the team.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
