<HEADLINE> Torture Suspect Accused Years Ago </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ELEPHANT BUTTE, N.M. (AP) -- The daughter of a man accused of  
sexually torturing three women told police 13 years ago that her 
father abducted, tortured and sold women in Mexico. 
</P>
<P>
	FBI Agent Doug Beldon said Thursday that investigators could not  
substantiate the allegations of Glenda Jean Ray, now 32. 
</P>
<P>
	``The allegations were nonspecific,'' Beldon said. ``No victims  
were identified, and none came forward.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Ray is a co-defendant with her father, David Parker Ray, 59,  
in a sex-torture case that was opened in March when a naked woman 
fled Mr. Ray's mobile home wearing only a metal collar with a 
padlocked chain. 
</P>
<P>
	Two other alleged victims have since been located, and the three  
are the basis of 37 charges against Ray. Ms. Ray is charged with 12 
counts involving kidnapping and sexual assault. 
</P>
<P>
	A third suspect, Cynthia Lee Hendy, 39, initially was charged  
with 25 counts related to the case. Ms. Hendy, Ray's girlfriend, 
will plead guilty to five counts, including accessory and 
conspiracy charges, her lawyer said. 
</P>
<P>
	In documents released Wednesday, Ms. Hendy told investigators  
that Ray had admitted involvement in as many as 14 killings. 
</P>
<P>
	No bodies have been found. Ray denies the allegations.  
</P>
</TEXT>
