<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 8 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Clinton, Jiang Agree to Talk  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton and Chinese President Jiang  
Zemin agreed today to talk, as tensions with China over NATO's 
bombing of the Chinese Embassy in Belgrade appeared to be easing. 
Jiang had avoided talking to Clinton since the bombing Saturday, 
which killed three people. His readiness to talk was conveyed by 
Chinese Ambassador Li Zhaoxing, who took a condolence book to the 
White House for Clinton to sign. ``He indicated a willingness to 
talk, and we're setting up the call,'' said National Security 
Council spokesman David Leavy. It was unclear whether the call 
could be arranged before tomorrow. 

</P>
<P>
	Apaches Combat Ready, But Unused  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Apache attack helicopters that have been  
in Albania for more than three weeks are now ready for combat 
against Serb forces in Kosovo, but NATO's top commander has yet to 
ask President Clinton for the go-ahead, a senior Pentagon official 
said today. The question of when -- and even if -- the Apaches will 
go into action against Serb forces in Kosovo has been a topic of 
speculation for weeks, in large part because the low-flying 
helicopters are vulnerable to anti-aircraft fire and their use 
would raise considerably the risk of American battlefield 
casualties. 

</P>
<P>
	Senate GOP Retreats on Gun Control  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Senate Republicans retreated under pressure  
today on gun control, calling for fresh restrictions on sales at 
gun shows less than 24 hours after rejecting them. Democrats 
swiftly denounced the offer, saying it contained numerous loopholes 
despite the public outrage over last month's high school shootings 
in Colorado. ``It's the most Swiss-cheesy bill I've ever seen,'' 
said Sen. Charles Schumer, D-N.Y. The developments came as some 
Republicans expressed concern about the outcome of a series of 
votes yesterday. 

</P>
<P>
	Yugoslavia May Lose Some Net Access  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Parts of Yugoslavia could lose Internet access  
because an American satellite company might be ordered to stop 
transmitting into the country under a U.S. trade embargo. Loral 
Space and Communications Ltd. of New York said today it could be 
forced to cut transmissions into Yugoslavia from one of its 
satellites, which serves at least two of the country's major 
Internet providers.''To put it bluntly, we somehow got used to 
air-raid sirens, bombings and threats of invasion, but we don't 
know how we're going to survive without the Internet,'' said Alex 
Krstanovic, cofounder of Beonet, one of the affected Internet 
providers in Yugoslavia. 

</P>
<P>
	Yeltsin Impeachment Hearings Begin  
</P>
<P>
	MOSCOW (AP) -- President Boris Yeltsin came under fire today as  
lawmakers, opening impeachment hearings, hurled accusations of his 
carrying out policies that have claimed the lives of millions of 
Russians. The lower house of parliament, the State Duma, accused 
Yeltsin of destroying the Soviet Union, selling out Russia to the 
West and starting war in the breakaway province of Chechnya. 

</P>
<P>
	Boeing To Cut Up to 7,000 Jobs  
</P>
<P>
	ST. LOUIS (AP) -- A decline in orders for the F-15 fighter plane  
has prompted Boeing to eliminate 6,500 to 7,000 jobs by mid-2001 at 
its St. Louis plant. The company announced the moves today, saying 
it will consolidate factories that make three planes, including the 
F-15. The company said it expects the cuts to come from management 
and union members. Roughly 800-900 workers already have been given 
notice. The next round of layoff notices could go out as early as 
Monday, officials said. 

</P>
<P>
	Cell Used To Make New Liver Tissue  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Special bone marrow cells have been shown to  
convert into basic liver tissue, raising the possibility of one day 
using a patient's own marrow to repair failing livers, researchers 
say. In laboratory rat studies at the University of Pittsburgh 
Medical Center, researchers found in bone marrow a master, or stem, 
cell that under special conditions will convert itself into 
functioning liver tissue cells. Bryon Petersen, lead author of the 
study to be published tomorrow in the journal Science, said the 
work is the first step toward learning how to rescue failing livers 
using the body's own stem cells. 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Ends at Record of 11,107.19  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks were mostly higher today on reports  
showing moderate inflation, but some technology shares pulled the 
Nasdaq lower. The Dow Jones industrial average rose 106.82 points 
to end at 11,107.19, a new closing high. The Dow is up over 21 
percent this year. On the NYSE, gainers led losers 1,807-1,193. The 
Nasdaq was at 2,582.00, down 24.54. 

</P>
<P>
	Golf Great Gene Sarazen Dies at 97  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Gene Sarazen, one of only four men to win all  
four of golf's major pro titles, died today. He was 97. Sarazen 
died at a Naples, Fla., hospital from complications of pneumonia, 
said his lawyer. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by BRADLEY BROOKS  

</P>
