<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-13 06:50:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> No New Bombing in Belgrade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- NATO has not returned to bomb any targets in  
downtown Belgrade since Friday night's mistaken hit on the Chinese 
Embassy, but a U.S. military planner said the alliance has not 
sworn off the area. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's not a moratorium on any target that I know of,'' Maj.  
Gen. Charles Wald said at a briefing Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Wald, a strategic planner at the Joint Chiefs of Staff, said  
NATO hit a few targets outlying Belgrade in recent days, and took 
advantage of the clear sky to concentrate on hitting airfields, 
bridges and other targets in the disputed Serbian province of 
Kosovo. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't know of any order whatsoever from any place that I've  
heard of to stop,'' Wald said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Air Force general who is running the air war wants to target  
Belgrade and the leadership around Yugoslav President Slobodan 
Milosevic. 
</P>
<P>
	While carrying out the top military priority -- ``killing the  
army in Kosovo -- I also need to strike at the leadership and the 
people around Milosevic to compel them to change their behavior in 
Kosovo and accept the terms NATO has on the table,'' said Lt. Gen. 
Michael C. Short. 
</P>
<P>
	In a New York Times interview, Short noted it took weeks for  
NATO leaders to approve bombing of leadership targets. 
</P>
<P>
	``Airmen would have liked to have gone after that target set on  
the first night and sent a clear signal that we were taking the 
gloves off from the very beginning, that we were not going to 
incrementalize, that we're not going to try a little bit of this 
and see how you like it and try a little bit of that and see how 
you like it,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Short, whose son is an A-10 pilot flying in the conflict, said  
NATO fliers' work is complicated by the lack of troops on the 
ground. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think there's any question it affects me,'' the  
general said. ``I'd like to have that company commander down there 
on the ground saying to my son, the A-10 driver, 'OK, they are dug 
in 500 meters in front of me. I can see tanks. I can see troops 
massed on the other side of that village.''' 
</P>
<P>
	Privately, U.S. officials say military planners are double- and  
triple-checking maps and target lists in Belgrade, the Serbian 
capital and Milosevic's base. 
</P>
<P>
	The attack on the Chinese Embassy killed three, strained  
U.S.-Chinese relations and embarrassed NATO and the United States. 
Defense Secretary William Cohen and other officials blamed faulty 
maps and communications miscues for the error. 
</P>
<P>
	At the time, NATO said the bombing came during the heaviest  
onslaught on downtown Belgrade to date -- including bombing runs on 
government buildings and a hotel NATO identified as the 
headquarters of the alleged war criminal nicknamed Arkan. 
</P>
<P>
	NATO planes have flown close to 20,000 missions since the  
bombing began seven weeks ago, of which more than 5,000 were 
``strike,'' or actual bombing sorties, Wald said. The alliance has 
dropped or fired about 10,000 bombs or missiles, taken out 11 of 
Milosevic's 14 MiG-29s and dozens of tanks, Wald said. 
</P>
<P>
	About two-thirds of allied air strikes are carried out by U.S.  
planes and pilots. 
</P>
<P>
	Tuesday represented NATO's most successful day yet, Defense  
Secretary William Cohen said at the same briefing, noting the 
allies flew more than 600 missions and struck nearly 70 targets. 
</P>
<P>
	Gen. Hugh Shelton, chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff, also  
was upbeat, but predicted Serb military and police forces could 
withstand NATO bombing for ``quite some time.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Shelton noted that bombing has little effect on the sidearms and  
rifles carried by individual Serb troops. Those weapons are the 
main instruments used to evict Kosovo's ethnic Albanians from their 
homes in a two-month campaign of ethnic terror, U.S. officials say. 
</P>
<P>
	NATO began bombing in March to force Milosevic to accept a peace  
deal for Kosovo and allow refugees to return home. 
</P>
<P>
	Some 750,000 refugees crowd camps in bordering nations, while  
others are on the move inside Kosovo. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is possible that a force like the one Milosevic is using  
for ethnic cleansing and terror in Kosovo could hold out for quite 
some time,'' Shelton said. 
</P>
<P>
	He would not be more specific, and insisted the alliance is  
prepared to continue its intensified bombing for as long as 
necessary. 
</P>
<P>
	Also Wednesday, the Air Force and Navy activated another 2,173  
reservists and 35 more aircraft for the Kosovo conflict. That 
brought to 4,409 the number of reservists ordered to active duty so 
far. 
</P>
<P>
	Cohen said last week that a total of 5,035 reservists would be  
activated in the current round, but the services have yet to pick 
some of the units to be included, officials said. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton has authorized the Pentagon to activate as many as  
33,102 reservists. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990513.0209 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-13 08:15:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Comments on Resignation of Rubin </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Comments on Robert Rubin's resignation as treasury secretary:  

</P>
<P>
	House Speaker Dennis Hastert, R-Ill.:  
</P>
<P>
	``Secretary Rubin and I disagreed on many things, mainly the  
importance tax cuts play in keeping our economy growing. But we 
also agreed on many things, and he generally did his best to keep 
the more liberal elements of the Clinton-Gore administration in 
check.'' 
</P>
<P>
	----------	 
</P>
<P>
	Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss.:  
</P>
<P>
	``He has been a worthy adversary. He has been a good secretary  
of the Treasury, even though we don't agree on some issues. He's 
done an excellent job.'' 
</P>
<P>
	----------	 
</P>
<P>
	Senate Minority Leader Tom Daschle, D-S.D.:  
</P>
<P>
	``His leadership was crucial in containing the financial crisis  
in Asia and restoring stability to the global economy.'' 
</P>
<P>
	----------	 
</P>
<P>
	Senate Banking Committee Chairman Phil Gramm, R-Texas:  
</P>
<P>
	``Of all the officials in the Clinton administration, he has had  
more credibility with me, and I think with Congress, than any other 
official, and justifiably so.'' 
</P>
<P>
	----------	 
</P>
<P>
	Rep. Charles Rangel of New York, top Democrat on the House Ways  
and Means Committee: 
</P>
<P>
	``He had a quality that formed a natural bridge of confidence  
between the skepticism that normally exists between House members 
and the executive branch. He never held himself out as more 
important than he really is. So many of us respond as if we know 
what makes the Earth spin.'' 
</P>
<P>
	--------	 
</P>
<P>
	House Ways and Means Committee Chairman Bill Archer, R-Texas:  
</P>
<P>
	``Secretary Rubin has been a strong and sometimes solitary voice  
within the Clinton administration for open markets and fiscal 
discipline, which has helped keep our economy strong.'' 
</P>
<P>
	--------	 
</P>
<P>
	Senate Finance Committee Chairman William Roth, R-Del.:  
</P>
<P>
	``His stewardship has been a good stabilizing force in a  
turbulent world economy.'' 
</P>
<P>
	--------	 
</P>
<P>
	House Minority Leader Dick Gephardt, D-Mo.:  
</P>
<P>
	``Bob Rubin deserves much of the credit for the economic  
policies which have made our economy the envy of the world ... his 
judgment and intelligence will be greatly missed.'' 
</P>
<P>
	----------	 
</P>
<P>
	Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan of New York, top Democrat on the  
Finance Committee: 
</P>
<P>
	``Robert E. Rubin has set a standard of public service which has  
been desperately needed in this time and will be there for 
generations to come. (First Treasury Secretary Alexander) Hamilton 
could have asked for no finer successor.'' 
</P>
<P>
	----------	 
</P>
<P>
	Sen. Charles Schumer, D-N.Y.:  
</P>
<P>
	``Bob Rubin has been the shining star of this administration. He  
instilled confidence in our markets from Main Street to Wall Street 
and has brought the two together like no one else has.'' 
</P>
<P>
	----------	 
</P>
<P>
	Sen. Paul Sarbanes of Maryland, senior Democrat on the Senate  
Banking Committee: 
</P>
<P>
	``I especially have deep respect for his efforts to bring all  
Americans into the mainstream of economic life. His commitment to 
opportunity for all has been a hallmark of his service.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
