<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> EPA Says Pollution Up After Decline </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The amount of toxic chemicals released into  
the environment by industrial plants increased by 2.2 percent in 
1997, ending years of steady decline, the Environmental Protection 
Agency said Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	The increase in total releases of 644 toxic chemicals by 21,490  
facilities was attributed largely to plants sending more metal 
wastes to landfills and other disposal sites, instead of to 
recycling centers. That was because in 1997, the year the latest 
data covered, metal recycling prices increased, officials said. 
</P>
<P>
	The industries covered by the annual reporting requirement said  
that in 1997 they put 2.58 billion pounds of toxic waste into the 
air and water and onto land, including wastes injected deep into 
the earth. That compares with 2.52 billion pounds in 1996, 
according to revised figures reported for that year. 
</P>
<P>
	Before 1997, releases had been trending down each year since the  
reporting began for the year 1988, although companies are 
generating more waste during production. Still, toxic emissions 
have dropped by almost 43 percent since the reporting requirement 
began, the agency said. 
</P>
<P>
	``And we believe it will continue to decline in the long term,''  
said EPA Administrator Carol Browner. 
</P>
<P>
	The number of chemicals on which releases must be reported has  
doubled to 644 chemicals since the Toxic Inventory Released data 
were first collected. Next year, seven additional industrial 
sectors, including utilities, will have to report releases. 
</P>
<P>
	The EPA said air pollution accounted for nearly 52 percent of  
the waste releases, or 1.3 billion pounds, a decline of 127 million 
pounds from 1996. 
</P>
<P>
	About 30 percent of the total, or 785 million pounds, was  
disposed of on land, including landfills, on-site disposal and 
transfers to waste brokers. 
</P>
<P>
	An additional 218 million pounds, or 8.5 percent, was released  
into lakes and streams, an increase of 41 million pounds. Nearly 
233 million pounds, or 9 percent, was injected deep into the 
ground. 
</P>
<P>
	Texas had the largest amount of releases, 268 million pounds;  
followed by Ohio, 213 million pounds; Louisiana, 188 million 
pounds; Illinois, 134 million pounds; and Pennsylvania, 133 million 
pounds. 
</P>
<P>
	The chemical industry accounts for the largest volume of toxic  
releases, followed by primary metals, and the pulp and paper 
industries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
