<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 4:35 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	China Urges Defiance of US Bullying  
</P>
<P>
	BEIJING (AP) -- China's president accused the United States today  
of seeking global dominance and urged nations worldwide to defy 
American bullying and create a new just order. The harsh words 
showed just how much the embassy bombing in Yugoslavia has damaged 
Chinese political will for smooth U.S. relations. The statement 
marked a turnabout for President Jiang Zemin, who last year claimed 
credit for engineering a rapprochement with Washington. It was the 
first time in three years of improving relations that Jiang has 
outright called the United States a term China reserves for enemy 
countries -- hegemonist. 

</P>
<P>
	Serb Pullout Called Insignificant  
</P>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Western authorities today called the  
departure of 120 Yugoslav troops from Kosovo an insignificant move 
and possibly a sham. The troops broke into grins and waved for 
reporters who had been invited to watch. It was evidently an 
attempt to counter widespread disbelief of a Yugoslav army 
withdrawal order last Sunday. NATO and U.S. officials say a partial 
pullout from Kosovo won't stop their seven-week-old air campaign 
and doesn't satisfy their demands for a full troop withdrawal from 
the southern Serb province. 

</P>
<P>
	Senate GOP Backpedal on Gun Vote  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Senate GOP leaders today considered reversing  
yesterday's vote and requiring background checks for all private 
firearm sales at gun shows. ``For the life of me,'' President 
Clinton said on the no-vote, ``I can't figure out how they did 
it.'' He said there was ``simply no excuse for letting criminals 
get arms at gun shows they can't get at gun stores.'' An aide to 
Sen. Larry Craig, R-Idaho, a board member of the National Rifle 
Association, said today that because of the uproar among GOP 
senators, Craig will offer an amendment requiring background checks 
on all sales at gun shows. 

</P>
<P>
	Impeachment of Yeltsin Begins  
</P>
<P>
	MOSCOW (AP) -- Russian lawmakers began impeachment hearings today  
to remove Boris Yeltsin, claiming the president is guilty of 
treason, first-degree murder and plotting to sell Russia out to the 
West. Political leaders say the chances of impeaching Yeltsin 
soared after the president outraged lawmakers yesterday by sacking 
the country's popular prime minister, Yevgeny Primakov. A vote on 
impeachment in the lower chamber of parliament could be held as 
early as tomorrow. The charge that he launched the botched 1994-96 
war in Chechnya is the one most likely to attract enough votes for 
impeachment. 

</P>
<P>
	American Airlines Hit With Suit  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- American Airlines, the nation's second-largest  
air carrier, was charged today with monopolizing airline passenger 
service to and from Dallas-Fort Worth International Airport. The 
Justice Department charged American with repeatedly trying to drive 
small, startup airlines out of the DFW airport, the nation's third 
largest, by saturating their routes with flights of its own and 
cutting fares. This is the first predatory-practices case brought 
since airlines were deregulated in 1978. 

</P>
<P>
	Tobacco Industry Wins Again in Court  
</P>
<P>
	KANSAS CITY, Mo. (AP) -- A federal jury handed the tobacco  
industry its second victory in four days today, deciding Brown &AMP; 
Williamson Tobacco Corp. was not at fault in the case of a man who 
died of lung cancer in 1995 after smoking Kools. Charles Steele's 
family had sued for $26 million, claiming the nation's 
third-largest tobacco company sold him an unreasonably dangerous 
product. Jury foreman Gary White said Steele ``was quite aware of 
the dangers, but the pleasures outweighed the dangers.'' 

</P>
<P>
	Cellular Phones To Add 911 Routing  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Responding to concerns that cellular calls to  
911 do not always go through, federal regulators took action today 
to eventually increase the chances such calls reach emergency 
dispatchers. The Federal Communications Commission is requiring new 
-- not existing -- analog cellular phones to have software routing a 
911 call to another carrier when the customer's own company or one 
designated to handle ``roaming'' calls cannot complete the call. 
Fast-growing digital phones -- 18.8 million now in use -- are not 
covered by the rules. 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Ends at Record of 11,107.19  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks were mostly higher today on reports  
showing moderate inflation, but some technology shares pulled the 
Nasdaq lower. The Dow Jones industrial average rose 106.82 points 
to end at 11,107.19, a new closing high. The Dow is up over 21 
percent this year. On the NYSE, gainers led losers 1,807-1,193. The 
Nasdaq was at 2,582.00, down 24.54. 

</P>
<P>
	Golf Great Gene Sarazen Dies at 97  
</P>
<P>
	NAPLES, Fla. (AP) -- Gene Sarazen, the former caddie who competed  
against everyone from Bobby Jones to Jack Nicklaus and was one of 
only four men to win all four of golf's major professional 
championships, died today at age 97. Sarazen died at Naples 
Community Hospital from complications of pneumonia, his lawyer 
said. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by GABRIEL MADWAY  

</P>
</TEXT>
