<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Cellular Phones To Add 911 Routing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Responding to concerns that cellular calls to  
911 do not always go through, federal regulators took action 
Thursday to eventually increase the chances such calls reach 
emergency dispatchers. 
</P>
<P>
	The Federal Communications Commission is requiring new -- not  
existing -- analog cellular phones to have software routing a 911 
call to another carrier when the customer's own company or one 
designated to handle ``roaming'' calls cannot complete the call. 
Phones usually are not programmed to do that. 
</P>
<P>
	Manufacturers selling phones in the United States need to make  
changes to new analog cellular phones and new ``dual mode'' phones 
(only for operating in the analog mode) within nine months. 
</P>
<P>
	Fast-growing digital phones -- 18.8 million now in use -- are not  
covered by the rules. Digital phones are more complex and 
technology does not exist to deal with the call completion problem, 
FCC officials said. 
</P>
<P>
	The rules do not require the roughly 50.4 million analog  
cellular phones now in use to be retrofitted. But they do not 
prevent a carrier from retrofitting existing phones, although 
neither regulators nor industry officials are aware of any company 
planning to do so. 
</P>
<P>
	The rules also do not prevent a cellular carrier from swapping  
out existing phones with new ones containing the switching the FCC 
requires. 
</P>
<P>
	People buy a new cell phone every two to three years, a FCC  
attorney said. 
</P>
<P>
	Because there are some areas where no carrier has an antenna to  
pick up a call, the rules cannot guarantee a 911 call will be 
completed. Still, FCC Chairman Bill Kennard said the action 
``increases the number of these type of critical calls that are 
completed.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Cellular Telecommunications Industry Association and the  
Association of Public-Safety Communications Officials, whose 
members include 911 dispatchers, hailed the FCC's action. 
</P>
<P>
	More than 98,000 calls to 911 are made each day on cell phones.  
Most are completed. But some -- neither the FCC nor the cellular 
industry has estimates on the number -- do not go through. 
</P>
<P>
	There are a number of reasons why that happens: A company has a  
``dead zone,'' meaning it does not have an antenna in a particular 
area to pick up the call; there is congestion on the cellular 
network; or interference from buildings, mountains or other objects 
can block the call. 
</P>
<P>
	The FCC identified three technologies that should accomplish the  
switching it requires. But the agency did not dictate a specific 
one for companies to use. 
</P>
<P>
	Separately, the FCC exempted analog cable TV boxes from rules  
giving customers the option of buying them in stores. Customers 
usually lease the boxes through their local cable company. Digital 
boxes eventually will be sold in stores. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
