<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Markets Take Rubin News in Stride </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- After a few nervous moments Wednesday, Wall  
Street took the news of Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin's 
long-rumored resignation in stride. 
</P>
<P>
	Market watchers had wondered whether a change in the ranks of  
U.S. policy makers would be the pin that popped the nation's 
economic balloon. 
</P>
<P>
	And at first, reports of Rubin's resignation did hit the market  
hard. The Dow plummeted 213 points and bonds also tumbled. But the 
markets soon recovered. The Dow ended 27.21 points lower at 
10,998.94. Bond prices were only slightly lower. 
</P>
<P>
	Among the reasons for the muted response: the economy is going  
strong, and Rubin has a well-regarded successor. 
</P>
<P>
	``The issue for the market is: Are we changing a person or  
changing a policy?'' said Jeffrey Applegate, chief investment 
strategist at Lehman Brothers in New York. ``At the end of the day, 
this move does not seem to indicate a change in policy.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rubin will be succeeded by his deputy, Lawrence Summers, who has  
had a strong background in academia and a gradually expanding role 
in the Clinton administration. Last year, he was a key player in 
the administration's efforts to stem the Asian financial crisis. 
</P>
<P>
	Stuart Eizenstat, an undersecretary at the State Department,  
will replace Summers. 
</P>
<P>
	Most market watchers expect the new team to extend the policies  
that made Rubin a hero among business leaders. 
</P>
<P>
	``Larry Summers will bring great experience, skill and  
continuity to this critical role,'' David H. Komansky, chairman and 
chief executive at Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co., said in a statement. 
</P>
<P>
	Investment banks and management professionals have lionized  
Rubin, who earned millions as a banker and co-chairman of Goldman 
Sachs &AMP; Co. before joining the administration. 
</P>
<P>
	The policies of Rubin and Federal Reserve Chairman Alan  
Greenspan produced a stellar investment climate. Strong growth, low 
inflation and low unemployment have combined in an unprecedented 
period of economic expansion. Since Rubin became treasury secretary 
in 1995, the Dow Jones industrial average has soared from just 
under 4,000 to more than 11,000. 
</P>
<P>
	``Wall Street has taken this in stride because he's leaving in  
very good stead,'' said Joseph V. Battipaglia, chief investment 
strategist at Gruntal &AMP; Co. 
</P>
<P>
	Analysts also noted that Greenspan, whose third term ends in  
June 2000, is expected to stay for a fourth four-year term. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
