<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Mortgage Rates Up for Fourth Month / National Mortgage Survey  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The average interest rate on 30-year  
fixed-rate mortgages rose for the fourth consecutive week to the 
highest level in two months. 
</P>
<P>
	The average this week was 7.10 percent, up from 7.02 percent the  
previous week, Freddie Mac, the mortgage company said Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	So far this year, rates have fluctated between 6.74 percent at  
the end of January and 7.11 percent in mid-March. 
</P>
<P>
	Fifteen-year mortgages, a popular option for refinancing,  
averaged 6.71 percent this week, up from 6.61 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	On one-year adjustable-rate mortgages, lenders were asking an  
average initial rate of 5.71 percent, up from 5.68 the week before. 
</P>
<P>
	The rates do not include add-on fees known as points, which  
averaged at or just over 1 percent of the loan amount for all three 
types of mortgages. 

</P>
</TEXT>
