<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Young Entrepreneurs Going High-Tech </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- A tiny teddy bear dangling from her backpack,  
Jasmine Jordan chatted easily about business plans and corporate 
sponsorship for the magazine she runs -- at age 15. 
</P>
<P>
	She's a child of the inner city, the kind of person who  
President Clinton says deserves more attention from Americans 
during these boom times. 
</P>
<P>
	But she's already a success story -- a graduate of a pioneering  
program that teaches low-income youths to run their own businesses. 
</P>
<P>
	Jasmine watched Wednesday as the 10-year-old National Foundation  
for Teaching Entrepreneurship unveiled its biggest project -- an 
educational software program developed by Microsoft Corp. that the 
foundation hopes to distribute to 1 million youths by 2005. 
</P>
<P>
	``If you can get a community that's technologically savvy and  
knows how to generate wealth, you can turn around a generation,'' 
said Steve Mariotti, president of the New York-based foundation, 
which has 23,000 graduates. ``It's the ultimate policy weapon.'' 
</P>
<P>
	After a lifetime of such work, Mariotti doesn't place much hope  
in political promises such as Clinton's proposed ``new markets 
initiative,'' announced Tuesday, to drum up corporate investment in 
neglected areas. 
</P>
<P>
	What works, said Mariotti, are specifics. The foundation, for  
instance, develops entrepreneurship in schools and in after-school 
programs. It funds teen-age businesses. 
</P>
<P>
	Now, its new software program will teach even more youths about  
the stock market, how to raise capital and write a balance sheet. 
</P>
<P>
	Ira Simmonds uses foundation materials to teach a class in  
entrepreneurship at Frederick Douglass Academy, a revered public 
school in Harlem. And he's seen what it can do. 
</P>
<P>
	Simmonds recalled one student, who used to do his homework, not  
much more, and sometimes not even that. After taking the class, 
he's eager to be at school, and asks lots of questions. 
</P>
<P>
	``One of the most important aspects of the course has been to  
teach them they can control their destiny,'' said Simmonds. 
</P>
<P>
	For teen-agers, entrepreneurship also happens to be hot. A 1996  
Gallup poll found that nearly seven out of 10 high school students 
want to start and run their own business, mainly so that they can 
be their own boss. 
</P>
<P>
	Yet at a time when ideas are the most important capital, 85  
percent of teen-agers said they were taught little to practically 
nothing on entrepreneurship in school. 
</P>
<P>
	Given a few minutes Wednesday with Microsoft executive Jeff  
Raikes at the company's New York offices, Jasmine and others chosen 
as the foundation's ``Entrepreneurs of the Year'' got down to 
business quickly. They peppered him with questions about the 
Internet and their ventures. 
</P>
<P>
	``How can having a Web site help my business on a local level?''  
asked Harold Deloach, a 1989 graduate, now 26, who said he wanted 
to keep his Philadelphia electrical repair business small for now. 
</P>
<P>
	Raikes answered that even if Deloach doesn't want to advertise  
on-line, he can use a Web site to find suppliers or better business 
deals. 
</P>
<P>
	Microsoft has contributed $2 million in cash or software to the  
foundation in the last three years. It's good public relations, of 
course, and a key way to invest in the highly entrepreneurial 
high-tech field. 
</P>
<P>
	But Raikes suggested that the foundation draws Microsoft  
volunteers in 13 cities because it provides a tangible way to help 
very intangible problems. 
</P>
<P>
	``This provides the tools for these kids to pursue their  
dreams,'' said Raikes, a group vice president at Microsoft. 
``That's so different from the way society addresses these 
issues.'' 
</P>
<P>
	For Jasmine, a New Yorker whose father died recently and whose  
mother suffers from medical problems, the program has allowed her 
to reap much more than extra money. 
</P>
<P>
	``Through my magazine, I've been introduced to an entire new  
world,'' she said as she showed off ``Tools for Living,'' her 
bi-monthly for young entrepreneurs that now has a circulation of 
16,000. ``I plan to run it into my twenties and thirties.'' 


</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
