<HEADLINE> Brewery Plans To Hire New Workers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MILWAUKEE (AP) -- Miller Brewing Co. plans to add more than 100  
workers this summer, in part because of expected production 
increases now that it has acquired four new brands from other 
breweries, officials said. 
</P>
<P>
	The brewery plans to hire 112 new employees for its Milwaukee  
facility starting in June, spokesman Michael Brophy said Wednesday. 
It is the first time in 20 years the company has hired new 
employees at that facility. 
</P>
<P>
	The company currently has 830 employees at its Milwaukee  
brewery. It could add about 100 union employees and 12 supervisors, 
a 13.5 percent increase, Brophy said. 
</P>
<P>
	The brewery needs more workers because it is making more beer as  
a result of the sale in April of Stroh Brewery Co. to Miller and 
Pabst Brewing Co. 
</P>
<P>
	In the deal, Miller acquired two brands from Stroh and two from  
Pabst. Miller also got Pabst's brewery in Tumwater, Wash. 
</P>
<P>
	Besides the new hires, Miller plans to spend $11 million to add  
a new canning line to the brewery and will expand its brewing 
operation to weekends. 
</P>
</TEXT>
