<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Consults on Social Security </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton met with a group of  
Democratic lawmakers at the White House on Thursday to discuss ways 
he might help revive chances for congressional action to shore up 
Social Security this year. 
</P>
<P>
	``The president wanted to get their views on what the most  
productive strategy would be for moving forward,'' said Gene 
Sperling, Clinton's top economic adviser. 
</P>
<P>
	The Democrats who met with Clinton -- all members of the House  
Ways and Means Committee, which oversees the nation's retirement 
program -- said they recommended fleshing out the Social Security 
rescue plan Clinton outlined in his State of the Union speech, and 
they offered to present it officially as legislation. That is 
something the White House has not yet done. 
</P>
<P>
	``The president has a proposal and we can't legislate with  
proposals,'' said Rep. Charlie Rangel, R-N.Y., the senior Democrat 
on the committee. 
</P>
<P>
	It is unclear whether more specifics and formal language can  
help move Clinton's plan forward. Republicans have criticized some 
of its basic premises, including government-managed investment of 
some of Social Security's cash reserves in the stock market. 
</P>
<P>
	``If it is just warming up again the same plan, I don't see that  
as the answer to the problem,'' said the committee chairman, Rep. 
Bill Archer, R-Texas. 
</P>
<P>
	Archer, who has come up with a rival proposal that would let  
individual Americans invest Social Security's current surpluses in 
personal accounts, said it will take a show of willingness by 
Clinton to compromise to prompt Republican action. 
</P>
<P>
	Democrats and Republicans both say they want to take steps to  
avert a cash shortage expected to threaten Social Security once 
baby boomers, now in middle age, retire. 
</P>
<P>
	However, several weeks ago, Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott,  
R-Miss, said he did not think anything can be accomplished this 
year because he and others in his party felt Clinton had failed to 
take a strong enough lead on the sensitive political issue. 
</P>
<P>
	Republicans leaders instead are pushing a fallback plan that  
would at least put legislative hurdles in the way of lawmakers who 
might seek to spend any government surpluses that come from Social 
Security taxes -- as opposed to income taxes -- on other programs or 
tax cuts. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, Clinton's top advisers on Social Security have held a  
series of meetings to discuss the administration's next move. 
</P>
<P>
	Those familiar with the meetings say that among options still  
being discussed within the administration is the possibility that 
Clinton could offer some adjustments to his plan in answer to 
criticisms that have been raised. 
</P>
<P>
	``The president is looking for something to indicate he's  
willing to negotiate with Congress,'' said John Rother, a lobbyist 
for the AARP, the nation's largest organization of older adults. 
``But just as importantly, he is looking for something that would 
make it clear to the public that he is continuing to make an effort 
here.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
