<HEADLINE> Stock Markets Mixed in Asia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HONG KONG (AP) -- Asian markets ended mixed Thursday, hurt by  
apprehension over the resignation of U.S. Treasury Security Robert 
Rubin. 
</P>
<P>
	Tokyo, the region's largest market, fell as Rubin's resignation  
and the dismissal of Russian Prime Minister Yevgeny Primakov 
dragged down market sentiment. 
</P>
<P>
	The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average lost 96.11 points,  
or 0.57 percent, ending the day at 16,851.25. On Wednesday, the 
average rose 1.22 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Japanese officials reacted quickly to word of Rubin's departure,  
downplaying the possible impact on financial markets. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't expect U.S. policy to change,'' Finance Minister  
Kiichi Miyazawa said. 
</P>
<P>
	Many investors also sat on the sidelines amid expectations of  
poor corporate earnings reports, traders said. Most Japanese 
companies will release profit results later this month for the 
fiscal year ended in March. 
</P>
<P>
	In currency dealings, the U.S. dollar rose against the Japanese  
yen. In late trading, the dollar bought 121.58 yen, up 0.72 yen 
from late Wednesday in Tokyo and also higher than its late New York 
level of 120.95 yen overnight. 
</P>
<P>
	In Hong Kong, shares rose slightly, led by banking giant HSBC  
Holdings, whose recent share placement boosted market confidence. 
</P>
<P>
	The blue-chip Hang Seng Index was up 40.7 points, or 0.31  
percent, at 13,053.67. On Wednesday, the index rose 1.1 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	HSBC on Tuesday completed Asia's largest equity fund raising so  
far this year, offering 88 million new shares valued at U.S. $3 
billion. 
</P>
<P>
	The share placement was to cover part of the U.S. $10.3 billion  
cost of buying Republic New York Corp. and soaked up much of the 
market's liquidity Thursday, traders said. 
</P>
<P>
	In Seoul, share prices dived, with the key index plunging 4  
percent on higher interest rates and worries over massive rights 
offering plans by local companies next month, analysts said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Kospi index fell 30.76 points to 742.37.  
</P>
<P>
	ELSEWHERE:   	
</P>
<P>
	BANGKOK: Shares fell as investors cashed in on recent gains. The  
SET index fell 9.67 points, or 2.0 percent, to 476.89. 
</P>
<P>
	KUALA LUMPUR: Shares rose on a continued bull run. The Kuala  
Lumpur Composite Index was up 9.55 points, or 1.3 percent, at 
733.53. 
</P>
<P>
	MANILA: Shares fell on news of Rubin's resignation and  
Primakov's dismissal. The PSE index fell 57.51 points, or 2.2 
percent, to 2,522.01. 
</P>
<P>
	SINGAPORE: Shares fell as major institutional investors adopted  
a wait-and-see attitude. The STI fell 20.19 points, or 1.1 percent, 
at 1,868.83. 
</P>
<P>
	TAIPEI: Shares fell for the third straight session as investors  
continued to cash in on recent gains. The Weighted Price Index was 
down 32.21 points, or 0.43 percent, to 7,416.20. 
</P>
<P>
	SYDNEY: Shares rose on late buying of some of the country's  
major banks. The All Ordinaries Index was up 14.6 points, or 0.48 
percent, at 3,029.6. 
</P>
<P>
	WELLINGTON: Shares rose on gains made by market heavyweight  
Telecom Corp. of New Zealand Ltd. The NZSE-40 Capital Index was up 
23.65 points, or 1.1 percent, at 2,219.15. 
</P>
<P>
	JAKARTA: Markets were closed due to a national holiday.  

</P>
</TEXT>
