<HEADLINE> 2 Ex-Prosecutors Acquitted in Ill. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WHEATON, Ill. (AP) -- A judge dismissed charges Thursday against  
two of seven law enforcement veterans accused of railroading a man 
for the 1983 murder of a 10-year-old girl. 
</P>
<P>
	Judge William Kelly said there was insufficient evidence to  
prove that ex-DuPage County prosecutors Robert Kilander and Patrick 
King were part of a conspiracy to send the man to death row. 
Kilander is now a county judge and King a federal prosecutor. 
</P>
<P>
	But the judge rejected motions to acquit the other five  
defendants -- an ex-prosecutor and four sheriff's deputies, who will 
begin presenting their case next Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	They are charged with conspiring to frame Rolando Cruz by lying,  
creating evidence and withholding information that could have 
helped his defense. Cruz was twice convicted and spent nearly a 
decade on death row before being acquitted at his third trial in 
1995. 
</P>
<P>
	Legal experts say they cannot recall another trial in which  
prosecutors were charged with crimes for how they handled a case. 
</P>
<P>
	Special prosecutor William Kunkle, who rested his case Thursday,  
declined comment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
