<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> UCSD Athletics Director Resigns </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN DIEGO (AP) -- Judy Sweet, the first woman president of the  
NCAA, resigned Wednesday as athletics director at the University of 
California, San Diego after 24 years to return to a full-time 
faculty position. 
</P>
<P>
	A trailblazer in college athletics, Sweet was one of the first  
women to direct a combined men's and women's program when she 
became athletic director at California-San Diego in 1975. UCSD won 
24 national championships, 31 runner-up trophies and had 30 
third-place finishes in the Division III. 
</P>
<P>
	``I am truly grateful for the privilege to have served as UCSD  
director of athletics for 24 years, and the opportunity to be a 
part of the tremendous growth and success that the athletics 
program has experienced,'' Sweet said in a statement. 
</P>
<P>
	Sweet's resignation will be effective June 30, when she will  
return to full-time teaching at the La Jolla campus. The university 
planned to launch a national search for an athletics director 
immediately. 
</P>
<P>
	Sweets is a 1969 graduate of Wisconsin who earned a master's  
degree from Arizona in 1972. In 1973, she joined UCSD, where she 
was women's badminton coach and assistant athletic director before 
getting the top job. 
</P>
<P>
	By 1983, just three years after the bitterly divided NCAA  
membership voted to make room for women's sports and women 
administrators, she was named to the policy-making NCAA Council. 
She was in line by 1988 for the post of secretary-treasurer, the 
highest NCAA office any woman had attained. 
</P>
<P>
	She completed her two-year term as NCAA president in 1993. A  
year later, she was one of four finalists for the post of executive 
director of the NCAA. 
</P>
<P>
	She was a part of the most eventful era of change in college  
sports history. During her tenure as NCAA president, NCAA schools 
tightened academic requirements and loosened time demands for 
athletes, reduced coaching staffs and trimmed back scholarships 
limits. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
