<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Congress Agrees on $11.7B for Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- House-Senate negotiators want to give  
President Clinton nearly twice the money he wants for the 
bombardment of Yugoslavia, but the package has grown into a 
hodgepodge of provisions dealing with tobacco, steel and other 
issues that is raising doubts about its immediate fate. 
</P>
<P>
	Bargainers from the two chambers expected to meet again today  
amid fading hopes of striking a compromise bill, whipping it 
through Congress and shipping it to Clinton for his signature by 
week's end. 
</P>
<P>
	Wednesday afternoon, lawmakers agreed to spend $11.7 billion for  
the fighting over Kosovo, the refugees and Balkan states that have 
accepted them, and to strengthen a slew of Pentagon programs, 
dwarfing the $6 billion Clinton requested. That is the biggest 
chunk of the bill, and the item with the strongest political 
appeal. 
</P>
<P>
	The measure also contains nearly $1 billion he sought to help  
Honduras and other Central American countries rebuild from last 
fall's Hurricane Mitch, plus $566 million to aid U.S. farmers 
struggling from low commodities prices. 
</P>
<P>
	But by the time an often surly bargaining session ended just  
before 1 a.m., the bill's price tag had surged toward $15 billion 
and confusion reigned. Lawmakers added tobacco language opposed by 
the administration, a new loan program for smaller steel companies 
unpopular with conservatives, and still faced questions about how 
parts of the package would be paid for. 
</P>
<P>
	Senate Appropriations Committee Chairman Ted Stevens, R-Alaska,  
said he did not know what would happen next beyond a meeting of GOP 
leaders ``to figure out what we're going to do.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Sure it's in trouble,'' said Rep. David Obey of Wisconsin, top  
Democrat on the House Appropriations Committee. ``It's a mess.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Despite an earlier veto threat from White House officials, the  
bargainers approved a provision by Sen. Kay Bailey Hutchison, 
R-Texas, that would bar the federal government from laying claim to 
any of the $246 billion from settlements that states have reached 
with the tobacco industry. Clinton planned to billions of those 
funds for federal programs, but governors -- backed by many members 
of Congress -- want to keep it for the states. 
</P>
<P>
	``He won't veto,'' predicted Hutchison in an interview, saying  
it would jeopardize ``money for troops in Kosovo doing his 
mission.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But White House budget office spokeswoman Linda Ricci chided  
Congress for ``trying to take advantage of emergency needs in 
Kosovo and Central America by loading up this bill with everybody's 
pet projects.'' 
</P>
<P>
	She added, ``We've warned them not to load up this legislation''  
with unnecessary provisions. 
</P>
<P>
	Another complication was the bargainers' acceptance of a  
provision by Sen. Robert Byrd of West Virginia, top Democrat from 
the Senate appropriations panel, for $140 million that would back 
$1 billion in loans for small steel producers hurt by low-price 
imports. The provision is sure to prove unpopular with 
conservatives. 
</P>
<P>
	Negotiators rejected a similar proposal by Sen. Pete Domenici,  
R-N.M., for $125 million to create a $500 million loan program for 
oil and gas companies. 
</P>
<P>
	The measure also has $100 million for Jordan and $900 million  
for the costs of recent tornadoes in the Midwest and for a cushion 
for future disasters. 
</P>
<P>
	In other decisions,  
</P>
<P>
	--Kansas GOP Sens. Pat Roberts and Sam Brownback lost an effort  
to forgive more than $200 million in interest and penalties owed by 
the state's natural gas producers ruled to have overcharged 
customers. 
</P>
<P>
	--Stevens and Sen. Frank Murkowski, R-Alaska, accepted a  
compromise involving fishing restrictions in parts of their state's 
Glacier Bay National Park and a $26 million buyout for fish 
processors and others. 
</P>
<P>
	--Bargainers dropped a provision by Sen. Charles Robb, D-Va., for  
up to $40 million for families of the victims of a 1998 accident in 
which a Marine jet sent an Italian ski gondola crashing down a 
mountainside, killing 20 people. 
</P>
<P>
	To Clinton's $6 billion defense request, funds lawmakers added  
included $1.8 billion for a troop pay raise that would begin in 
January; $819 million to help Kosovo's refugees and Baltic states 
bordering Yugoslavia; $475 million to modernize overseas military 
bases to $475 million; and $200 million for the Coast Guard. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
