<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Titans' Matthews Agrees to Contract </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) -- At 37, Bruce Matthews isn't thinking  
about retirement. Neither are the Tennessee Titans, who signed the 
16-year veteran offensive lineman to a four-year contract Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Terms of the deal weren't disclosed.  
</P>
<P>
	``If I finish this contract, I'd be very impressed,'' Matthews  
said. ``I guess the natural thing is to think about retirement, 
because obviously it's going to happen. But I still enjoy it. I get 
excited for the games.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Matthews has spent his entire career with the franchise and has  
never missed a game due to injury. He became an unrestricted free 
agent at the end of last season, but indicated a desire to stay 
with the team. 
</P>
<P>
	``We wanted him badly to finish his career here,'' Titans  
general manager Floyd Reese said. ``In this world of unrestricted 
free agency, it may never happen again.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Matthews, who doesn't have an agent, negotiated directly with  
the Titans. 
</P>
<P>
	``Bruce has been in the league long enough to understand what  
the numbers are, and where he fits,'' Reese said. 
</P>
<P>
	Matthews ranks 11th on the NFL's career games list with 248 and  
can pass Jackie Slater this season for the most games played by an 
offensive lineman (259). He has started 244 games playing all five 
offensive line positions. 
</P>
<P>
	Durability is in the Matthews family genes. His brother, Clay,  
played 19 seasons and 278 games with the Cleveland Browns and 
Atlanta Falcons. His father, Clay Sr., played four seasons with the 
San Francisco 49ers in the 1950s. 
</P>
<P>
	The 6-foot-5, 305-pound Matthews played left guard last season,  
but will move to center because of the loss of Mark Stepnoski, who 
signed with Dallas in the offseason. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm really excited about it,'' Matthews said. ``You eliminate  
a lot of the collisions, 'cause you're not pulling and doing some 
of the things you have to do at guard.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Titans are coming off a third straight 8-8 season, but  
Matthews believes the team is close to being a championship 
contender. He noted that Atlanta went to the Super Bowl last year, 
one season after his brother retired. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm going to hang around long enough that this thing will have  
to go to the Super Bowl,'' he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
