<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Accuser Passed Lie Detector </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Kathleen Willey says she's prepared to testify  
again if her one-time friend Julie Hiatt Steele is retried for 
obstructing the investigation of President Clinton. 
</P>
<P>
	Newly unsealed results of two FBI polygraph examinations of Mrs.  
Willey show she failed a question on the first test regarding 
whether she provided details of an alleged sexual advance by 
Clinton to her friend Ms. Steele. She passed a later test in which 
she alleged that advance took place. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Willey explained to the polygraph examiner last year that  
at first she couldn't recall when she told Ms. Steele of the 
alleged 1993 incident with Clinton, but was reminded of it later by 
Ms. Steele. 
</P>
<P>
	In a second lie detector test six days after the first one, Mrs.  
Willey was found to be truthful after answering ``yes'' to two 
questions: ``Before 1997 did you tell Julie Steele that the 
president came on to you?'' and ``In 1993 did you tell Julie Steele 
about an encounter with the president in his office?'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Steele says the first time she'd heard of an alleged  
Clinton-Willey encounter was when Mrs. Willey asked her to lie 
about it to Newsweek magazine in 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Willey was the chief prosecution witness for Independent  
Counsel Kenneth Starr's office in last week's obstruction trial of 
Ms. Steele for allegedly lying to two grand juries and the FBI in 
Starr's investigation of Clinton, who denies any sexual encounter 
with Mrs. Willey. The jury deadlocked in Ms. Steele's trial in 
Alexandria, Va. 
</P>
<P>
	Starr is considering whether to seek a new trial and has filed a  
court motion asking for permission to approach jurors who are 
willing to be interviewed by prosecutors about how they reached 
their views on Ms. Steele's guilt or innocence. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'd like to see (the case) retried,'' Mrs. Willey said  
Wednesday night on CNN's ``Larry King Live.'' Of her testimony last 
week, Mrs. Willey said, ``I've done it once. I guess I could do it 
again.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Regarding Ms. Steele, Mrs. Willey said, ``I think she did try to  
obstruct justice'' by telling Starr's investigators a story that 
contradicted part of Mrs. Willey's account. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. District Judge Claude Hilton unsealed the 1998 lie detector  
results this week after a federal appeals court directed him to 
reconsider an earlier denial. News organizations, including The 
Associated Press, went to court to challenge the secrecy 
surrounding the documents. 
</P>
<P>
	On another part of the polygraph examinations in which she said  
Clinton made a sexual advance, Mrs. Willey initially tested 
``inconclusive'' but in the second test was found to be truthful. 
</P>
<P>
	In the second test last Sept. 15 in the FBI's Washington field  
office, Mrs. Willey was asked, ``In November 1993 did the president 
place his hand on your breast?'' and ``Did President Clinton place 
your hand on his groin?'' Both times, Mrs. Willey answered ``yes,'' 
a three-page FBI summary of the test results stated. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is the opinion of this examiner that Ms. Willey was  
truthful'' when responding to those two questions, the summary 
added. 
</P>
<P>
	The polygraph questions did not address whether Clinton's  
alleged advance against Mrs. Willey was unwanted. Mrs. Willey says 
she rebuffed him. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
