<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Fortier Appeals Okla. Bomb Sentence </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DENVER (AP) -- Michael Fortier's lawyer told a federal appeals  
court Thursday that Fortier's 12-year prison sentence should be 
reduced because there is no evidence that money he raised helped 
pay for the Oklahoma City bombing. 
</P>
<P>
	Fortier, 30, pleaded guilty to failing to alert authorities to  
the 1995 bomb plot, which killed 168 people and injured 500 others. 
He testified against Timothy McVeigh and Terry Nichols and admitted 
helping McVeigh sell stolen weapons and lying to FBI agents after 
the bombing. 
</P>
<P>
	Defense attorney Michael McGuire told the 10th U.S. Circuit  
Court of Appeals that McVeigh and Nichols never told Fortier how 
they planned to use the money raised from selling the weapons at 
gun shows. 
</P>
<P>
	``There was no agreement or condition or anything,'' he told the  
three-judge panel, noting that the bombing occurred five months 
after Fortier gave McVeigh and Nichols thousands of dollars. ``It 
all happened too far after the fact.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutor Sean Connelly said Fortier still bears some  
responsibility for the bombing. He said Fortier's cooperation with 
investigators and his lesser role have already earned him a less 
severe sentence than McVeigh and Nichols. McVeigh received the 
death penalty, Nichols a life sentence. 
</P>
<P>
	Connelly said McVeigh drove Fortier past the federal building on  
a trip to pick up stolen guns and told him: ``That's my target.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Circuit Judge John Porfilio suggested the drive-by was warning  
enough about the conspiracy. ``That doesn't sound innocent to me,'' 
Porfilio said. 
</P>
<P>
	A ruling is not expected for several months.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
