<DOCNO> APW19990513.0249 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-13 02:33:59 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Obituaries in the News  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
                            *Eqbal Ahmad    	
</P>
<P>
	ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) -- Eqbal Ahmad, an anti-war scholar once  
accused of plotting to kidnap former U.S. Secretary of State Henry 
Kissinger, died Tuesday. He was 67. 
</P>
<P>
	A professor and founding member of the Institute for Policy  
Studies in Washington D.C., Ahmad returned to his home in Pakistan 
after retiring two years ago. 
</P>
<P>
	A fierce opponent of U.S. Involvement in the Vietnam War, Ahmad  
was among seven people accused of plotting to kidnap Kissinger and 
to blow up underground heating tunnels to federal offices in 
Washington. 
</P>
<P>
	Dubbed the Harrisburg Seven, their 1971 trial ended in a hung  
jury when prosecutors withdrew some charges and the rest were 
thrown out on appeal. 
</P>
<P>
	Ahmad later helped found the Institute for Policy Studies and  
the Transnational Institute in Amsterdam. He retired two years ago 
from teaching at Hampshire College in Amherst, Mass. 

</P>
<P>
                          *Herbert M. Baus    	
</P>
<P>
	PALM SPRINGS, Calif. (AP) -- Writer Herbert M. Baus, campaign  
manager and adviser to President Richard M. Nixon and other 
California politicians, died of Parkinson's disease May 6. He was 
85. 
</P>
<P>
	Baus' Los Angeles campaigning firm, Baus &AMP; Ross, was formed  
after World War II and used then-pioneering techniques of voter 
polling and direct mail advertising. He was a proponent of several 
California ballot initiatives including establishing daylight 
savings time in California. 
</P>
<P>
	His roster of California political heavyweights included Los  
Angeles County Sheriff Peter J. Pitchess and Gov. Edmund G. ``Pat'' 
Brown Sr. Although Baus retired from Baus &AMP; Ross in 1968, he 
continued as a consultant and a campaign supporter for Nixon in 
U.S. Senate, vice presidential and presidential races. 
</P>
<P>
	In February 1974, Baus told Nixon: ``The time has come for you  
to bow out.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Baus also took his pleas for resignation to newspaper opinion  
pages, writing to Nixon in the Los Angeles Times: ``The paramount 
issue has become whether the country will be ripped apart by your 
impeachment for a colony of crimes that have become linked to your 
office -- or whether you will go away, quietly. Given the sorry 
circumstances, my advice -- and I speak as an old ally -- is that you 
should resign, for the good of yourself, your party and your 
country.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Also an author, Baus' books included ``Politics Battle Plan,''  
written with business partner William B. Ross; ``Wine Your Way to 
Health'' (1973); and the ``Master Crossword Puzzle Dictionary'' in 
(1981). 

</P>
<P>
                         *William P. Gruber    	
</P>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- William P. Gruber, a veteran business writer who  
retired last year from the Chicago Tribune, died Tuesday of a heart 
ailment. He was 67. 
</P>
<P>
	He was business editor of Chicago Today when it folded in 1974  
and then joined the Tribune. Gruber wrote a column chronicling the 
comings and goings of the area business community. 
</P>
<P>
	Gruber is survived by a brother and a sister.  

</P>
<P>
                           *Robert Keane    	
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Robert Keane, a longtime newspaper union  
organizer who began his career as a payroll clerk at the Daily 
News, died Tuesday of pneumonia. He was 76. 
</P>
<P>
	Keane was a Newspaper Guild negotiator for a decade and a half,  
and represented the union in talks with the Daily News, the New 
York Post, the New York Amsterdam News and Scientific American, 
among other publications. 
</P>
<P>
	Keane became involved in the Daily News Guild unit around 1960,  
and later became its chairman. He soon went to work full-time as a 
Guild organizer, helping to negotiate job security provisions at 
the Daily News in the late 1960s that became a model for workers at 
other newspapers and magazines, said Barry Lipton, president of the 
New York Guild. 
</P>
<P>
	Keane left the Guild in the 1970s to become administrator of the  
Guild-News pension fund, from which he retired in the early 1990s. 
</P>
<P>
	He and his late wife, Norine, had eight sons and a daughter,  
four of whom entered the news business. One son, Kevin, is 
administrator of the Wire Service Guild in New York; another, Paul, 
is an entertainment editor at the Daily News; and daughter Lillian 
Berry works in advertising sales at the News. 
</P>
<P>
	Robert Keane is also survived by 18 grandchildren and four  
great-granddaughters. 

</P>
<P>
                           *C. Earl Leslie    	
</P>
<P>
	ALEXANDRIA, Va. (AP) -- C. Earl Leslie, who worked in the White  
House social office to hand letter everything from inaugural 
invitations to historic documents, died of cancer May 6 in 
Alexandria, Va. 
</P>
<P>
	Leslie mastered the art of engrossing -- a form of lettering  
commonly used in the Middle Ages -- at a young age and moved here in 
1933 to be secretary to then-Interior Secretary Harold L. Ickes. 
</P>
<P>
	Leslie moved to the White House two years later, where he served  
during the administrations of Franklin Roosevelt, Harry Truman and 
Dwight Eisenhower. 
</P>
<P>
	His work varied from the proclamation of German surrender in  
World War II to place cards for state dinners. Leslie, who served 
as assistant chief of the White House's social office, was 
sometimes called upon by the Secret Service as a handwriting 
expert. 
</P>
<P>
	Leslie continued engrossing independently for 20 years after  
leaving the White House. 

</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Saul Steinberg, a cartoonist whose work was  
compared to Pablo Picasso and is perhaps best known for his drawing 
showing New York City as the center of the world, has died. He was 
84. 
</P>
<P>
	Steinberg, who drew cartoons for The New Yorker magazine for  
more than 50 years, died Wednesday at his home in Manhattan. His 
brooding doodles were considered a fine art and drew comparisons to 
legendary painters such as Picasso and Duchamp. Art critic Harold 
Rosenberg described Steinberg as ``a writer of pictures, an 
architect of speech and sounds, a draftsman of political 
reflections.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Among Steinberg's most famous cartoons is ``View of the World  
from 9th Avenue (1975),'' which first appeared on the magazine's 
cover the following year. The drawing shows a bird's-eye view of 
the world looking west from Manhattan, with the great detail of New 
York streets fading into ill-defined clumps for the rest of the 
nation and the world. 
</P>
<P>
	This perspective -- as seen in the cartoon from the standpoint of  
a chauvinistic Manhattanite -- spawned similar drawings for numerous 
cities, including London, Paris, Rome and Venice. 
</P>
<P>
	Born in Romania in 1914, Steinberg studied at the University of  
Bucharest before moving to Italy, where he received a doctoral 
degree in architecture in 1940. 
</P>
<P>
	But Steinberg began drawing in 1934, quickly discovering his  
skill as a cartoonist. The New Yorker published its first Steinberg 
cartoon in 1941, a sketch of a reverse centaur. Steinberg arrived 
in the United States a year later. 
</P>
<P>
	Steinberg is survived by Hedda Lindenberg Sterne, whom he  
married in 1943. They were separated in the 1970s but never 
divorced. 

</P>
<P>
                        *John M. Tubergen Jr.    	
</P>
<P>
	WESTERVILLE, Ohio (AP) -- John M. Tubergen Jr., a deaf man who  
helped pioneer bringing television news to the hearing impaired, 
died May 4 of pneumonia. He was 80. 
</P>
<P>
	Sitting by an anchorman for Chicago station WNBQ, Tubergen used  
sign language to report the news for the five-minute television 
program ``World News for the Hard of Hearing,'' which was broadcast 
in 1958 for 13 weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	His entry into the field was prompted in the 1950s when, working  
as a newspaper proofreader, Tubergen missed a tornado warning 
because he couldn't hear a newscast. 
</P>
<P>
	He sent an angry letter to the news director for NBC's central  
division, telling him the station wasn't serving its 100,000 
hearing impaired viewers. 
</P>
<P>
	The response was an offer to provide the ``talking hands'' for  
what was considered the first sustained news program for the deaf, 
the Chicago American reported in 1958. 
</P>
<P>
	The show and other live broadcasts were canceled when there was  
an electrician's strike, author Jack R. Gannon wrote in the book 
``Deaf Heritage.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Tubergen later tutored deaf students at Harper College in  
Palatine, where his students included actress Marlee Matlin. 

</P>
<P>
                         *Rosemary Valaire    	
</P>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Rosemary Valaire, a former soloist with  
Britain's Royal Ballet and influential teacher at the Westside 
School of Ballet for three decades, died Friday of a brain tumor. 
She was 68. 
</P>
<P>
	Valaire was born as Rosemary Feuerheerd in London and adopted  
her stage name from the character Valerius in William Shakespeare's 
play ``The Two Noble Kinsmen.'' Valaire was a soloist with the 
Royal Ballet from 1946 until 1954 and held the prestigious Solo 
Seal. 
</P>
<P>
	She later reconstructed the Royal Ballet's version of ``Sleeping  
Beauty'' for several companies, including the American Ballet 
Theater in 1976, when she coached Natalia Makarova and Mikhail 
Baryshnikov for the lead roles. Valaire was widely known for her 
adherence to classical ballet. 
</P>
<P>
	She began teaching in 1967 at the Westside School of Ballet in  
Santa Monica, where she teamed up with Mounsey, a former New York 
City Ballet dancer, and worked through three decades. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990513.0250 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-13 06:05:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Board OKs Tax Break for GM Plant </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LANSING, Mich. (AP) -- A state board has approved a $73 million  
tax credit for General Motors Corp. for a proposed new luxury car 
plant to be built in Lansing. 
</P>
<P>
	The tax credit granted by the Michigan Economic Growth Authority  
on Wednesday is the centerpiece of a $98.9 million state incentive 
package for the world's biggest automaker. 
</P>
<P>
	Lansing Mayor David Hollister noted that the proposed Cadillac  
plant would be the first domestic assembly plant built by GM in 
over a decade. The plant will build the Cadillac Catera, now 
produced in Germany, and possibly other models. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are committed to overcoming every obstacle'' to make sure  
the plant comes to Lansing, Hollister said. 
</P>
<P>
	GM spokesman Kyle Johnson warned that a few more pieces still  
must fall in place before the plant can become a reality. The 
contract reached with UAW Local 652 remains unratified, and the 
company also has to reach an agreement on incentives with city 
officials and obtain a state air-quality permit. 
</P>
<P>
	``It has been a wonderful, ongoing effort to get to this  
point,'' Johnson said. 
</P>
<P>
	Hollister said he expected the City Council to approve a tax  
abatement package by June 14. 
</P>
<P>
	State officials estimate the new plant would provide more than  
$2 billion in revenue for the state, even after deducting the tax 
credit and other incentives. The new plant would employ at least 
1,500 people. If it gets the final go-ahead, groundbreaking could 
take place in the fall, with the plant opening in late 2001 and 
production starting early in 2002. 
</P>
<P>
	The plant, which would require at least a $500 million  
investment, eventually could make up to 211,000 vehicles annually. 
Lansing also hopes to get a new small-car factory set to open in 
2004 to replace its aging Pontiac Grand Am and Oldsmobile Alero 
plants. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
