<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990513.0251 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-13 13:25:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bad Mistake Costs Stars / Hockey Game Story  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DALLAS (AP) -- Sergei Zubov might as well strap on the goat's  
horns. 
</P>
<P>
	In spite of strong, reliable play throughout the playoffs, the  
Dallas defenseman's giveaway pass up the middle of the ice in 
overtime cost the Stars the game Wednesday night. That and the 
Stars' lead in the best-of-7 playoff series. 
</P>
<P>
	The heavily favored Stars are now tied 2-2 in their best-of-7  
series with the St. Louis Blues. Game 5 is Saturday in Dallas. 
</P>
<P>
	Zubov's pass landed right on the stick of Pierre Turgeon, who  
broke in on Ed Belfour and scored his second overtime game-winner 
of the playoffs from 25 feet out. The goal, Turgeon's fourth and 
12th point of the playoffs, gave the Blues a 3-2 victory. 
</P>
<P>
	``Bad giveaway. You can't have that. He knows it. We all know  
it,'' said Dallas coach Ken Hitchcock. ``There was nobody there. 
The lane was up the wall. It was wide open. As a matter of fact, if 
we get it up the wall, it would have been a 3-on-2.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But even as Zubov's poor puck decision earned the scorn of his  
coach, his teammates backed him and chalked the goal up to a night 
of bad luck. 
</P>
<P>
	Consider Geoff Courtnall's goal at the 7:41 mark, which bounced  
off Mike Modano's stick and right past Belfour to give the Blues a 
2-1 lead. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't know how many times you hear people say it's a game of  
inches and bounces, but tonight was a perfect example,'' said Stars 
captain Derian Hatcher. ``If you look at the second goal, there's a 
pass out of the corner, and it hits Modano) and goes in. There's 
nothing you can do about that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Such was the case with Pat Verbeek's apparent game-winning goal  
with 5:36 left to play. It was disallowed because half of Jamie 
Langenbrunner's skate was in the crease. It was 2-2 and off to 
overtime, advantage Blues. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was a huge play and we got a little bit of an adrenaline  
boost from that,'' Blues coach Joel Quenneville said of the 
disallowed goal. ``We wouldn't have had much time to get back into 
it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The series has been surprisingly even, with the fifth-seeded  
Blues showing themselves to be on par with top-seeded Dallas -- in 
the good and bad. 
</P>
<P>
	Both teams won both games at home. Both power plays have been  
abominable, with Dallas going 1-for-21 and St. Louis 2-for-21. Both 
Belfour and Grant Fuhr have given up some poor goals, and both have 
been spectacular at other times. 
</P>
<P>
	But going into Game 5, St. Louis has the momentum, courtesy of a  
2-1 edge in overtime victories this series. The Blues are now 4-2 
in overtimes through 11 playoff games. Nonetheless, St. Louis is 
not exactly begging to head into the extra period again. 
</P>
<P>
	``Right now, it's on our side but it can always go back,''  
center Craig Conroy said. ``So, hopefully we'll stay away from OT 
the rest of the series.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Having the chance to continue the series after falling into a  
2-0 hole is just what the Blues wanted after a two-game homestand. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's like starting over again,'' Conroy said. ``Best of three,  
it's anybody's ballgame.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
