<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Britain Moves Against Web Site </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- The names of more than 100 purported British spies  
have been removed from a U.S.-based World Wide Web site, but the 
British government is concerned copies of the list may be posted 
elsewhere on the Internet. 
</P>
<P>
	Foreign Secretary Robin Cook said Thursday that the list had  
been released by Richard Tomlinson, a former British agent now 
living in Switzerland. 
</P>
<P>
	But in an e-mail to the British Broadcasting Corp., Tomlinson  
denied he had posted such a list and said any names on his site 
were already in the public domain. 
</P>
<P>
	``People are jumping to the wrong conclusion. My Web site  
doesn't contain any names,'' Tomlinson said, according to the BBC. 
</P>
<P>
	The Foreign Office on Wednesday asked newspaper editors not to  
publish details from the list, which it described as ``fact and 
fantasy.'' It gave no further details about the site or its 
address. 
</P>
<P>
	Publishing such details ``could put lives at risk,'' said Rear  
Adm. David Pulvertaft, secretary of the Defense, Press and 
Broadcasting Advisory Committee, which advises media on issues of 
national security. 
</P>
<P>
	Cook said ``not all the names'' on the list were connected with  
the Secret Intelligence Service, known as MI6. 
</P>
<P>
	``Nevertheless, the release of any such list, however inaccurate  
it may be, is a deeply irresponsible and dangerous act,'' Cook told 
reporters. He also said it was illegal. 
</P>
<P>
	Cook said Tomlinson nursed a ``deep-seated and irrational  
grievance'' against his previous employers. 
</P>
<P>
	Tomlinson, 35, was dismissed from the security service in 1995.  
He was jailed for six months in Britain in late 1997 after he 
showed the synopsis of a book on his career to an Australian 
publisher. During his four-year career as a British agent, he 
served in Moscow and Bosnia. 
</P>
<P>
	The government said the offending list had been deleted from the  
Web, but that it was concerned copies may have been made that now 
are circulating on other Web sites. 
</P>
<P>
	Once a page has appeared on the Internet, it is easy for another  
user to copy it and re-post the contents, known as ``mirroring.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A Foreign Office spokesman said Thursday night that ``No  
injunction has been served, so we have to assume it has been 
removed voluntarily.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The spokesman added that no copies of the page had thus far been  
identified, although careful checks were being made. 
</P>
<P>
	British government lawyers previously obtained an injunction to  
shut down a Swiss-based Web site set up by Tomlinson, alleging he 
threatened to publish the location of MI6 offices around the world 
and a detailed list of serving officers, along with other 
information. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
