<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-13 16:21:54 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Suns Season Was Star-Crossed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHOENIX (AP) -- From the beginning, the Phoenix Suns' season  
seemed cursed. 
</P>
<P>
	First, the new collective bargaining agreement ruined the Suns'  
grand plan for a free-agent spending spree. 
</P>
<P>
	Then Antonio McDyess, counted on as Jason Kidd's perfect partner  
in the coming years, decided after one season to go back to Denver, 
even if it meant less money. 
</P>
<P>
	The Suns tried to regroup by signing Tom Gugliotta and trading  
for Luc Longley. But the mix just wasn't there. The team was soft 
and inconsistent, traits that led to Phoenix being swept from the 
first round of the playoffs for the first time since 1985. It was 
the fourth straight first-round exit for Phoenix. 
</P>
<P>
	Now general manager Bryan Colangelo said the challenge is to do  
something about it. 
</P>
<P>
	``The biggest needs we have are athleticism and interior  
toughness, and generally overall toughness,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	It's a sentiment echoed by the players.  
</P>
<P>
	``We need a few more big bodies,'' forward-center Cliff Robinson  
said, ``maybe a few more athletic, big bodies. I just think we need 
a little more toughness around the basket.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The team could also use a consistent shooting threat at the  
off-guard spot. 
</P>
<P>
	Rex Chapman was supposed to fill that role, but he was injured  
early in the season and never displayed the sharpshooting form 
expected of him. When Chapman was hitting from the outside, the 
Suns were a much more dangerous team. When he wasn't hitting, he 
was a definite defensive liability, especially against bigger, 
stronger guards such as Portland's Isaiah Rider. 
</P>
<P>
	Colangelo said he expects Chapman to spend the offseason getting  
healthy and into the right frame of mind in time for training camp 
next October. 
</P>
<P>
	The bright spot, of course, was Kidd. He led the league in  
assists and had seven triple doubles. But he was surrounded by 
players not suited for his up-tempo, intense style. One writer in 
Portland wrote that ``Having Jason Kidd play for the Suns was like 
having Julia Child cook at Burger King.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Jason Kidd had a spectacular season, a phenomenal season,''  
coach Danny Ainge said. ``If there is one element to his game that 
took him to the superstar level it was making big shots down the 
stretch consistently. He made a lot of big shots for us this year. 
</P>
<P>
	``We can't have him do it by himself every night, obviously,''  
Ainge said. ``We need some help in the low post to take a little 
bit of heat off of him.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ainge never hid his frustration at the Suns' meek demeanor.  
Ainge was as nasty a player as could be found in the NBA, but his 
team showed little of his toughness. 
</P>
<P>
	``As a player, I wasn't afraid to get booed on the road. I  
wasn't afraid to take a hard foul when we needed it,'' Ainge said. 
``I get very frustrated when they're laying us out on the ground, 
and we're not doing it on the other end. I get frustrated that 
we're not doing it first -- the first play of the first game.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Phoenix has Dallas' No. 1 pick in the coming draft, thanks to  
the trade that sent Steve Nash to the Mavericks. That is a lottery 
pick. 
</P>
<P>
	Colangelo expects to use that pick, which will be no worse than  
No. 8, to address the team's need for some inside muscle. He also 
plans to use the new $2 million exception to the salary cap to sign 
a free agent to bolster the team's toughness. 
</P>
<P>
	Phoenix also has its own first-round pick, No. 16 overall, but  
might send it to Chicago as part of the Longley deal. 
</P>
<P>
	Most players on the Suns roster aren't exactly attractive trade  
material. Kidd, of course, is virtually untouchable. Chapman has a 
big new contract and is coming off an awful season. 
</P>
<P>
	Gugliotta, who admits he didn't have the season he wanted,  
likewise has a new contract and is expected to stay in Phoenix. 
Gugliotta is a different player than the departed McDyess, whose 
sheer strength and jumping ability was a trait totally absent from 
the Suns after he left. 
</P>
<P>
	Colangelo thinks Gugliotta will fit in better after more time  
with Phoenix and a slightly different mix of teammates. 
</P>
<P>
	Longley was inconsistent in his first season away from Chicago,  
and had a horrible playoff series, but his large contract would 
make him unattractive to other teams. 
</P>
<P>
	George McCloud is on a one-year contract.  
</P>
<P>
	Robinson, who had a standout season, probably will be re-signed  
since he was Phoenix's lone consistent inside defender. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're going to make every effort to re-sign him,'' Colangelo  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, the Suns, always the most successful franchise in the  
Valley of the Sun, are creating mostly yawns among fans. The team's 
string of playoff home sellouts ended at 50 with the Wednesday 
night loss to Portland. 
</P>
<P>
	Colangelo said years of success have made the franchise a bit  
complacent, a bit too comfortable, both on the basketball side and 
business side. 
</P>
<P>
	``With increased competition and the heightened expectations  
that come with our success, it's time to reevaluate it,'' he said. 
``We've been to the playoffs 11 straight years. People expect us to 
advance past the first round. I feel like we've been operating this 
business for several years in a very efficient, suitable way, but 
it's time to step it up, both on the court and on the basketball 
side.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
