<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Court Rules for Microsoft Workers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SEATTLE (AP) -- A federal appeals court has ruled that thousands  
of former temporary workers for Microsoft Corp. should have been 
allowed to participate in the company's employee stock-purchase 
program -- a decision that could cost the software company millions 
of dollars. 
</P>
<P>
	The 9th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals in San Francisco ruled  
late Wednesday that at least 10,000 former temporary workers since 
1986 should have been allowed to participate in the stock-purchase 
plan, which offers discounts on Microsoft stock. It said they must 
be compensated for appreciation of shares they never got to buy. 
</P>
<P>
	Microsoft was reviewing the ruling ``and we will have to  
consider all of our options,'' spokesman Dan Leach said. The 
company could ask for a rehearing by the three-judge panel that 
ruled Wednesday, ask for review by the entire 9th Circuit court, or 
seek review by the U.S. Supreme Court. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is a significant ruling because it cuts across the industry  
and cuts across business,'' said Rob Enderle, a computer-industry 
analyst with Giga Group of Santa Clara, Calif. 
</P>
<P>
	He estimated the direct cost to Microsoft could be $15 million  
to $20 million. The ruling was released after the stock market 
closed Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	``As a practical matter, Microsoft will have a hard time saying  
people who are employees for the purpose of stock-plan eligibility 
... are not employees for other purposes,'' said Stephen Strong, a 
Seattle attorney who helped bring the class-action lawsuit. 
</P>
<P>
	The class of workers involved includes temporary workers and  
independent contractors who worked 20 hours or more per week for at 
least five months over a year, any time after 1986, said another 
attorney in the case, David Stobaugh. 
</P>
<P>
	Microsoft currently has 5,500 to 6,500 temporary workers.  
</P>
<P>
	The company recently told agencies through which it hires  
temporary workers to improve their compensation packages. They are 
still not eligible for the discounted stock-purchase program, 
however. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. District Court in Seattle is still considering another  
issue in the case: whether Microsoft must give the same 401(k) 
benefits to temporary workers as it does to its regular employees. 
</P>
<P>
	A second class-action lawsuit asks the courts to determine  
whether temporary workers must have the same access to personnel 
files and health insurance benefits that Microsoft employees 
receive. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
