<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Obituaries in the News  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
                            *Eqbal Ahmad    	
</P>
<P>
	ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) -- Eqbal Ahmad, an anti-war scholar once  
accused of plotting to kidnap former U.S. Secretary of State Henry 
Kissinger, died Tuesday. He was 67. 
</P>
<P>
	A professor and founding member of the Institute for Policy  
Studies in Washington D.C., Ahmad returned to his home in Pakistan 
after retiring two years ago. 
</P>
<P>
	A fierce opponent of U.S. Involvement in the Vietnam War, Ahmad  
was among seven people accused of plotting to kidnap Kissinger and 
to blow up underground heating tunnels to federal offices in 
Washington. 
</P>
<P>
	Dubbed the Harrisburg Seven, their 1971 trial ended in a hung  
jury when prosecutors withdrew some charges and the rest were 
thrown out on appeal. 
</P>
<P>
	Ahmad later helped found the Institute for Policy Studies and  
the Transnational Institute in Amsterdam. 

</P>
<P>
                          *Herbert M. Baus    	
</P>
<P>
	PALM SPRINGS, Calif. (AP) -- Writer Herbert M. Baus, campaign  
manager and adviser to President Richard M. Nixon and other 
California politicians, died May 6 of Parkinson's disease. He was 
85. 
</P>
<P>
	Baus' Los Angeles campaigning firm, Baus &AMP; Ross, was formed  
after World War II and used then-pioneering techniques of voter 
polling and direct mail advertising. He was a proponent of several 
California ballot initiatives including establishing daylight 
savings time in California. 
</P>
<P>
	His roster of California political heavyweights included Los  
Angeles County Sheriff Peter J. Pitchess and Gov. Edmund G. ``Pat'' 
Brown Sr. Although Baus retired from Baus &AMP; Ross in 1968, he 
continued as a consultant and a campaign supporter for Nixon in 
U.S. Senate, vice presidential and presidential races. 
</P>
<P>
	In February 1974, Baus told Nixon: ``The time has come for you  
to bow out.'' He also took his pleas for resignation to newspaper 
opinion pages, writing to Nixon in the Los Angeles Times. 
</P>
<P>
	Also an author, Baus' books included ``Politics Battle Plan,''  
written with business partner William B. Ross; ``Wine Your Way to 
Health'' (1973); and the ``Master Crossword Puzzle Dictionary'' in 
(1981). 

</P>
<P>
                              *Bin Baz    	
</P>
<P>
	RIYADH, Saudi Arabia (AP) -- Saudi Arabia's top cleric, whose  
rulings ranged from sanctioning Viagra for Muslim men to banning 
short veils for women, died Thursday of cancer. He was in his 80s. 
</P>
<P>
	Bin Baz, head of the Council of Senior Islamic Scholars, was a  
highly influential scholar whose pronouncements reflected the 
official point of view and often carried the weight of law. 
</P>
<P>
	Two years ago on Bin Baz's advice, the government banned the  
import and production of veils that failed to completely cover a 
woman's face. Women in Saudi Arabia generally don't appear in 
public without a black cloak and a head scarf. 
</P>
<P>
	He also ruled that consulting fortune tellers and practicing  
witchcraft was forbidden in Islam, and equated death by reckless 
driving tantamount to committing suicide. Islam condemns suicide. 
</P>
<P>
	Last year, Bin Baz ruled that Muslim men may use the  
anti-impotence drug Viagra if it does not contain any intoxicating 
substances. 

</P>
<P>
                           *Judy Chabola    	
</P>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Judy Chabola, an award-winning choreographer  
and stage director of televised events including the Olympics and 
Emmy, Grammy and Academy Awards ceremonies, died Sunday of breast 
cancer. She was 47. 
</P>
<P>
	Chabola was special events coordinator for the Los Angeles  
Unified School District when she volunteered to help with the 1984 
summer Olympics. She contributed to the dance routines for the 
opening and closing ceremonies at the Los Angeles Coliseum. 
</P>
<P>
	That assignment won a Bob Fosse Award in choreography for her  
and her co-creator, Kenny Ortega. They both were nominated for an 
Emmy. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Chabola choreographed the ceremonies for the 1992 Olympics  
in Barcelona, the 1992 and 1994 soccer World Cup, and 10 Super Bowl 
half-time shows. She worked on more than 100 special events and TV 
broadcasts, including Emmy, Grammy, Oscar, Billboard and Essence 
awards. 

</P>
<P>
                           *Sir Ian Fraser    	
</P>
<P>
	BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) -- Sir Ian Fraser, a pioneer in  
using penicillin to treat battle wounds during World War II, died 
Tuesday at age 98. 
</P>
<P>
	Fraser was serving with the Royal Army Medical Corps in West  
Africa in 1942 when he was sent to Algiers to take charge of a 
research team testing a new drug, penicillin. He carried out his 
research in a hospital but soon took it to the battlefield where 
the drug could be tested as soon as casualties occurred. 
</P>
<P>
	Fraser followed British troops ashore on the invasion of  
Sicily's beaches and operated aboard a ship continuously for 48 
hours, saving many lives. He served until 1946, when he returned to 
Belfast. 
</P>
<P>
	He served as a senior consulting surgeon at the Royal Victoria  
Hospital, Belfast, and the Royal Belfast Hospital for Sick 
Children. 
</P>
<P>
	Fraser was knighted in 1963. His memoirs, ``Blood, Sweat and  
Cheers'' were published in 1989. 

</P>
<P>
                          *Meg Greenfield    	
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Meg Greenfield, a Pulitzer Prize-winning  
editor and writer who ran the editorial page at The Washington Post 
for 20 years, died Thursday of lung cancer. She was 68. 
</P>
<P>
	She was also a columnist for Newsweek magazine since 1974.  
</P>
<P>
	Greenfield voiced opinions on the great turmoils and scandals of  
her time, up through Clinton's impeachment. She said she tried not 
to lose sight of the humanity of the fallen. 
</P>
<P>
	Indeed, the Post, for all its groundbreaking coverage of  
Watergate, editorialized in favor of President Nixon's pardon -- 
``to the disgust of most of our friends,'' she said -- when she was 
deputy editor of the editorial page, a position she held from 1970 
to 1979. She became editor of the page in 1979. 
</P>
<P>
	Greenfield joined the Post in 1968 as an editorial writer after  
11 years with Reporter magazine. 
</P>
<P>
	She won a 1978 Pulitzer for writing editorials, including some  
in defense of outgoing President Ford, who had been criticized in 
earlier Post commentary. 

</P>
<P>
                         *Sally Payne Kelly    	
</P>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Sally Payne Kelly, an actress who appeared in  
a series of 1940s Westerns with Roy Rogers and Gene Autry before 
becoming an illustrator for children's books, died Saturday. She 
was 85. 
</P>
<P>
	Originally known as the ``Sunshine Girl'' of artists' models,  
Sally Payne came to Hollywood under contract to appear in Republic 
Studios cowboy films. 
</P>
<P>
	She made her debut in a bit part as a tourist in the 1934 film  
``Hollywood Hobbies.'' By 1940, before moving into a series of 
westerns, she had appeared as a maid in ``No, No, Nanette'' and as 
Lucy Endover in ``La Conga Nights.'' 
</P>
<P>
	She married Western Airlines executive Arthur F. Kelly in 1942  
and turned to art. She painted oils for her home and those of 
friends and illustrated a series of ``Small Star'' children's 
books, including ``Neighbors.'' 

</P>
<P>
                           *C. Earl Leslie    	
</P>
<P>
	ALEXANDRIA, Va. (AP) -- C. Earl Leslie, who worked in the White  
House social office to hand letter everything from inaugural 
invitations to historic documents, died May 6 of cancer. He was 91. 
</P>
<P>
	Leslie mastered the art of engrossing -- a form of lettering  
commonly used in the Middle Ages -- at a young age and moved here in 
1933 to be secretary to then-Interior Secretary Harold L. Ickes. 
</P>
<P>
	Leslie moved to the White House two years later, where he served  
during the administrations of Franklin Roosevelt, Harry Truman and 
Dwight Eisenhower. 
</P>
<P>
	His work varied from the proclamation of German surrender in  
World War II to place cards for state dinners. Leslie, who served 
as assistant chief of the White House's social office, was 
sometimes called upon by the Secret Service as a handwriting 
expert. 
</P>
<P>
	Leslie continued engrossing independently for 20 years after  
leaving the White House. 

</P>
<P>
                           *Gene Sarazen    	
</P>
<P>
	NAPLES, Fla. (AP) -- Gene Sarazen, the elegant, knickers-wearing  
``Squire'' of golf in the 1920s and '30s who invented the sand 
wedge club and was one of only four men to win all four of the 
sport's major championships, died Thursday of pneumonia. He was 97. 
</P>
<P>
	Sarazen won the PGA Championship three times, the U.S. Open  
twice and the Masters and British Open once each. Only Sarazen, 
Nicklaus, Ben Hogan and Gary Player won all four majors at least 
once in their careers. 
</P>
<P>
	Sarazen's best year was 1932, when he won the British Open with  
a then-record 283 and captured the U.S. Open by shooting a 
final-round 66. 
</P>
<P>
	His victory in the 1932 British Open was made possible in part  
by his invention of the sand wedge, the wide-angled club 
particularly useful in smashing balls out of sand traps. 
</P>
<P>
	Sarazen's greatest acclaim came from a 235-yard 4-wood shot he  
made at the Masters in 1935. Trailing Craig Wood by three strokes 
with just four holes remaining, Sarazen holed the shot for a 
double-eagle 2 -- the rarest score in golf. The shot tied Wood in 
regulation and Sarazen won in a playoff. It also elevated the 
status of the previously obscure Masters. 
</P>
<P>
	Sarazen, born Eugenio Saraceni, won the 1954 PGA Seniors title  
and in 1973, at age 71, made a hole-in-one during the first round 
of the British Open. It was his last tournament. 

</P>
<P>
                          *Saul Steinberg    	
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Satirical cartoonist Saul Steinberg, who created  
hundreds of drawings for The New Yorker, including the famous image 
of what the world looks like to the egocentric Manhattanite, died 
Wednesday at 84. 
</P>
<P>
	His drawings were full of thin, sharp lines and populated with  
cats, dogs and crocodiles -- his symbols for primitive political 
society. His art was sometimes compared to that of Pablo Picasso 
and Joan Miro. 
</P>
<P>
	Steinberg drew 85 covers and 642 other drawings for the magazine  
over 50 years. 
</P>
<P>
	Among his most famous cartoons was ``View of the World from 9th  
Avenue,'' which appeared on the magazine's March 29, 1976, cover. 
The drawing is a bird's-eye view of the world looking west from 
Manhattan, with the detailed streets of New York fading into 
ill-defined clumps for the world beyond. 
</P>
<P>
	Steinberg sold his first drawing while living in Italy in 1935.  
The New Yorker published its first Steinberg cartoon in 1941, a 
sketch of a reverse centaur. He arrived in the United States a year 
later. 
</P>
<P>
	Steinberg is survived by Hedda Lindenberg Sterne, whom he  
married in 1943. They were separated in the 1970s but never 
divorced. 

</P>
<P>
                        *John M. Tubergen Jr.    	
</P>
<P>
	WESTERVILLE, Ohio (AP) -- John M. Tubergen Jr., a deaf man who  
helped bring television news to the hearing impaired, died May 4 of 
pneumonia. He was 80. 
</P>
<P>
	Sitting by an anchorman for Chicago station WNBQ, Tubergen used  
sign language to report the news for the five-minute television 
program ``World News for the Hard of Hearing,'' which was broadcast 
in 1958 for 13 weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	His entry into the field was prompted in the 1950s when, working  
as a newspaper proofreader, Tubergen missed a tornado warning 
because he couldn't hear a newscast. 
</P>
<P>
	He sent an angry letter to the news director for NBC's central  
division, telling him the station wasn't serving its 100,000 
hearing impaired viewers. 
</P>
<P>
	The response was an offer to provide the ``talking hands'' for  
what was considered the first sustained news program for the deaf, 
the Chicago American reported in 1958. 
</P>
<P>
	The show and other live broadcasts were canceled when there was  
an electrician's strike, author Jack R. Gannon wrote in the book 
``Deaf Heritage.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Tubergen later tutored deaf students at Harper College in  
Palatine, where his students included actress Marlee Matlin. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
