<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Wordly Manner: Preakness Contender? </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BALTIMORE (AP) -- Beware of Worldly Manner in Saturday's  
Preakness. 
</P>
<P>
	Assistant trainer Tom Albertrani said the Dubai-based colt has  
thrived at Churchill Downs since his seventh-place finish in the 
Kentucky Derby May 1. 
</P>
<P>
	``He came out of the Derby in great shape, and we're  
confident,'' Albertrani said Thursday at Pimlico, a day after the 
colt shipped in from Kentucky. ``The Derby tuned him up a little. 
He's put on weight and he's more focused.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The race served as a prep race of sorts for Worldly Manner, who  
did not race officially as a 3-year-old leading up to the Kentucky 
Derby. His only race was a private trial in Dubai, United Arab 
Emirates, where he finished first. 
</P>
<P>
	But his strong effort in the 1 1/4-mile Derby -- he was contending  
for the lead with Cat Thief entering the stretch -- was received 
well by owners Sheikh Mohammed al Maktoum and Sheikh Maktoum al 
Maktoum. Charismatic, a 31-1 shot, won the Derby by a neck over 
Menifee in a 19-horse field. 
</P>
<P>
	``Worldly Manner ran a very credible race, and we were pleased  
with it,'' Albertrani said, adding that Sheikh Mohammed will attend 
the Preakness. ``We were excited at the quarter pole, but the last 
100 yards he got a little weary. You can say he will improve off 
that race.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Preakness distance is 1 3-16 miles, 1-16th of a mile shorter  
than the Derby. 
</P>
<P>
	Worldly Manner, who will be ridden again by Jerry Bailey, leaves  
from the No. 10 post and was 12-1 in the morning line. In his final 
workout Tuesday, he went 5 furlongs in 1:01 at Churchill Downs. 
</P>
<P>
	Worldly Manner was trained by Bob Baffert as a 2-year-old, but  
John Mabee sold the colt for a reported $5 million. Before the 
Derby, Worldly Manner's last official race was a victory in the Del 
Mar Futurity last September. 
</P>
<P>
	Asked if Saeed bin Suroor might consider changing training  
methods and send the sheikh's horses to run in traditional Derby 
preps, Albertrani said: ``Maybe in the future we'll try a different 
approach. 
</P>
<P>
	``Maybe he needed a race mentally more than physically,'' he  
added. ``Jerry asked him to come out running and he didn't realize 
he was going to take the bit and keep it.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990513.0270 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-13 22:22:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Boeing Cutting Up to 7,000 Jobs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ST. LOUIS (AP) -- Boeing will eliminate 6,500 to 7,000 jobs in  
St. Louis by 2001 because of a decline in orders for the F-15 
fighter plane. 
</P>
<P>
	The company announced the moves Thursday and said it will  
consolidate factories that make three planes, including the F-15. 
The company said it expects the cuts to come from management and 
union members. 
</P>
<P>
	``We knew there would be layoffs, but not of this magnitude,''  
said Rick Smith, president of District 837 of the International 
Association of Machinists &AMP; Aerospace Workers. ``When they lost the 
sales, we all expected something to happen, but not this quickly 
and not this big. These are all good, relatively high-paying 
jobs.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Layoffs of 800 to 900 St. Louis workers were announced earlier.  
Jerry Daniels, a Boeing vice president, said 300 to 400 workers 
would be let go every month until the reduction is complete. 
</P>
<P>
	Last month, the Greek government signed a $3.5 billion contract  
to buy Lockheed Martin's F-16s instead of the Boeing jets. That 
order alone could have kept the Boeing line open two more years. 
</P>
<P>
	Two weeks later, the Israeli government postponed a $2.5 billion  
purchase of F-15s. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
