<DOCNO> APW19990513.0271 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-13 16:31:41 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Daly, Geiger Get Into Tussle </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- The Magic and 76ers didn't waste any time  
before starting the rough stuff Thursday night. 
</P>
<P>
	With the Sixers leading early in Game 3 of their playoff series,  
Philadelphia's Matt Geiger got into a tussle for the ball with 
Orlando coach Chuck Daly. The Sixers had promised to retaliate for 
hard fouls on Allen Iverson in Game 2, and they took the Magic's 
physical play to another level right from the opening tip. 
</P>
<P>
	With the Sixers leading 11-2, Orlando point guard Darrell  
Armstrong lost the ball out of bounds as he dribbled in front of 
the Magic bench. Daly wanted a timeout, but the ball was out of 
bounds before Armstrong could ask for one. 
</P>
<P>
	So Daly grabbed the ball and wouldn't give it up. Geiger  
wrestled it away from him in a surreal confrontation between a 
68-year-old coach and a 7-foot-1, 248-pound center. No technical 
fouls were called. 
</P>
<P>
	Moments earlier, Geiger got into a confrontation with Armstrong  
after Geiger hit Orlando's Isaac Austin after the whistle on a 
traveling call. Austin walked up to Geiger and bumped him. Geiger 
started screaming, and Armstrong ran up to him and pointed right in 
his face. 
</P>
<P>
	Geiger raised his arms and shouted, ``That's right! That's  
right!'' 
</P>
<P>
	Technicals were called on Geiger and Armstrong. The Sixers, at  
home for the first playoff game since 1991, led 23-15 after the 
first quarter. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990513.0272 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-13 05:15:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 8 a.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Yugoslavia Shows Signs of Pullout  
</P>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- About 120 Yugoslav troops, in a  
convoy of trucks and buses, left Kosovo today, in the first sign of 
a military pullout from the stricken Serb province. Foreign 
reporters taken to a border post at Merdara saw the convoy leave, 
and an army officer there blamed constant NATO bombing for the 
``slow pace'' of withdrawals since the Yugoslav high command 
announced a partial pullout from the stricken province had been 
ordered from last Sunday. 

</P>
<P>
	NATO Attacks Serbian TV Headquarters  
</P>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Flames and heavy smoke billowed up  
from Serbian television headquarters in Novi Sad today after a NATO 
attack, and President Slobodan Milosevic acknowledged suffering 
heavy casualties in NATO's 51-day bombing campaign.Without giving 
specific figures, Milosevic said yesterday that ``during this 
struggle, many members of the police and security forces died 
courageously.'' Alliance warplanes hit airports, television 
transmitters, a coal mine and a railway station late yesterday and 
early today in Serbia, the dominant republic of Yugoslavia. 

</P>
<P>
	Yugoslav Peace Talks Resume  
</P>
<P>
	MOSCOW (AP) -- Russian and Western envoys pushed ahead with  
mediation efforts for Kosovo today, under new pressure for a 
breakthrough after Boris Yeltsin threatened to pull Russia out of 
negotiations. Yeltsin welcomed French President Jacques Chirac 
today for talks on the conflict in Yugoslavia. Yeltsin did not 
refer to his warning yesterday that Russia might halt its mediation 
efforts, an unexpected blow to the peace process just when the West 
was hoping a solution was near. 

</P>
<P>
	Yeltsin Impeachment Hearings Start  
</P>
<P>
	MOSCOW (AP) -- Impeachment hearings began today against President  
Boris Yeltsin, a day after he plunged the nation into a political 
crisis by dismissing Yevgeny Primakov, Russia's popular prime 
minister and his Cabinet. The hearings began with lawmakers reading 
out reports on the five impeachment charges Yeltsin is facing: 
instigating the 1991 Soviet collapse, improperly using force 
against hard-line lawmakers in 1993, launching the botched 1994-96 
war in Chechnya, ruining Russia's military and waging genocide 
against Russians with economic policies that impoverished the 
country. 

</P>
<P>
	New President Elected in Italy  
</P>
<P>
	ROME (AP) -- Treasury Minister Carlo Azeglio Ciampi was elected  
president of Italy today, winning wide backing from both the 
government and the opposition. At least 674 votes, cast secretly by 
senators, deputies and regional representatives, were required to 
become the next head of state. When the tally came within a few 
votes of that number, most of hall broke into a standing ovation 
for Ciampi -- applause that continued as he passed the mark. No 
final tally of votes was yet available. 

</P>
<P>
	Hillary Clinton Urges Ireland Peace  
</P>
<P>
	BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) -- U.S. First Lady Hillary Rodham  
Clinton called on Northern Ireland's women today to make the 
killing earlier this year of a Roman Catholic lawyer ``a final 
rebuke'' to anyone trying to derail the peace process. Mrs. Clinton 
said the people who planted a bomb in the car of lawyer Rosemary 
Nelson, who represented many Catholic clients, must not be allowed 
to quiet the voices of those pursuing peace. ``Women will not be 
deterred,'' Mrs. Clinton told about 400 female activists, community 
workers and politicians at a conference called ``Vital Voices: 
Women in Democracy.'' 

</P>
<P>
	Japanese Stock Prices Finish Lower  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Japanese stocks ended lower today following news  
U.S. Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin will step down. The Nikkei 
lost 96.11 points, ending the day at 16,851.25. 

</P>
<P>
	Knicks Take 2-1 Lead Against Heat  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The New York Knicks have a 2-1 lead in their  
best-of-5 series against the Miami Heat, leaving the division 
champion Heat one game from elimination. The Knicks unleashed one 
of the most dominant flurries imaginable, using an incredible 32-2 
run to take control of the game -- and their first-round series -- in 
defeating the Miami Heat 97-73. It was a multi-pronged offense that 
boosted the Knicks as Latrell Sprewell scored 20 off the bench, 
Allan Houston had 18, Patrick Ewing 15 and Marcus Camby 13. 
</P>
