<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Gun Lobbyists Scramble To Influence </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Colorado school shootings instantly  
changed the dynamics of the gun control debate, leaving lobbyists 
on both sides scrambling to influence lawmakers' responses. 
</P>
<P>
	Lawmakers and their aides leaving the floor during a Senate  
debate on gun provisions were quickly approached by either James 
Baker, the chief lobbyist for the National Rifle Association, or 
Bob Walker, president of Handgun Control Inc. 
</P>
<P>
	Baker asked them not to add gun control provisions to the  
juvenile crime bill as a knee-jerk reaction to the Littleton high 
school massacre. 
</P>
<P>
	Walker argued the time was right for new protections.  
</P>
<P>
	``The sense of outrage that people have expressed in nonstop  
phone calls since the Littleton tragedy is transmuting itself into 
the political process,'' Walker said. 
</P>
<P>
	Those on both sides of the gun issue have had just three weeks  
to react since juvenile crime legislation now before the Senate was 
transformed into a vehicle for gun control measures. 
</P>
<P>
	So they're relying heavily on the oldest form of influence  
peddling in the business -- walking the halls of the Capitol to make 
personal pitches. 
</P>
<P>
	The NRA also took out full-page ads in major national  
newspapers, sent mailings to the states where senators are wavering 
and activated its grass-roots lobby. 
</P>
<P>
	``Because Bill Clinton and his anti-gun cronies in the Senate  
are trying to exploit the recent school shootings, we urgently need 
you to call your two U.S. senators immediately and urge them to 
oppose the Clinton gun control package,'' an NRA alert to members 
said, urging each member to also call five other supporters of gun 
owners' rights and encourage them to follow suit. The NRA also 
plans to send a letter later this month to all of its millions of 
members, urging them to call their senators and representatives. 
</P>
<P>
	Baker also previewed another argument the gun lobby is making  
all over Capitol Hill -- that lawmakers don't need new laws, they 
just need to enforce the current ones. 
</P>
<P>
	``If we're not going to enforce the laws we currently have, what  
sense does it make to pass another one?'' Baker argued. 
</P>
<P>
	In the end, the NRA won the first round Wednesday.  
</P>
<P>
	In the first vote on gun control since the Littleton shooting on  
April 20, the Senate rejected fresh restrictions on sales at gun 
shows. But some Senate Republicans were already pushing for a new 
vote on the gun show issue Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	The NRA finds itself in the unaccustomed position of being alone  
in opposition to some of the provisions being proposed for the 
juvenile crime bill. That's because the Colorado tragedy caused a 
split in the usually united pro-gun lobby. 
</P>
<P>
	The trade group that represents gun manufacturers, distributors  
and dealers has endorsed such measures as increasing the minimum 
age for buying a gun to 21 and banning violent young people from 
ever owning guns. 
</P>
<P>
	Robert Ricker, executive director of the American Shooting  
Sports Council, admits getting some double takes when he tells 
lawmakers or their aides that he favors some restrictions on gun 
owners' rights. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have to re-examine our positions so we can concentrate on  
the areas where we can help prevent more tragedies,'' Ricker said. 
</P>
<P>
	Both Ricker and Baker said the two gun groups still agree 95  
percent of the time, just not on this issue. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, NRA supporters in Congress acknowledge that emotions are  
running against them. 
</P>
<P>
	``Whenever there is a disaster, there are always people who will  
be more prone to pass something as a knee-jerk response than under 
normal circumstances,'' said Rep. Bob Barr, R-Ga. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
