<HEADLINE> U.S. Deports Man for Nazi Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Another member of a notorious Nazi-sponsored  
killing battalion, blamed for the murder of 19,000 Jewish men, 
women and children during World War II, has been expelled 
permanently from the United States. 
</P>
<P>
	Kazys Ciurinskas, 81, who lived in Crown Point, Ind., left the  
country Wednesday afternoon by plane from Chicago on his way to 
Lithuania, the Justice Department announced. 
</P>
<P>
	On April 15, U.S. Immigration Judge Anthony Petrone in Chicago  
had ordered Ciurinskas removed from this country after he admitted 
participating in Nazi-sponsored persecution. 
</P>
<P>
	Eli M. Rosenbaum, director of the department's Nazi-hunting  
Office of Special Investigations, said the removal order was part 
of a settlement agreement in which Ciurinskas admitted he was an 
armed member of the 2nd Lithuanian Schutzmannschaft (Protective 
Detachment) Battalion and concealed that service when he applied 
for a visa to enter the United States in 1949. 
</P>
<P>
	Ciurinskas also conceded he was subject to removal under a  
provision of U.S. law that requires removal of any alien who 
assisted Nazi persecution, the department said. 
</P>
<P>
	After a trial, a federal judge in Indiana revoked Ciurinskas'  
naturalized U.S. citizenship in 1997 because of his service in the 
2nd Battalion. 
</P>
<P>
	The court noted the battalion assisted the Nazis in 10 killing  
actions in Lithuania and Byelorussia, now Belarus, that murdered 
more than 19,000 Jewish men, women and children in the fall of 
1941. The court concluded that Ciurinskas participated in at least 
one such action. 
</P>
<P>
	Ciurinskas is one of several members of the 2nd Battalion that  
the special investigations office has ousted from this country. Two 
other members of the 2nd Battalion have been ordered deported to 
Lithuania. 
</P>
<P>
	Juozas Naujalis was ordered deported to Lithuania by the  
immigration court in Chicago in 1997, but is appealing his case to 
the U.S. Board of Immigration Appeals. 
</P>
<P>
	Another 2nd Battalion member, Antanas Mineikis of Gulfport,  
Fla., was deported to Lithuania in 1992 after admitting he drove 
multiple truckloads of civilian victims to mass shooting sites and 
observed their murders. ``I saw women and children shot,'' Mineikis 
admitted in a sworn statement. 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier this year, Rosenbaum criticized Lithuania for dragging  
its feet in prosecuting two other major Nazi-collaborators that his 
office pursued in this country. Rosenbaum said then that the U.S. 
government has evidence that 91-year-old Aleksandras Lileikis had 
been feigning illness to avoid trial. 
</P>
<P>
	Lileikis, who lived for 40 years in Norwood, Mass., outside  
Boston, is accused of executing Jews for the Nazis while serving as 
head of security police in the Lithuanian capital of Vilnius during 
the German occupation. 
</P>
<P>
	Rosenbaum's office got a U.S. District Court to revoke Lileikis'  
naturalized U.S. citizenship in 1996 and was moving to deport him 
when he returned to Lithuania. 
</P>
<P>
	A Lithuanian medical panel also has said that 91-year-old Kazys  
Gimzauskas, who was Lileikis' wartime deputy, is too ill to stand 
trial. Gimzauskas fled to Lithuania from his home in St. 
Petersburg, Fla., in 1993. He, too, was stripped of his naturalized 
U.S. citizenship in a proceeding begun by Rosenbaum's office. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. officials said Wednesday that the Lithuanian trials of  
Lileikis and Gimzauskas remain stalled. 
</P>
<P>
	The 2nd battalion's killings in Lithuania and Byelorussia were  
``calculated and unspeakably brutal,'' Rosenbaum said. Captured 
wartime documents show the fall 1941 killing spree ``repulsed even 
the Nazis,'' Rosenbaum added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
