<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bond Prices Soar on Economic Reports / Bonds  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Bond prices skyrocketed Thursday, helped by two  
economic reports that allayed investor fears about inflation. 
</P>
<P>
	The price of the benchmark 30-year Treasury bond rose 1 point,  
or $10 per $1,000 in face value. 
</P>
<P>
	Its yield, which moves in the opposite direction, fell to 5.75  
percent from Wednesday's 5.82 percent. The yield is a key benchmark 
for interest rates on many types of loans. 
</P>
<P>
	Investors were cheered by two economic reports that indicated  
the U.S. economy was still chugging along with no signs inflation 
is accelerating. 
</P>
<P>
	The Labor Department said the government's Producer Price Index  
for finished goods rose 0.5 percent in April. That followed a 
smaller 0.2 percent increase in March and brought the annual rate 
of inflation in prices wholesalers pay to 1.1 percent so far in 
1999, compared with a 0.1 percent decline for all of 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	The April rise was largely due to a 5.1 percent jump in energy  
prices -- the largest in nearly nine years -- which economists had 
expected. 
</P>
<P>
	Excluding gasoline prices, which are frequently volatile, the  
report ``indicates continued price stability for the U.S. 
economy,'' said Labor Secretary Alexis Herman. 
</P>
<P>
	In a separate report, the Commerce Department said retail sales  
rose a smaller-than-expected 0.1 percent in April to a seasonally 
adjusted annual rate of $239.3 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	``The fundamentals driving consumer spending remain positive,''  
said Bruce Steinberg, chief economist for Merrill Lynch. ``However, 
higher gasoline prices have put a crimp in consumers' 
pocketbooks.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In the broader market, prices of short-term Treasury securities  
rose between 1/8 and 7/32 point, while intermediate maturities rose 
between 11/32 and 3/4 point, reported Bridge Telerate. 
</P>
<P>
	Yields on three-month Treasury bills was unchanged from late  
Wednesday at 4.58 percent, while the discount was unchanged at 4.46 
percent. Six-month yields were unchanged at 4.68 percent, while the 
discount fell 0.01 percentage point to 4.50 percent. One-year 
yields edged down to 4.72 percent as the discount fell 0.03 
percentage point to 4.50 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Yields are the interest bonds pay by maturity, while the  
discount is the interest at which they are sold. 
</P>
<P>
	The federal funds rate, the interest on overnight loans between  
banks, rose to 4.81 percent from Wednesday's 4.69 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	In the tax-exempt market, the Bond Buyer index of 40 actively  
traded municipal bonds rose 14/32 to 122 31/32. The average yield 
to maturity fell to 5.32 percent from late Wednesday's 5.34 
percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
