<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> FCC Airwaves Auction Fetches $45.1M </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Government licenses to provide telephone,  
television and Internet services via relatively new wireless 
technology fetched $45.1 million in an auction that ended 
Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	All 161 licenses on the block were sold to 40 companies at the  
Federal Communications Commission in bidding that closed after 43 
rounds. 
</P>
<P>
	The licenses are for a technology called local multipoint  
distribution service, or LMDS, envisioned to provide services to 
compete with local phone and cable companies. 
</P>
<P>
	The new service's delivery is akin to cellular phone service,  
although it is not mobile. To receive telephone, television or data 
service, the customer needs a small receiver dish in or near a 
window. 
</P>
<P>
	TLA Spectrum LLC was the biggest winner -- in terms of money  
pledged on licenses -- offering $7.04 million for 13 licenses. 
McLeodUSA Inc., was the second-largest pledging $4.96 million on 13 
licenses, and Cloudnine Communications was the third highest 
offering $4.15 million on 31 licenses. 
</P>
<P>
	At a FCC auction last year 864 of the same kind of licenses  
fetched $578.6 million. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
