<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Milosevic Snubs U.N. Commissioner </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- President Slobodan Milosevic refused  
Thursday to meet with the U.N. high commissioner for human rights. 
</P>
<P>
	Mary Robinson came to Belgrade to demand an end to what she  
called ``a campaign of ethnic cleansing carried out with 
cold-blooded determination by the government military and security 
forces.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I wanted to be part of ensuring that it could not be said that  
it was not known what was being done,'' Robinson told reporters. 
``I do regret not having that opportunity.'' 
</P>
<P>
	On her return to her headquarters in Geneva, she said Milosevic  
perhaps was unwilling to see her because ``he would have been 
uncomfortable with what I would have been saying to him.'' The 
Yugoslav government made no comment. 
</P>
<P>
	Her message was deeply unwelcome for a government intent upon  
portraying Serbs as the victims of NATO bombs, not the villains of 
Kosovo. She also dismissed Yugoslav contentions that it was NATO's 
airstrikes that have caused the massive numbers of ethnic Albanians 
to flee from Kosovo. 
</P>
<P>
	Robinson, a former Irish president, was able to meet Foreign  
Minister Zivadin Jovanovic to deliver her message. 
</P>
<P>
	She said Jovanovic countered by saying more than 1,200 civilians  
have been killed by NATO bombs and more than 2,000 injured -- 
figures dramatically higher than the last government estimate. 
</P>
<P>
	Robinson told reporters that the civilian deaths were worrying  
and questioned NATO's policy of bombing nonmilitary targets. 
</P>
<P>
	But she said ``my main concern is the gross, deliberate campaign  
of ethnic cleansing which has driven now approximately a million 
Kosovar Albanians out of Kosovo.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Robinson, who has been on a tour taking her to Bosnia, Croatia,  
Montenegro, Macedonia and Albania, said not a single refugee told 
her they were fleeing NATO bombs. 
</P>
<P>
	She said she'd spoken with scores of ethnic Albanian refugees  
who gave her first-hand accounts of being driven out of Kosovo by 
Serbian forces, and that she had heard accounts collected by human 
rights workers and others working with refugees. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've heard direct witness myself of the human rights  
violations suffered by a large number of Kosovar Albanians driven 
from their homes directly, and it was people in uniform army 
uniform, police uniform, paramilitary uniform,'' Robinson said. 
</P>
<P>
	``It has been very brutal and very direct, in some cases  
separating menfolk from their families. Many of them saw their 
houses being burned immediately behind them.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Robinson was also taken by the army to the central Serbian city  
of Nis, where NATO cluster bombs have killed several people. She 
arrived in Nis on Wednesday shortly after an attack and saw the 
damage as well as unexploded cluster bombs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
