<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ripken Returns From First DL Stint </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ARLINGTON, Texas (AP) -- Baseball's iron man is back.  
</P>
<P>
	Cal Ripken Jr. came off the first disabled list stint of his  
19-year career Thursday and proclaimed himself in better shape 
physically and mentally. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was a strange experience being away,'' Ripken said.  
</P>
<P>
	Ripken went 1-for-4 with an RBI single and a run scored but it  
wasn't nearly enough as the Baltimore Orioles lost to the Texas 
Rangers 15-7. In the field, he failed a stop a hard-hit grounder 
between his legs for his sixth error this season. 
</P>
<P>
	Ripken, 38, said before the game that there's no trace of the  
nerve irritation in his lower back that sidelined him April 18. 
</P>
<P>
	Ripken was eligible to return May 3, but he needed an extra 10  
days. He spent the first part of this week on a rehabilitation 
assignment at the team's extended spring training camp in Sarasota, 
Fla., getting the rust off and proving to himself that the pain was 
gone. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's not in my mind,'' Ripken said. ``I think about it when I  
take a plane trip, but that's because I have to sit in one 
position. When I'm actually going through reactions, doing 
something fast speed -- sliding into a base, backhand a ball or dive 
for a ball -- I don't think about it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Instead, Ripken has been thinking a lot about his father, who  
died late in spring training. Ripken said he intentionally stayed 
away from the team and the stadium to dwell on his loss. 
</P>
<P>
	``I needed time and space,'' he said. ``I didn't have the  
benefit at the time. Maybe the injury was a blessing in disguise. 
It gave me an opportunity, actually, to think about things, to 
grieve.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It also gave him a chance to better appreciate his amazing  
streak of 2,632 consecutive games from May 1982, his rookie year, 
through last September, when he voluntarily sat down. 
</P>
<P>
	``Sometimes I took for granted the ability to go out there and  
play all the time,'' Ripken said. ``Now, having had to take some 
time off, I certainly appreciate how lucky I was and how much I 
really do enjoy being out there.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ripken said being in the locker room again felt like the first  
day of spring training. He called the game ``a second opening 
day.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Guys are a kind of acting a little goofy and running around,''  
he said. ``There's a whole bunch more energy than you normally 
have.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ripken said he noticed that Wayne Gretzky and John Elway retired  
while he was out, but he shot down any talk that he's considering 
joining them -- at least, not immediately. 
</P>
<P>
	``No, I haven't thought about retirement, necessarily. I haven't  
gotten to that point yet,'' Ripken said. ``I'd love to talk to all 
those guys (about) how they came upon reaching their decision. I 
only know my own situation and how I feel about myself. 
</P>
<P>
	``Because of the injury, it does cast some uncertainty on my  
future. That could be a consideration. But, simply, I have to go 
out there with a good body and a good mind and see how it all works 
out and I'll know one way or another.'' 
</P>
<P>
	During Ripken's recent absence, Rafael Palmeiro surpassed him in  
games played this decade. 
</P>
<P>
	Palmerio, Ripken's teammate the last five seasons, appeared in  
his 1,401st game of the 1990s on Thursday. It was Ripken's 1,398th. 
</P>
<P>
	``Until I saw that on TV the other day, I had no idea,''  
Palmeiro said. ``I'm glad he's back. To me, it doesn't seem right 
for him to be on the DL.'' 
</P>
<P>
	First baseman Calvin Pickering, who didn't have a hit in seven  
at-bats over seven games, was sent down to Triple-A Rochester to 
make room for Ripken. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
