<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Farm State Democrats Criticize GOP </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Farm state Democrats criticized Republicans on  
Thursday for rejecting $5.3 billion in emergency aid for farmers 
and pledged to continue to push the issue. 
</P>
<P>
	Sen. Tom Harkin, D-Iowa, and Sen. Byron Dorgan, D-N.D., tried to  
get the money included in a supplemental spending bill being worked 
out by House and Senate budget negotiators. But when put to a vote 
late Wednesday night, the farm aid proposal, which started as a 
$4.3 billion deal but increased as lawmakers added riders, got a 
14-14 tie vote. One Republican, Sen. Conrad Burns, R-Mont., voted 
with all the Democrats in favor of the package. 
</P>
<P>
	Instead, the committee agreed to $566 million for farmers, which  
includes money to replenish the shrinking coffers that supply farm 
loans. The proposal will still have to get past both floors of 
Congress. 
</P>
<P>
	Democrats say the money isn't nearly enough, particularly when  
budget planners agreed to $11.6 billion for the air assault on 
Yugoslavia and to boost defense spending. President Clinton had 
only requested $6 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	Congress is telling farmers ``you better get down and paint your  
tractors in camouflage,'' said Sen. Dick Durbin, D-Ill. ``What does 
it take to get the attention of the Republican leadership around 
here?'' 
</P>
<P>
	``For them, on defense, the sky is the limit,'' said Dorgan.  
</P>
<P>
	Republicans said the agreement helped farmers.  
</P>
<P>
	``The Democrats are grandstanding,'' said Sen. Thad Cochran,  
R-Miss., chairman of the Agriculture Committee's appropriations 
panel, adding that the GOP leaders are open to passing more money 
later this year if the administration requests it. ``We gave the 
administration everything they asked for and more.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Selma Sierra, spokeswoman for Rep. Joe Skeen, R-N.M., said  
Clinton's request to replenish the farm loan funds was $152 
million, so Republicans increased it fivefold. ``If they think we 
don't care about farmers, then Democrats must be heartless,'' 
Sierra said. 
</P>
<P>
	Congress last year passed a $6 billion emergency package for  
farmers as prices plummeted. With low prices expected to continue 
much of this year, many lawmakers have pushed for early emergency 
funds to ease the pain. 
</P>
<P>
	The farm money includes the money for loans as well as $20  
million in farmworker aid; $70 million in livestock assistance and 
$145 million to help pork producers, who have been suffering from 
their lowest prices in 40 years. 
</P>
<P>
	One more Republican vote ``would have made all the difference in  
the world,'' Harkin said. ``We helped everybody but farmers.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
