<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-13 15:31:54 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Columnist Meg Greenfield Dies at 68 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A believer in Washington's humanity but a  
sharp critic of its poison and puffery, Meg Greenfield shaped The 
Washington Post's editorial voice for three decades. She died 
Thursday of cancer at age 68. 
</P>
<P>
	A Pulitzer Prize-winning editor, editorial writer and Newsweek  
columnist, Greenfield provided commentary on the great turmoil and 
scandals of her time, all the while mindful that the fallen, or the 
larger than life, were flesh and blood. 
</P>
<P>
	``I am, to this day, even given the uncountable number of scuzzy  
public betrayals and lies, much more comfortable when a scoundrel 
eludes us or we miss the scent, than when we are pursuing someone 
who shouldn't be charged,'' she wrote in a Newsweek column last 
November. 
</P>
<P>
	Much earlier, she had advanced the view that Washington,  
contrary to widespread belief, ``does not exclude everything 
human.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Greenfield, who had lung cancer, died at her Washington home.  
</P>
<P>
	``She shaped the editorial page of the Post in a highly personal  
way -- independent and strong but respectful of others' opinions,'' 
said publisher Donald E. Graham. ``On the ethics of our business 
she was the Supreme Court, as far as I was concerned.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A native of Seattle, she joined the Post in 1968 after 11 years  
with the old Reporter magazine and became deputy editor of the 
editorial page two years later. In 1979 she became editor of the 
page, a position she held until her death. 
</P>
<P>
	She wrote columns for Newsweek since 1974 in a recognizably  
textured, sometimes elaborate style that reflected a distrust of 
easy answers. 
</P>
<P>
	``She called on those of us who work in government to pursue  
far-sighted public policy and bipartisan solutions,'' President 
Clinton. ``Her voice of eloquence and reason will be sorely 
missed.'' He said she ``perfected the art of the newspaper 
column.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Post, for all its groundbreaking coverage of Watergate,  
editorialized in favor of President Nixon's pardon -- ``to the 
disgust of most of our friends,'' she said -- when she was deputy 
chief of the page. 
</P>
<P>
	She won a 1978 Pulitzer for writing editorials, some of which  
spoke out in defense of outgoing President Ford and renounced some 
of the paper's earlier criticisms of him. ``How odd that so few of 
us have been willing to acknowledge that decency in the White House 
can be regarded as a luxury or a bonus or a fringe benefit only at 
our peril,'' she wrote. ``It is central.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Yet she could be tough on ``the media, the social twits, the  
congressmen and their multitudinous hatcheries of assistants, the 
lawyers and (let us never forget) the principals'' -- as she 
described the cast of characters involved in some of the ``pathetic 
little squalors'' of the Clinton impeachment affair. 
</P>
<P>
	Greenfield was ``uninfluenced by trends or molds,'' said  
Katharine Graham, former publisher of the paper and a longtime 
friend. 
</P>
<P>
	A slight but commanding woman at 5-foot-1, she saw a ``little  
Mussolini in every editorial writer.'' But she questioned how 
powerful that role really was. 
</P>
<P>
	``What we tend to notice here is the great number of wise  
suggestions we make that are rejected at the polls, and in the 
agencies, and in the U.S. Congress, and in the District school 
board, and if there's someplace I've left out, remind me,'' she 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Post said that in 1982, fed up with Washington's vast public  
relations industry, she tried to stop the editorial staff from 
accepting any manuscript or interview request that came from a 
``flack firm,'' but the rule proved impractical and lapsed. 
</P>
<P>
	Greenfield's father ran an antiques business and her mother died  
when she was 12. She graduated from Smith College in 1952, spent a 
year at Cambridge University studying poet William Blake on a 
Fulbright scholarship and worked in the 1956 presidential election 
as New York research director for Democratic candidate Adlai 
Stevenson. 
</P>
<P>
	Funeral arrangements were pending.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990513.0293 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-13 22:22:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Boeing To Cut Up to 7,000 Jobs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ST. LOUIS (AP) -- Flagging sales of Boeing Co.'s premier F-15  
fighter have forced the elimination of up to 7,000 jobs at the 
company's massive manufacturing plant here and triggered a 
reorganization meant to strengthen the aerospace company in the 
future. 
</P>
<P>
	Officials said the layoffs represent roughly 35 percent of the  
plant's work force. Most of the cuts, expected to be completed by 
mid-2001, will come from the ranks of management, but labor 
officials say 1,600 to 1,800 union members will also lose their 
jobs. 
</P>
<P>
	Boeing has previously announced that it planned to eliminate  
anywhere from 43,000 to 53,000 jobs in coming years. The company 
said that Thursday's announcement pushes its estimate to the higher 
end of that range. 
</P>
<P>
	Back in July of 1998, Boeing predicted that its total work force  
of 238,000 would be reduced to roughly 185,000 to 195,000. Boeing 
currently employs 219,000. 
</P>
<P>
	Boeing has blamed most of its job cuts up until now on reduced  
demand from Asian customers who were suffering from that region's 
prolonged recession. Most of the previous cuts came in the Puget 
Sound area in Washington. 
</P>
<P>
	Boeing suffered another blow last month when the Greek  
government signed a contract to buy Lockheed Martin's F-16. The 
F-15 costs about $55 million each, while the F-16, an advanced 
fighter, goes for about $30 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Two weeks after Boeing lost the $3.5 billion sale to Greece, the  
Israeli government postponed a $2.5 billion F-15 purchase. 
</P>
<P>
	The Greek order alone could have kept the Boeing line open two  
more years. 
</P>
<P>
	``Once we completed an assessment of our business environment  
based on the April 30 decision by the government of Greece, we 
decided to let our team and the community know as soon as possible 
what to expect for the foreseeable future,'' said Jerry Daniels, 
Boeing vice president, general manager and St. Louis site director. 
</P>
<P>
	``We remain committed to St. Louis and are taking these steps to  
ensure our competitiveness on our existing work, including a 
multiyear contract on C-17 and a proposed multiyear buy of the 
FA-18EF and on future programs, such as the joint strike fighter.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Employees gathered at a nearby restaurant to celebrate the  
retirement of three Boeing managers seemed to accept the layoffs as 
inevitable in light of the recent sales losses. 
</P>
<P>
	``After losing the (Greek) contract, that would be the amount I  
think you'd expect,'' said Stacey Ward, who has worked in the 
company's training department for four years. 
</P>
<P>
	``But the key to this whole thing is that we have to change the  
way we do business. We have to become leaner and better streamline 
our operations.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Layoffs of between 800 and 900 St. Louis workers were announced  
earlier. About 300 of those already have been given notice, 
officials said. About 300 to 400 workers are to be let go every 
month until the reduction is complete. 
</P>
<P>
	Daniels said displaced St. Louis employees may find work at  
other Boeing sites. 
</P>
<P>
	Union leaders said that when anticipated sales to Greece and  
Israel fell through recently, they expected layoffs. But they were 
shocked by the size of the reduction in force. 
</P>
<P>
	``We knew there would be layoffs, but not of this magnitude,''  
said Rick Smith, president of District 837 of the International 
Association of Machinists &AMP; Aerospace Workers. ``When they lost the 
sales, we all expected something to happen, but not this quickly 
and not this big. These are all good, relatively high-paying jobs. 
It's not going to be pretty.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Missouri lawmakers said loss of the F-15, first built here in  
1972, jeopardizes U.S. national security. 
</P>
<P>
	``The F-15 is the very best fighter airplane in the world,''  
said Sen. John Ashcroft. ``If we allow the line to go down where we 
don't have the next generation available to us, we put U.S. 
security at risk,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	More than 1,500 F-15s have been delivered to the U.S. Air Force,  
Israel, Saudi Arabia and Japan. Current orders for the F-15 will be 
completed by early 2000. 
</P>
<P>
	Peter Jacobs, a Boeing analyst at Ragen Mackenzie Inc. in  
Seattle, said the production declines in St. Louis will hurt 
Boeing's revenue in 2000 and 2001, but the company may also face a 
longer term problem rehiring skilled workers after that. 
</P>
<P>
	Boeing will need these workers as it ramps up production of the  
F-18 Super Hornet, a new carrier-based fighter which is being built 
in St. Louis, Jacobs said. 
</P>
<P>
	``One of the challenges Boeing will now face is getting the  
skilled work force to come back when they're needed, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Jacobs added that the F-15s are at the tail end of their  
delivery cycle. 
</P>
<P>
	``Even if Boeing would have won the order from Greece and got  
the full order from Israel, it would probably have still resulted 
in job reductions in St. Louis.'' 
</P>
<P>
	There was a bit of good news for Boeing Thursday.  
</P>
<P>
	Boeing said it agreed to protect more than 3,000 Puget Sound  
area maintenance and facilities jobs that had been scheduled for 
elimination. The company said it saved those jobs after union 
workers agreed to productivity improvements. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990513.0294 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-13 22:41:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Children Must Be Careful in Sun </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Dr. Roger Ceilley sighed as he watched  
children at a Des Moines day-care center frolic under the noon sun. 
</P>
<P>
	Noon is not a very safe time to be outdoors. Worse, ``there's  
not a speck of shade in the entire area.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A child born this year has a one in five chance of developing  
skin cancer later in life, mostly from sun exposure, according to 
the American Academy of Dermatology. 
</P>
<P>
	Children get 80 percent of their lifetime sun by age 18, and  
even a few bad sunburns during childhood can increase their risk of 
melanoma, the deadliest skin cancer. 
</P>
<P>
	Ceilley, a University of Iowa dermatologist, is not a grump who  
thinks children should stay indoors. ``I lived outdoors when I was 
a kid,'' he says. 
</P>
<P>
	But consider when American children play most outside: during  
recess at school, anywhere from 10 a.m. to 3 p.m. -- the hours when 
the sun's ultraviolet rays are strongest. In fact, experts 
recommend seeking shade until after 4 p.m. 
</P>
<P>
	How many kids don protective hats, sunscreen or sunglasses  
before racing out to the jungle gym? And how many playgrounds have 
lots of shady trees? 
</P>
<P>
	So the academy's National Coalition on Sun Safety teamed up with  
the safer-playground group KaBoom to open the nation's first 
specially designed ``sun-safe playground'' on New York's Staten 
Island last month. 
</P>
<P>
	A massive tarpaulin-like structure shields two-thirds of the  
play area from ultraviolet rays. Benches for parents or 
baby-sitters have little roofs, too. 
</P>
<P>
	It's part of the coalition's effort to teach Americans to better  
protect their kids, and themselves, when they're in the sun. 
</P>
<P>
	The snazzy-looking playground is generating interest from  
neighboring communities. Coalition co-chairman Ceilley hopes it 
will become a nationwide model, illustrating that small steps like 
utilizing shade could help save lives. 
</P>
<P>
	More than 1 million Americans will be diagnosed with some form  
of skin cancer this year. Someone dies of it every hour. 
</P>
<P>
	Most skin cancers are basal cell or squamous cell types, which  
often appear as pale, waxlike, pearly nodules or red, scaly 
patches. The deadliest form, melanoma, often starts as a small 
mole-like growth that grows larger, has ragged or irregular edges, 
and has mixed shadings of brown or black. Melanoma cases are 
increasing by 3 percent a year. 
</P>
<P>
	Caught early, most skin cancer is curable. But melanoma spreads  
quickly, and even basal and squamous cell cancer can dramatically 
disfigure the skin if the malignancies grow large before removal. 
So doctors urge adults to check their skin monthly, and have a 
dermatologist check any suspicious spot promptly. 
</P>
<P>
	But prevention is best, and that explains the focus on children.  
</P>
<P>
	``Sun safety is just like car safety,'' Ceilley says. ``It's  
something you need to think about every day,'' not just when the 
family is headed for the beach. 
</P>
<P>
	For both children and adults, choose a sunscreen that has at  
least a sun protection factor, or SPF, of 15. Make sure it protects 
against both types of ultraviolet rays, UVB and UVA. Not all 
sunscreens do. 
</P>
<P>
	If children are reluctant, new kid-friendly color-changing  
brands may entice them. 
</P>
<P>
	But don't think that wearing sunscreen means you can bake in the  
noon sun. Recent studies have confused the public by finding that 
skin cancer has risen even as sunscreen use has. Many scientists 
believe the problem is that too many people think slathering on 
lotion means they can stay in intense sun longer. 
</P>
<P>
	Sunscreens do reduce the risk of sunburn, which is important and  
means everyone should use them, experts say. Tanning, they note, is 
a sign of sun damage. But don't rely on sunscreen exclusively -- you 
must still avoid midday exposure and wear protective clothing. 
</P>
<P>
	Find a fun hat with a brim for children and adults, advises  
Ceilley. He notes that Australia, where skin cancer is so epidemic 
that sun safety is a major government effort, requires hats and 
sunscreen for school recess. 
</P>
<P>
	Wear sunglasses, because the sun also causes cataracts.  
</P>
<P>
	As for adults, ``it's never too late'' to start being sun-savvy.  
``The skin does have an amazing ability to recover.'' 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	EDITOR'S NOTE -- Lauran Neergaard covers health and medical  
issues for The Associated Press in Washington. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
