<HEADLINE> U.S. 5, Netherlands 0 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MILWAUKEE (AP) -- Tiffeny Milbrett scored one goal and assisted  
on three others, leading the U.S. women's national soccer team to a 
5-0 victory over the Netherlands on Thursday night. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was an awesome performance. Not only did she score the  
first goal, but her ability to pass and find the lanes in traffic 
was very, very impressive,'' U.S. coach Tony DiCicco said. 
</P>
<P>
	Mia Hamm added the 106th goal of her international career in the  
second half, putting her in second place among career scorers, one 
goal behind the record held by Elisabetta Vignotto of Italy. 
</P>
<P>
	Christie Pearce made a run down the left side and passed across  
to Hamm, who made a sliding deflection into the net. 
</P>
<P>
	``She didn't have a lot of room to find me, and she did, and I  
missed it a little bit, but because the ball was hit so hard, all I 
had to do was kind of redirect it,'' Hamm said. 
</P>
<P>
	The United States dominated the first half, holding the  
Netherlands without a shot. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite the dominance, the lead was only 1-0 at halftime on  
Milbrett's first goal. Julie Foudy made a run to the end line and 
centered the ball, and Milbrett knocked it home for her 56th career 
goal. 
</P>
<P>
	Goalkeeper Marleen Wissink kept the Netherlands in the game in  
the opening half, stopping Brandi Chastain's penalty kick in the 
fourth minute and making a diving save on Chastain in the 18th 
minute. 
</P>
<P>
	The United States missed two other chances when Chastain put  
Hamm's corner kick over the crossbar, and again when Hamm hit the 
post. 
</P>
<P>
	In the second half, Milbrett took a pass from Chastain in the  
60th minute, made a move on a defender and came in on a breakaway. 
She faked Wissink to the ground and passed to a wide-open Cindy 
Parlow, who tapped it in. 
</P>
<P>
	Milbrett then set up Kristine Lilly six minutes later and capped  
off her night by setting up Shannon MacMillan. 
</P>
<P>
	``I just want to go out there and play every game and do what I  
can,'' Milbrett said. ``If that means goals and assists, great. If 
that means helping out my team however else I can, that's how it 
goes.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The teams are touring in advance of the World Cup, to be held in  
the United States from June 19-July 10. The United States, 5-1 on 
its tour, plays the Netherlands again Sunday in Chicago. 
</P>
</TEXT>
