<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 10 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	China, U.S. Agree To Talk  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton and Chinese President Jiang  
Zemin have agreed to talk, a sign that the tensions may be easing 
with China over NATO's bombing of the Chinese Embassy in Belgrade. 
Jiang had avoided talking to Clinton since the bombing Saturday, 
which killed three people. His readiness to talk was conveyed by 
Chinese Ambassador Li Zhaoxing, who took a condolence book to the 
White House for Clinton to sign. ``He indicated a willingness to 
talk, and we're setting up the call,'' said National Security 
Council spokesman David Leavy. It was unclear whether the call 
could be arranged before tomorrow. 

</P>
<P>
	Apaches Ready For Combat  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The U.S. Apache helicopters are ready for  
combat in Yugoslavia, but NATO has yet to ask President Clinton for 
the official go-ahead to use them. The question of when -- and even 
if -- the Apaches will go into action against Serb forces in Kosovo 
has been a topic of speculation for weeks, in large part because 
the low-flying helicopters are vulnerable to anti-aircraft fire. 
Their use would raise the risk of American battlefield casualties. 

</P>
<P>
	GOP Reconsidering Gun Control  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Under pressure, Senate Republicans retreated  
today on gun control. They called for fresh restrictions on sales 
at gun shows less than 24 hours after rejecting them despite public 
outrage over last month's high school shootings in Colorado. But 
Democrats denounced the new offer, saying it contained numerous 
loopholes. ``It's the most Swiss-cheesy bill I've ever seen,'' said 
Sen. Charles Schumer, D-N.Y. 

</P>
<P>
	Bus Driver Had Been Fired for Drugs  
</P>
<P>
	NEW ORLEANS (AP) -- The driver of a charter bus that crashed and  
killed 22 people was fired from bus companies in 1996 and 1989 
after testing positive for marijuana four times, authorities said 
today. A federal investigator also confirmed a report that Frank 
Bedell, 46, tested positive for marijuana when he was hospitalized 
Sunday after the bus veered off a highway and plunged into an 
embankment. 

</P>
<P>
	Rwanda Says Congo Is Backing Hutus  
</P>
<P>
	KIGALI, Rwanda (AP) -- Rwanda insisted today that its troops will  
remain in Congo, accusing the central African country of preparing 
rebels to overthrow the Rwandan government. Rwanda has troops in 
neighboring Congo to support rebels fighting against the government 
of Congolese President Laurent Kabila. After nine months of 
fighting, the rebels have swept through the eastern half of Congo. 
The Hutu militiamen fled Rwanda into neighboring Congo in July 1994 
after the Tutsi-led Rwandan Patriotic Front won power and ended the 
state-sponsored massacres of at least 500,000 minority Tutsis and 
politically moderate Hutus, earlier that year. 

</P>
<P>
	EPA Says Pollution Up After Decline  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The amount of toxic chemicals released into  
the environment by industrial plants increased by 2.2 percent in 
1997, ending years of steady decline, the Environmental Protection 
Agency said today. The increase in total releases of 644 toxic 
chemicals by 21,490 facilities was attributed largely to plants 
sending more metal wastes to landfills and other disposal sites, 
instead of to recycling centers. That was because in 1997, the year 
the latest data covered, metal recycling prices increased, 
officials said. Before 1997, releases had been trending down each 
year since the reporting began in 1988, although companies are 
generating more waste during production. 

</P>
<P>
	Ventura Writes Tell-All Biography  
</P>
<P>
	ST. PAUL, Minn. (AP) -- In his new autobiography, Gov. Jesse  
``The Body'' Ventura brags about losing his virginity at 16 to win 
a bet, tells of visiting prostitutes in Nevada, admits he used 
marijuana and steroids and confides he doesn't wear underwear. 
Published by Random House/Villard, ``I Ain't Got Time to Bleed: 
Re-working the Body Politic From the Bottom Up'' is available 
online and hits stores later this month. Some lawmakers, though, 
say the former pro wrestler's $19.95 tell-all is a tell-too-much. 

</P>
<P>
	Tokyo Stocks Higher  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Japanese stocks were up Friday after yet another  
record close on Wall Street. The Nikkei rose 73.86 points to 
16,925.11. On Thursday, the index lost 96.11 points. In New York, 
the Dow rose 106.82 points to close at a record of 11,107.19 
Thursday, while the Nasdaq closed at 2,582.00, down 24.54. 

</P>
<P>
	76ers Beat Magic  
</P>
<P>
	PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- Allen Iverson scored 33 points and had 10  
steals as Philadelphia beat Orlando 97-85 tonight in the 76ers' 
first home playoff game in eight years. The 76ers more than matched 
the Magic's physical play, thoroughly outmuscling and demoralizing 
them to take a 2-1 lead in the best-of-5 series. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by BRADLEY BROOKS  
</P>
