<HEADLINE> Judge Awards $5M in HIV Case </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	YORK, S.C. (AP) -- A judge has ordered a man to pay his former  
girlfriend $5 million for infecting her with the AIDS virus -- part 
of what her attorney described as a grudge against women. 
</P>
<P>
	Judge Buford Greer awarded $1 million in actual damages and $4  
million in punitive damages to the woman Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The woman, identified in court papers as Jane Doe, received a  
verdict in her favor in November after her former boyfriend failed 
to show up to defend himself. The man, identified only as John Doe, 
did not appear for the damages hearing either. 
</P>
<P>
	``I hope this verdict sends a message to people that you can't  
do this,'' said the woman's lawyer, Randall Hood. ``If you are 
HIV-positive, it is your duty to inform your partner.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The lawsuit contends the man never told the woman he had HIV --  
the virus that causes AIDS -- when they began dating five years ago. 
</P>
<P>
	Hood said the woman had a long-term, monogamous relationship  
with the man, but the man had a grudge against women and decided to 
infect her. 
</P>
