<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-13 22:11:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> SEC Targets Online Investment Fraud </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The catchy staccato strains of the ``Mission  
Impossible'' theme fill the darkened ballroom of the Capital 
Hilton. Officials of the Securities and Exchange Commission are 
showing a flashy video on Internet topics at a conference, and 
they've gotten to the part dealing with the agency's enforcement 
efforts. 
</P>
<P>
	Is policing the Internet against burgeoning investment fraud an  
impossible mission for the SEC? No, the regulators say, but it's 
getting very difficult. 
</P>
<P>
	As it seeks to bolster its ability to fight online fraud, the  
SEC could be getting help from Congress, where two Republican 
senators are proposing an increase in its budget and greater leeway 
in the kind of enforcement actions it can take. 
</P>
<P>
	Even if the SEC gets the help the lawmakers are offering,  
however, the agency's crime-fighting powers will continue to be 
hampered in several ways. 
</P>
<P>
	The SEC, an independent federal agency, can file only civil  
lawsuits against suspected violators. Unlike the Justice 
Department, it cannot put anyone in jail. And unlike state 
securities regulators, SEC fraud-fighters don't have the legal 
authority to go undercover online, although they can and do conduct 
Internet surveillance. 
</P>
<P>
	There are other limits: The market watchdog agency can bar  
brokers who have violated the law from the brokerage industry, but 
not from other financial activities such as promoting stocks. And 
while it has aggressively gone after people and companies engaging 
in Internet fraud with civil fines and court orders compelling them 
to refrain from such activity, it doesn't have authority to shut 
down Web sites. 
</P>
<P>
	On top of that, enforcement attorneys and auditors have been  
leaving the SEC at a worrisome pace for lucrative jobs in private 
practice. 
</P>
<P>
	Against this background, the SEC and state regulators are  
battling a new form of fraud that is proliferating in Internet junk 
mail, online newsletters, electronic ``chat rooms'' and Web sites. 
</P>
<P>
	Because the Internet is everywhere, unscrupulous stock promoters  
anywhere in the world can cloak themselves in anonymity and lure 
investors across the country, who have lost millions in such 
schemes in recent years. No longer do promoters have to give 
customers the hard sell over the telephone in unsolicited calls. 
</P>
<P>
	But securities regulators still operate under the old rule book.  
</P>
<P>
	``There is a certain breed of bottom-feeders who are simply not  
deterred by the prospect of civil injunctions or even stiff 
monetary penalties,'' SEC Enforcement Director Richard Walker said 
recently. ``There is no other ... deterrence for them than the 
threat of a life behind bars.'' 
</P>
<P>
	To create that deterrent, the SEC has been working closely with  
criminal prosecutors from the Justice Department and the offices of 
state attorneys general and local district attorneys. 
</P>
<P>
	The agency has nearly doubled the size of its ``Cyberforce''  
team, which prowls the Internet on the lookout for fraud, to 200 
people. 
</P>
<P>
	Sen. Judd Gregg, R-N.H., chairman of a Senate Appropriations  
subcommittee, recently proposed increasing the SEC's budget, now at 
$337.4 million, by $5.5 million next year to fight Internet fraud. 
That would bring the agency's funding to the level requested by the 
Clinton administration and the SEC. 
</P>
<P>
	Beyond manpower and money, the SEC is also looking to expand its  
enforcement reach. 
</P>
<P>
	Walker and other officials laid out the scope of Internet  
investment fraud at recent hearings by a Senate investigative 
subcommittee. 
</P>
<P>
	Walker acknowledged that with 850 attorneys and other  
enforcement employees nationwide to pursue all types of financial 
fraud, including the online variety, ``We are certainly challenged, 
if not strained.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Soon after the hearings, Sen. Susan Collins, R-Maine, the  
subcommittee's chairwoman, proposed legislation that would: 
</P>
<P>
	--Give the SEC legal authority to ban brokers who violate the law  
not just from the brokerage industry but also from promoting 
stocks. A significant amount of Internet fraud has come from 
promoters touting high-risk, small-company stocks without 
disclosing that they were paid to do so. 
</P>
<P>
	--Allow the SEC to bring ``follow-up'' cases based on enforcement  
actions by state securities regulators. 
</P>
<P>
	The proposals are ``tools that would be very valuable for the  
SEC to have,'' said Bradley Skolnik, Indiana's securities 
commissioner and president-elect of the North American Securities 
Administrators Association. ``They are long overdue.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In its third nationwide ``sweep'' against Internet fraud, the  
SEC on Wednesday announced it had charged 18 people and eight 
companies with using the Web to sell bogus securities. 
</P>
<P>
	Online investment fraud also can take the form of stock-price  
manipulation schemes, deceptive stock touting, investment pyramid 
schemes and unlicensed brokering or advising on investments. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
