<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> 15 Hurt in Calif. Tour Bus Crash </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	KNIGHTS FERRY, Calif. (AP) -- A tour bus returning from Yosemite  
National Park may have been speeding when it plunged 70 feet off a 
highway and into a ravine, investigators said. 
</P>
<P>
	Fifteen of the 31 people aboard were hurt Wednesday, most with  
broken bones, cuts and bruises. None of the injuries was considered 
life threatening. 
</P>
<P>
	The bus, filled with Japanese tourists, was headed for San  
Francisco when it veered off the westbound lane of Highway 120 in 
Tuolumne County and dropped 70 feet down an embankment, officials 
said. The bus landed upright. 
</P>
<P>
	``Seventy feet is a long way, so it could have been a lot  
worse,'' said California Highway Patrol Office Matthew Radke. 
</P>
<P>
	One witness told investigators the bus was traveling 75 mph and  
passing traffic prior to the wreck. The speed limit in the area for 
buses and big rigs is 55 mph, the CHP said. 
</P>
<P>
	The bus was operated by Visit USA Tours of San Francisco. The  
company, reached by phone early this morning, declined to comment 
on the crash. 
</P>
<P>
	The accident occurred just three days after 22 people were  
killed when a charter bus on its way to a Mississippi casino 
careened off a New Orleans interstate. 
</P>
<P>
	On Wednesday, authorities said the driver of that bus, Frank  
Bedell, was rushed by ambulance to a hospital less than 12 hours 
before he reported for work. He was treated for severe dehydration 
and low blood pressure -- a condition that made him nearly pass out 
-- and released, officials said. 
</P>
<P>
	The next morning, the luxury bus filled with 42 mostly elderly  
passengers hurtled off Interstate 610 and slammed into an 
embankment in New Orleans' City Park. 
</P>
<P>
	Bedell, who has become the focus of the federal probe into the  
nation's most deadly crash in a decade, remains on a ventilator in 
critical condition and has been unable to speak with investigators. 
</P>
<P>
	National Transportation Safety Board investigators said Bedell's  
health is a key component of their investigation. 
</P>
<P>
	Bedell, 46, suffers from congestive heart failure and undergoes  
dialysis three times a week, conditions that state officials have 
said would be grounds for removing his commercial driver's license 
had they known about them. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
