<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Slain Police Officers Remembered </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) --Wearing buttons and T-shirts bearing the names  
of their loved ones, thousands of friends and families paid tribute 
Thursday night to the police officers who have died in the line of 
duty. 
</P>
<P>
	The crowds assembled within the walls of the marble National Law  
Enforcement Officers Memorial, where the names of 312 police 
officers were added to the 15,000 already engraved there. Among 
those commemorated were the two U.S. Capitol police officers slain 
by a gunman in July. 
</P>
<P>
	Attorney General Janet Reno called the deaths of those two  
officers -- Jacob J. Chestnut and John Gibson -- a powerful wake-up 
call for the nation to the kinds of dangers officers at every level 
and all across the country face daily. 
</P>
<P>
	``The lives led by the individuals of our law enforcement  
community are not easy,'' Reno said. She said most people in other 
professions cannot imagine what it is like to go to work with the 
fear of being killed in the line of duty. 
</P>
<P>
	Although the crime rate has fallen, Reno said the nation cannot  
forget the lives lost in the effort. 
</P>
<P>
	``America tends to be complacent when crime goes down,'' she  
said. But to honor the memory of the officers, she promised, ``We 
will continue our efforts and together ultimately eliminate the 
culture of violence in our nation.'' 
</P>
<P>
	To that end, Reno called for steps such as background checks for  
gun buyers to limit the weapons that end up in the hands of 
criminals. She also urged families and communities to reach out to 
children, teaching them the difference between television and 
reality. Police especially can be powerful mentors for young 
adults, she added. 
</P>
<P>
	Friends, families and colleagues holding candles for the vigil  
illuminated the memorial as the outside lights dimmed. Many wore 
T-shirts and badges honoring loved ones. The slate-colored memorial 
-- just blocks from Washington's district and federal courthouses -- 
was adorned with roses, wreaths and pictures beside the names of 
the slain officers. 
</P>
<P>
	For Evette Wimberly, the event was a reminder of the many people  
who have shared her tragedy. Her husband, Kenneth Lee Wimberly Sr., 
32, a deputy sheriff in Gwinnett County, Ga., was working security 
at an apartment complex in late September when a man took 
Wimberly's gun and shot him dead. 
</P>
<P>
	``I just thank God it's not all in vain,'' said Mrs. Wimberly,  
accompanied by her children and wearing a button with her husband's 
image on it. ``It's helping me because I realize I am not alone.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Built in 1991, the memorial bears the names of nearly 15,000  
federal, state and local officers who have died in the line of 
duty. The 312 newly added names include 156 officers who died in 
1998 plus 156 officers whose names were discovered by memorial 
researchers over the past year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990513.0312 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-13 08:15:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
