<HEADLINE> NY Times News Services Chief Named </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Thomas K. Carley, director of business  
development for The New York Times News Services division, has been 
named president of the division, the company announced Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Carley will be responsible for the development and marketing of  
services that extend The Times's reach outside of the traditional 
newspaper, said Janet L. Robinson, president and general manager of 
The Times. 
</P>
<P>
	The News Services division includes The New York Times  
Syndication Sales Corporation, The New York Times News Service, 
TimesFax, Rights and Permissions, Photo Archives, Book Development, 
Large Type Weekly and Crossword Product Development. 
</P>
<P>
	``He is uniquely qualified to oversee this business venture as  
he brings a wealth of experience to this position,'' Ms. Robinson 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Carley, 42, joined The Times in 1987 as a circulation marketing  
analyst. Since then, he has served in a number of positions, 
including marketing sales planner, circulation promotion manager, 
database marketing director and sales promotion manager. 
</P>
<P>
	He became strategic planning project director at The Times in  
April 1997 and assumed his position as director of business 
development in the News Services division in March 1998. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
