<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Aged Storm Victims Face Recovery </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MOORE, Okla. (AP) -- Kathryn Ceyler, a widow in her 70s, hid in a  
closet when twisters shattered the home where she had lived for 29 
years. 
</P>
<P>
	Unhurt but shaken, she wanted no part of the crisis centers and  
food kitchens that sprang up around the destruction. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm an independent woman,'' she said.  
</P>
<P>
	A week later, however, she walked into the First Baptist Church  
in Moore for a hot meal and some groceries. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've never asked for any help in my life,'' she said, then  
admitted she needed some. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Ceyler is among the many elderly victims of last week's  
tornadoes who have been forced to start over at a time of life when 
they may be least prepared to do so. 
</P>
<P>
	While many can draw on past experience overcoming hardships,  
others in fragile health or on fixed incomes will struggle to 
recover from their losses, Red Cross clinical psychologist Joyce 
Libethe said Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	``If you're 70 or 80 years old you think, `How can I rebuild at  
this age?''' said Ms. Libethe, who has been counseling Oklahoma 
tornado survivors. 
</P>
<P>
	With support networks weakened as friends and relatives die and  
children move away, senior citizens often have only strangers to 
turn to, she said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Maybe they've gone 70 years taking care of themselves and now  
have to go out and ask for help and that's not easy for them,'' Ms. 
Libethe said. 
</P>
<P>
	The anger, shock and depression that usually follow such  
devastation can be overwhelming for anyone, but even more so for 
some elderly, she said. 
</P>
<P>
	``You see a lot of withdrawal,'' she said. ``You might find  
people thinking, `I've lived a long life, now this has happened. Do 
I have the energy to cope?''' 
</P>
<P>
	Charlene Robb, 63, of Moore has asked herself that question.  
Breathing problems, a ruptured disk and an illness that causes 
chronic pain already had sapped some of the joy from her retirement 
from hospital work. 
</P>
<P>
	Then the storm destroyed her 23-year-old home.  
</P>
<P>
	``There's too much work ahead of me to even think of relaxing,''  
she said Thursday as she ate lunch at a church food kitchen. ``I 
just keep pushing ahead.'' 
</P>
<P>
	J.D. Billings, 66, retired from landscaping work four years ago  
and spent much of his free time fishing until he was diagnosed with 
lung cancer. 
</P>
<P>
	He and his wife, Christine, drove out of their neighborhood 15  
minutes before the funnel clouds mowed through, chewing up the back 
of the Moore home where they had lived for 27 years. They had 
dropped their homeowner insurance just before the storm. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're just hopeful,'' Billings said as he talked with  
neighbors whose house was demolished. ``We'll try to rebuild.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Doris McLeod, 84, a widow for 17 years, was found between her  
toilet and bathtub, buried beneath 4 feet of debris and screaming 
for help after the twister moved through her Oklahoma City 
neighborhood. 
</P>
<P>
	She lost her wedding ring, a watch her husband had given her and  
all her clothes except one dress. Her son has helped her find 
another home. 
</P>
<P>
	``You just keep your faith in the Lord,'' she said, as she  
filled a cart with groceries at First Baptist. 
</P>
<P>
	Of the 44 people killed in the May 3 tornadoes, nine were 70 or  
older. The senior citizens who survived are being given special 
care at First Baptist. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're just trying to find the people who are too proud to get  
help,'' said Bud Parrish, First Baptist missions director. ``That's 
always their phrase: `I don't want to bother anyone.''' 
</P>
</TEXT>
