<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Jarrett Second in Winston Cup Race </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	RICHMOND, Va. (AP) -- Although Dale Jarrett has gone 14 straight  
races without winning, the number that matters most to him is 55 -- 
the amount of points by which he trails Jeff Burton in the Winston 
Cup standings. 
</P>
<P>
	And rather than fret about his lack of success, Jarrett views  
the Pontiac 400 on Saturday night at Richmond International Raceway 
as the next chance to prove he's ready to unseat two-time defending 
series champion Jeff Gordon. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've got a long time to go,'' Jarrett said. ``Jeff Gordon is  
still the man to beat, and that's not to take anything away from 
Mark Martin or Jeff Burton or anyone else. 
</P>
<P>
	``Out of the guys that are up there in the top five, he's the  
only one to win a Winston Cup championship.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Jarrett has spent the last three seasons as a contender. He  
finished second to Gordon in 1997, third behind Terry Labonte and 
runner-up Gordon in 1996 and third last year behind Gordon and 
Martin. 
</P>
<P>
	And Jarrett has been around long enough to know May is as  
important as November in the championship battle. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's something you have to concentrate on from the very  
beginning,'' he said of the title that rewards consistency more 
even than victories. 
</P>
<P>
	This weekend figures to challenge Jarrett and his Robert Yates  
Racing team as much as any because their luck hasn't been good at 
RIR of late. Last year in this race, he started fourth and finished 
second, nudged off the lead by eventual winner Labonte with two 
laps remaining. 
</P>
<P>
	Last fall, Jarrett started seventh in the Exide 400, but went  
backward. He limping home to a 16th-place finish that cost him 60 
points when Gordon and Martin ran second and third to Burton. 
</P>
<P>
	``The last race was one of the worst we've had at Richmond,''  
said Jarrett, who won at the track in the fall of 1997. ``We know 
what went wrong then, and we want to get back to those 
opportunities of having a chance to win.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bobby Labonte, right behind Jarrett in the points race, also  
hasn't won this season. But as one of three Pontiac drivers in the 
top nine in points, Labonte says he can't blame his manufacturer. 
Many have in the past. 
</P>
<P>
	Labonte's teammate with Joe Gibbs Racing, rookie Tony Stewart,  
is sixth in the points race, also without a victory. Ward Burton is 
ninth. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think people can argue that we don't win races because  
we're running a Pontiac,'' Labonte said. ``I feel like everything 
is pretty good between the makes right now ... probably the best 
it's been in a while.'' 
</P>
<P>
	John Andretti, 14th in points, posted the only Pontiac victory  
in the first 10 races, surging from far back to win last month in 
Martinsville. But Labonte thinks several others are capable of 
matching that feat. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think you can count out many Pontiac teams now,'' he  
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
