<HEADLINE> Bill Walton a Broadcaster in Demand </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	During his playing days, Bill Walton rarely spoke to reporters,  
or anyone else. 
</P>
<P>
	Just try to stop him now.  
</P>
<P>
	The Hall of Famer and NBC analyst, who missed more than nine of  
his 14 NBA seasons due to countless injuries, seems to be making up 
for lost time. 
</P>
<P>
	Walton worked two games for NBC last weekend and will do two  
more this weekend. In between, there are speaking engagements, 
charity events, a couple of hours a day with MSNBC's online site, 
and a temporary playoff gig with Turner Sports. 
</P>
<P>
	``One of the best things about broadcasting is that I'm able to  
work every day,'' Walton said. ``My legs weren't durable enough to 
play every day, but hopefully my voice will be.'' 
</P>
<P>
	There was a time when the 7-foot redhead avoided talking because  
of a severe stuttering problem. 
</P>
<P>
	Then, at age 29, he was taught how to speak properly by New York  
broadcaster Marty Glickman. 
</P>
<P>
	``I always tried to have a good working relationship with the  
media, but I was just so painfully shy and unable to speak,'' 
Walton said. 
</P>
<P>
	One reason Walton accepted Turner's offer to do playoff games  
was the possibility that he'd be able to work with Marv Albert 
again. 
</P>
<P>
	Albert and Walton were two-thirds of the NBC team that called  
the NBA Finals for three consecutive seasons from 1995-97, along 
with Matt Goukas. Thanks to the teamwork of NBC and Turner, they 
were reunited this week for the Bucks-Pacers series. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm really glad that NBC let Bill work at Turner,'' Albert  
said. ``It's very unusual that things like this happen, but the 
whole climate of TV has changed with people working for different 
networks.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Walton had his 30th operation nine years ago. He can't run -- and  
isn't even able to play his sons in a pickup game. But when he was 
doing the Indiana game last week, Pacers coach and former teammate 
Larry Bird somehow got the big man in motion. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was still trying to block his shot,'' Walton said. ``I never  
could even when I was healthy. I'm a very slow learner.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Walton has realized that you can't change the past and he's  
happy being able to stay around the game. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm having the time of my life and I'm doing all these games  
because this is a dream for me,'' he said. ``I am so amazed at how 
much broadcasting is like playing. The only difference is that I 
don't need an operation after every game.'' 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *THE BIG SHOW:* Finally, ``Sports Night'' creator Aaron Sorkin  
admitted the inspiration for his show: Keith Olbermann. 
</P>
<P>
	Sorkin, who also writes the episodes, just completed his first  
season of the show last week. Despite disappointing ratings, 
``Sports Night'' has been renewed by ABC for a second season. 
</P>
<P>
	Olbermann, the former ESPN ``SportsCenter'' host, interviewed  
Sorkin in the current issue of Esquire and was invited to be on the 
show -- even though he now works at Fox, rival of the Disney-owned 
ABC and ESPN. 
</P>
<P>
	Of course, the offer came only after Olbermann, who is always in  
search of more air time, pushed for an appearance on the series 
next season. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *TUBE BITS:* USA's French Open coverage will include live West  
Coast coverage and will show both women's semifinals for the first 
time. ... NBC has signed an extension that will keep the Breeders' 
Cup through 2001. ... The Houston Rockets have lost their last 14 
games on NBC. ... Former Brave and Dodger Brett Butler called his 
first of about 10 Atlanta games on Fox Sports Net this season. ... 
NBC's regular-season NBA ratings dropped 7 percent while Turner's 
improved 3 percent from last season. ... James Worthy made his 
Turner NBA playoff debut last week. ... Albert said there have been 
ongoing talks with Fox about joining its NFL team, but nothing has 
been finalized yet. 

</P>
</TEXT>
