<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Summers Expected To Succeed Rubin </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Larry Summers, the man President Clinton will  
nominate later today be the nation's next treasury secretary, has 
lately acted as the administration's fireman, assigned to contain 
economic brushfires as they've erupted around the world. 
</P>
<P>
	In January, he worked behind the scenes to coordinate rescue  
efforts with the International Monetary Fund when Brazil 
unexpectedly moved to devalue its currency. 
</P>
<P>
	A year earlier, when Indonesia balked at austerity measures  
imposed as part of an international bailout, Summers conducted a 
whirlwind six-day, seven-stop diplomatic mission through Asia. 
</P>
<P>
	Last summer, with the plummeting yen threatening to trigger  
another round of financial turmoil, he jetted to Tokyo to press for 
bolder countermeasures to Japan's recession. 
</P>
<P>
	As deputy secretary of the treasury, Summers, 44, also has put  
his stamp on a wide range of high-profile economic issues, from 
tobacco taxes to global warming to Social Security reform. 
</P>
<P>
	``He is a person of extraordinary talent and judgment,'' said  
Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan. 
</P>
<P>
	Now, Summers is poised to succeed his boss, Robert Rubin, and  
become the nation's 71st treasury secretary. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton was to announce the long-rumored change at a Rose Garden  
ceremony later today, the White House said. Rubin, a former Wall 
Street investment banker, has told the president he plans to return 
to private life, leaving Treasury at the end of July. 
</P>
<P>
	The outgoing secretary and his heir apparent, Summers, are a  
study in contrasts. 
</P>
<P>
	Rubin, former head of Goldman, Sachs &AMP; Co., is suave and slim  
and wears impeccably tailored suits. The portly Summers, who was a 
full professor at Harvard University at the tender age of 28, 
sometimes gives the impression of a preoccupied professor who has 
trouble keeping his shirttail tucked in. 
</P>
<P>
	Rubin appears relaxed and amiable. Summers, who almost always  
works with an open can of Diet Coke at hand, is intense and seldom 
smiles. Aides and colleagues remark on his propensity to call them 
at home after 11 p.m. and have complained of feeling belittled by 
his cutting remarks. Still, even his critics concede the acuity of 
his analysis -- his ability to ``think outside the box'' and ``add 
value'' to deliberations on almost any topic. 
</P>
<P>
	Summers was an also-ran in the Cabinet selection sweepstakes of  
1993, when Clinton chose the more personable Laura Tyson to head 
his Council of Economic Advisers. But he has learned to wait in the 
wings with good grace, to poke fun at his own image and permit 
glimpses of his less stodgy side. 
</P>
<P>
	Rubin and other top administration officials have worked  
assiduously to build Summers' public image, an important 
consideration for one of the few jobs in Washington where the wrong 
choice can throw financial markets into a tailspin. 
</P>
<P>
	Rubin, who once delighted in gently ribbing Summers in public,  
has lately shown more deference, asking ``Dr. Summers'' for his 
views. And Vice President Al Gore, has referred to Rubin and 
Summers as ``by far the best team our country has ever had at the 
Treasury Department.'' 
</P>
<P>
	On Capitol Hill, early Republican reaction to Summers' expected  
nomination, which the Senate must approve, was guarded. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think most people like Larry Summers. He's a likable fellow.  
But ... there's a lot of questions he'll have to answer to,'' said 
Senate Majority Whip Don Nickles, R-Okla. 
</P>
<P>
	Asked if Summers would face any problems being confirmed,  
Nickles said, ``I'm not going to say. Let's wait and see if he's 
nominated and we'll have to consider his nomination seriously.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
